INSERT INTO `mth_questions` VALUES (1,1,1,'freetext','ababa','<figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:862/485;\" src=\"https://live-production.wcms.abc-cdn.net.au/d3bea69d5a23fec74769121f1bd10c1a?impolicy=wcms_crop_resize&amp;cropH=1075&amp;cropW=1910&amp;xPos=10&amp;yPos=98&amp;width=862&amp;height=485\" width=\"862\" height=\"485\"></figure>','<figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:862/485;\" src=\"https://live-production.wcms.abc-cdn.net.au/d3bea69d5a23fec74769121f1bd10c1a?impolicy=wcms_crop_resize&amp;cropH=1075&amp;cropW=1910&amp;xPos=10&amp;yPos=98&amp;width=862&amp;height=485\" width=\"862\" height=\"485\"></figure><p>ddd</p>','2023-10-25 00:00:42',0,1,2,3,'','subtopic'),(4,1,2,'mcq',NULL,'Why is it known as Basic Algebra?',NULL,'2023-10-28 03:37:46',0,1,3,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(5,1,4,'mcq',NULL,'What is the length of a trigonometric triangle?',NULL,'2023-10-28 04:09:54',0,1,3,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(10,1,1,'mcq',NULL,'<p>What purpose does Boolean algebra solve?</p>','<p>well you know by now why</p>','2023-11-10 07:42:08',0,1,3,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(11,1,1,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Solve for \'x\' in the quadratic equation: 2x^2 - 7x + 3 = 0.</p>','<p>ok so this is because bla</p>','2023-11-10 09:59:49',0,1,3,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(12,1,7,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What is the domain of } y=\\ln (x-1) \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:<br>Since we cannot log a negative number or a zero, the expression inside the logarithm must be positive: $$ \\begin{gathered} x-1&gt;0 \\\\ \\therefore x&gt;1 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2023-11-11 02:20:03',0,1,1,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(13,1,7,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What is the range of } y=e^{x-1}+1 \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution: Since an exponential can never be negative or equal to 0 , the range of $e^u$ is always $&gt;0$ : $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; e^{x-1}&gt;0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore e^{x-1}+1&gt;1 \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the range is $y&gt;1$</p>','2023-11-11 02:39:52',0,1,1,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(14,1,7,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { Which of the following represents the domain of the function } f(x)=\\sqrt{3 x-2} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:<br>Since the expression inside a square root cannot be negative: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 3 x-2 \\geq 0 \\\\ &amp; 3 x \\geq 2 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x \\geq \\frac{2}{3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2023-11-11 04:50:34',0,1,1,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(15,1,7,'mcq',NULL,'<p>A function is defined by: $$<br>y=\\cos ^2 \\sqrt{x-2}<br>$$ Which of the following gives the domain and range of this function?</p>','<p>Solution:<br>In regard to domain, the expression inside a square root cannot be negative, meaning that: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; x-2 \\geq 0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x \\geq 2 \\end{aligned} $$ For a cosine function: $$ \\begin{gathered} -1 \\leq \\cos \\theta \\leq 1 \\\\ \\therefore 0 \\leq \\cos ^2 \\theta \\leq 1 \\end{gathered} $$ Since $y=\\cos ^2 \\sqrt{x-2}$, this therefore means that the range of the function is: $$ 0 \\leq y \\leq 1 $$</p>','2023-11-11 04:53:11',0,1,1,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(16,2,7,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { Which inequality defines the domain of the function } f(x)=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{x+5}} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since an expression inside a square root cannot be negative: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore x+5 \\geq 0 \\\\ &amp; x \\geq-5 \\end{aligned} $$ However, since the square root is on the denominator, it also cannot equal to 0 (we can\'t divide by 0 ) so we must change our domain to: $$ x&gt;-5 $$</p>','2023-11-11 07:32:50',0,1,1,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(17,1,1,NULL,NULL,'New Question',NULL,'2023-11-11 10:54:04',0,1,3,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(18,1,1,'mcq',NULL,'Fourth',NULL,'2023-11-11 10:56:01',0,1,3,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(19,1,12,'mcq',NULL,'Some Question',NULL,'2023-11-27 07:11:49',0,1,34,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(20,1,12,'mcq',NULL,'Some Question',NULL,'2023-11-27 07:17:59',0,1,3,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(21,1,12,'mcq',NULL,'Sids',NULL,'2023-11-27 07:19:03',0,1,NULL,0,'medium','subtopic'),(22,1,5,'mcq',NULL,'Some new',NULL,'2023-11-27 07:19:23',0,1,34,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(23,1,7,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What are the values of } x \\text { for which the function } f(x)=\\sqrt{x^2-5 x} \\text { is defined? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since the expression inside a square root cannot be a negative: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore x^2-5 x \\geq 0 \\\\ &amp; x(x-5) \\geq 0 \\end{aligned} $$ Imagining the parabola \\(x(x-5)\\) :</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:274/471;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f735c9c58b8fb96e877c00a0acc5c9d0.png\" width=\"274\" height=\"471\"></figure><p>Looking at when the parabola is above the \\(x\\)-axis, the domain \\(x(x-5) \\geq 0\\) is therefore: $$ x \\leq 0 \\text { OR } x \\geq 5 $$</p>','2023-11-28 10:40:11',0,1,1,0,'medium','subtopic'),(24,2,14,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { The best description of } x=y^2+4 \\text { is: } $$</p>','<p>Solution: Rearranging our equation to make \\(y\\) the subject: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; y^2=x-4 \\\\ &amp; y=\\pm \\sqrt{x-4} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, since one \\(x\\) value correlates to many \\(y\\) values, the relation is said to be \'One to Many\'</p>','2023-11-29 02:06:45',0,1,1,0,'easy','subtopic'),(28,1,14,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What type of relationship is represented by the graph shown below? } $$</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:425/372;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a6566022d79a2bf27d16cf8161e7ad8c.png\" width=\"425\" height=\"372\"></figure>','<p>Solution:<br>The graph passes the horizontal line test but fails the vertical line test, meaning that the relation is one to many.&nbsp;<br><br>This means that one \\(x\\) - value corresponds to many \\(y\\) - values, as can be seen in this relation.</p>','2023-11-29 06:03:40',0,1,1,0,'easy','subtopic'),(31,2,14,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What type of relation is shown below? } $$</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:714/551;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ef8ba8c3d4c8740d5750dc75ef593850.png\" width=\"714\" height=\"551\"></figure>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since multiple independent variables (left box) can be equal to multiple dependent variables (right box values), then this is therefore a many - to - many relation.<br><br>Essentially, since multiple arrows come out of the left box values AND the right box values have more than one arrow pointing at a value, then many left box values (independent variable) relate to many right box values (dependent variable). Hence, many - to - many.</p>','2023-11-29 07:17:45',0,1,1,0,'easy','subtopic'),(32,1,14,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What type of relation is shown below? } $$</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:324/240;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/714a091425e5d71dc4700744bba8d74f.png\" width=\"324\" height=\"240\"></figure>','<p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong><br>Since one independent variable (left box) can be equal to multiple dependent variables (right box values), then this is therefore a one - to - many relation.<br><br>Essentially, since multiple arrows come out of the left box values and the right box values only have one arrow pointing to each, then one left box value (independent variable) relate to many right box values (dependent variable). Hence, one - to - many.</p>','2023-11-29 21:09:31',0,1,1,0,'easy','subtopic'),(34,1,5,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Some Questionaaa</p>','<p>ansnds dsds</p>','2023-12-01 07:33:50',0,1,34,0,'medium','subtopic'),(35,1,18,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$<br>\\text { Solve } x^2-4 x-21=0<br>$$</p>','','2023-12-01 09:52:53',0,1,1,0,'easy','subtopic'),(36,1,14,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { The function } f(x) \\text { has the equation } x^2+(y-2)^2=4 \\text {, as shown below: } $$</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:375/283;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/3e68d43bebe08bc7c0e0d62bf8c4dab7.png\" width=\"375\" height=\"283\"></figure>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since the graph of the function fails BOTH the horizontal and vertical line test, it can therefore be considered many - to - many.</p>','2023-12-01 22:45:55',0,1,1,0,'easy','subtopic'),(37,1,14,'freetext',NULL,'<p>Classify the function $y=\\sin x$ as one - to - many, many - to - one, many - to many, or one - to - one.</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>The graph of $y=\\sin x$ fails the horizontal line test but passes the vertical line test.&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, it may be concluded that the function is many - to - one.</p>','2023-12-19 08:59:53',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(38,1,57,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What is the range of the function } y=-2 \\sqrt{25-x^2} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>When \\(x=0, y=-2 \\sqrt{25}=-2 \\times 5=-10\\), this is the minimum value<br><br>When \\(x=5, y=-2 \\sqrt{25-25}=0\\), this is the maximum value&nbsp;<br><br>Therefore, the range of the function will be: $$ -10 \\leq y \\leq 0 $$ In interval notation, this would be: $$ [-10,0] $$</p>','2023-12-19 22:32:14',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(39,1,57,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What is the range of } f(x)=4-x^2 ? $$</p>','<p>Solution: The function \\(f(x)\\) is a concave down parabola (since negative coefficient for \\(x^2\\) ) Therefore, its vertex is the maximum point \\(x\\) - coordinate of vertex is: $$ -\\frac{b}{2 a}=-\\frac{0}{2(-1)}=0 $$ When \\(x=0, y=4-0^2=4\\)&nbsp;</p><p>Students may also quickly sketch the graph if they wish:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:395/420;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/288c8a3162b2c065e3ccb9f82345d85f.png\" width=\"395\" height=\"420\"></figure><p>Therefore, maximum \\(y\\) - value is 4 , so the range of \\(f(x)\\) is \\(y \\leq 4\\) $$ \\therefore y \\in(-\\infty, 4] $$</p>','2023-12-19 22:36:26',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(40,1,57,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What is the domain of the function } f(x)=\\ln (2-x)+\\sqrt{5 x-3} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:<br><br>For \\(\\ln (2-x)\\), since the expression inside a logarithm cannot be equal to 0 or negative: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 2-x&gt;0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x&lt;2 \\end{aligned} $$ For \\(\\sqrt{5 x-3}\\), since we cannot square root a negative expression: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 5 x-3 \\geq 0 \\\\ &amp; 5 x \\geq 3 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x \\geq \\frac{3}{5} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, combining these two domains together: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\frac{3}{5} \\leq x&lt;2 \\\\ x \\in\\left[\\frac{3}{5}, 2\\right) \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2023-12-19 22:48:02',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(41,1,57,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { Which interval gives the domain of the function } y=\\frac{3}{\\sqrt{x+6}} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:<br><br>Since an expression inside a square root cannot be negative: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore x+6 \\geq 0 \\\\ &amp; x \\geq-6 \\end{aligned} $$ However, since the square root is on the denominator, it also cannot equal to 0 (we can\'t divide by 0), so we must change our domain to: $$ x&gt;-6 $$</p>','2023-12-19 22:49:58',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(42,1,57,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Find the largest domain for which \\(\\sqrt{2 x-5}\\) is defined. Give your answer in interval notation</p>','<p>Solution:<br><br>Since an expression inside a square root cannot be negative: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 2 x-5 \\geq 0 \\\\ &amp; 2 x \\geq 5 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x \\geq \\frac{5}{2} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the domain in interval notation would be: $$ \\left[\\frac{5}{2}, \\infty\\right) $$</p>','2023-12-19 22:53:06',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(43,1,58,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Which of the following is the equation of the line that has \\(y\\)-intercept at \\((0,6)\\) and is parallel to the line \\(y=-\\frac{3}{2} x+7 ?\\)</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Recall that if a line is parallel to another, they have the same gradient $$ \\therefore m=-\\frac{3}{2} $$ Where \\(m\\) is the gradient of the unknown line. Moreover, recall the point - gradient equation of a line: $$ y=m x+b $$ Since it is known that the line has \\(y\\) - intercept at \\((0,6)\\) : $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore b=6 \\\\ \\therefore y=-\\frac{3}{2} x+6 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2023-12-19 23:10:10',0,1,NULL,0,'easy','subtopic'),(44,1,59,'freetext','D','<p>$$ \\text { Which of the following graphs best represents } y=x^2+4 x-5 \\text { ? } $$</p><p>a)&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:272/549;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/3f494cc76b022d8da54fb0d6a97bc55f.png\" width=\"272\" height=\"549\"></figure><p>b)&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:330/504;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/2e2da84b8e11fcb38998a521dedeb886.png\" width=\"330\" height=\"504\"></figure><p>c)&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:306/414;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/31ef88db5e9eeaf96771c63621be50e2.png\" width=\"306\" height=\"414\"></figure><p>d)&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:319/418;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e865cffa2f8c79d0348d85ff2a65be6d.png\" width=\"319\" height=\"418\"></figure>','<p>Solution:<br><br>Firstly, since the coefficient of \\(x^2\\) is positive, the parabola is concave up&nbsp;<br>Then, factorising the quadratic to determine \\(x\\) - intercepts: $$ \\begin{gathered} y=x^2+4 x-5 \\\\ =(x+5)(x-1) \\\\ \\therefore x-\\text { intercepts at } x=-5, x=1 \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, the graph looks like:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:319/418;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9a3482b58e7272f7c5b58a7d17a8e7d0.png\" width=\"319\" height=\"418\"></figure>','2023-12-20 03:57:40',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(45,1,59,'mcq',NULL,'<p>The graph of the curve \\(y=(x+a)^2+b\\) is shown below:&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:364/530;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9b0d7deb3a44e528600918bd4e13f37c.png\" width=\"364\" height=\"530\"></figure><p>$$ \\text { What are the values of } a \\text { and } b \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since the \\(x\\) - coordinate of the vertex is \\(x=-3\\), then it can be said that: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; -a=-3 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore a=3 \\end{aligned} $$ Moreover, since the \\(y\\) - coordinate of the vertex is \\(y=-1\\), then: $$ \\therefore b=-1 $$</p>','2023-12-20 04:01:21',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(46,1,59,'freetext','D','<p>$$ \\text { Which diagram below best shows the graph } y=3-(x+2)^2 \\text { ? } $$</p><p>a)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:409/492;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/7f3515b00940d19882f6d1529624a527.png\" width=\"409\" height=\"492\"></figure><p>b)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:377/521;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f5dcd178290aded5eb02dab80023db04.png\" width=\"377\" height=\"521\"></figure><p>c)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:391/446;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/15334eb408f21afdf68ab518d47d62d4.png\" width=\"391\" height=\"446\"></figure><p>d)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:397/504;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e78415d03a81edc1020c9a88686b9d14.png\" width=\"397\" height=\"504\"></figure>','<p>Solution:<br>Since \\(y=3-(x+2)^2\\), the \\(x\\) - coordinate of the vertex will be at \\(x=-2\\)&nbsp;<br><br>The \\(y\\) - coordinate of the vertex will be at \\(y=3\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Therefore, the vertex should be in the \\(2^{\\text {nd }}\\) quadrant of my coordinate axes.&nbsp;<br><br>Finally, since there is a negative&nbsp;in front of the \\(x^2\\), we also know that the graph must be concave down and the following answer:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:397/504;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e78415d03a81edc1020c9a88686b9d14.png\" width=\"397\" height=\"504\"></figure>','2023-12-20 04:09:31',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(47,1,59,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { The solutions to the quadratic equation } 3 x^2-x-4=0 \\text { are: } $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Factorising \\(3 x^2-x-4=0\\) by cross multiplication: $$ \\begin{array}{cc} 3 &amp; -4 \\\\ 1 &amp; 1 \\end{array} $$$$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 3 x^2-x-4=(3 x-4)(x+1) \\\\ \\therefore(3 x-4)(x+1)=0 \\\\ x=\\frac{4}{3} O R-1 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2023-12-20 04:13:05',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(48,1,62,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { Which of the following is an even function? } $$</p>','<p>Solution: An even function is defined algebraically as a function where: $$ f(x)=f(-x) $$ Now testing out each option:&nbsp;<br>If \\(f(x)=x^2+x\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =(-x)^2+(-x) \\\\ &amp; =x^2-x \\\\ &amp; \\neq f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, not even<br><br>If \\(f(x)=x^3+x\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =(-x)^3+(-x) \\\\ &amp; =-x^3-x \\\\ &amp; \\neq f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, not even<br><br>If \\(f(x)=x^3+3\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =(-x)^3+3 \\\\ &amp; =-x^3+3 \\\\ &amp; \\neq f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ If \\(f(x)=x^2+3\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =(-x)^2+3 \\\\ &amp; =x^3+3 \\\\ &amp; =f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, this option is the even function and is thus the answer</p>','2023-12-20 04:20:19',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(49,1,62,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { Which of the following is an odd function? } $$</p>','<p>Solution: An odd function is defined algebraically as a function where: $$ -f(x)=f(-x) $$ Now testing out each option:&nbsp;<br><br>If \\(f(x)=x^2+2 x\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =(-x)^2+2(-x) \\\\ &amp; =x^2-2 x \\\\ &amp; \\neq-f(x) \\end{aligned} $$Hence, not odd&nbsp;<br><br>If \\(f(x)=x^3+2\\), $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =(-x)^3+2 \\\\ &amp; =-x^3+2 \\\\ &amp; \\neq-f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, not odd&nbsp;<br><br>If \\(f(x)=x^2+2\\), $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =(-x)^2+2 \\\\ &amp; =x^3+2 \\\\ &amp; \\neq-f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, not odd<br><br>If \\(f(x)=x^3+2 x\\), $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =(-x)^3+2(-x) \\\\ &amp; =-x^3-2 x \\\\ &amp; =-f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, this option is the odd function and is thus the answer</p>','2023-12-20 04:24:46',0,1,NULL,0,NULL,'subtopic'),(50,1,1,'mcq',NULL,'Smome Question',NULL,'2023-12-20 04:27:17',0,1,3,120,'easy','subtopic'),(51,1,62,'mcq',NULL,'<p>The function $f(x)$ is a continuous odd function. Which of the following statements is necessarily true?&nbsp;</p><p><br>i.&nbsp; &nbsp;\\(f(x^2)\\) is even&nbsp;</p><p><br>ii.&nbsp; \\(f(x)+f(-x)=0\\)</p><p><br>iii. \\(f(0)=0\\)</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since we know that \\(f(x)\\) is odd, therefore: $$ f(-x)=-f(x) $$ Looking at statement i: For the function \\(f\\left(x^2\\right)\\) : $$ f\\left((-x)^2\\right)=f\\left(x^2\\right) $$ Hence, since \\(f\\left((-x)^2\\right)=f\\left(x^2\\right)\\), it can be said that \\(f\\left(x^2\\right)\\) is even and statement \\(\\mathrm{i}\\) is true Looking at statement ii: $$ f(x)+f(-x)=0 $$ Since \\(f(-x)=-f(x)\\) : $$ \\therefore f(x)-f(x)=0 $$ Hence, statement ii is true<br><br>Looking at statement iii:&nbsp;<br>Since it is known that \\(f(-x)=-f(x)\\), then \\(f(0)\\) MUST equal to 0&nbsp;<br><br>Another way to imagine this is that since \\(f(x)\\) is odd, it has point symmetry, meaning that it must intersect the origin, so \\(f(0)=0\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, statement iii is true Therefore, all three statements are true!</p>','2023-12-20 04:27:35',0,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,'subtopic'),(52,1,62,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Given a function: $$f(x)=\\frac{2 x}{x^2-5}$$<br>Which of the following statements is true?</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>It appears that for \\(f(x)\\), many \\(x\\) - values correspond to only one \\(y\\)-value. Therefore, \\(f(x)\\) is considered many - to - one.&nbsp;<br><br>For example, for the \\(y\\) - value of 1 :$$ \\begin{gathered} 1=\\frac{2 x}{x^2-5} \\\\ x^2-5=2 x \\\\ x^2-2 x-5=0 \\\\ \\therefore x=\\frac{2 \\pm \\sqrt{4+20}}{2} \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, as can be seen, multiple \\(x\\) - values equal to the same one \\(y\\) - value. Now testing for even or odd, considering the expressions for \\(f(-x)\\) and \\(-f(x)\\) : $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =\\frac{2(-x)}{(-x)^2-5} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{-2 x}{x^2-5} \\\\ -f(x) &amp; =-\\frac{2 x}{x^2-5} \\\\ \\therefore f(-x) &amp; =-f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, \\(f(x)\\) is odd and many - to - one.</p>','2023-12-20 04:31:45',0,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,'subtopic'),(53,1,63,'mcq',NULL,'<p>If \\(f(x)=x^2-2 x\\) and \\(g(x)=2 x+1\\), which of the following is a correct expression for \\(f(g(x))\\) ?</p>','<p>Solution: $$ \\begin{aligned} f(g(x) &amp; =(g(x))^2-2 g(x) \\\\ &amp; =(2 x+1)^2-2(2 x+1) \\\\ &amp; =4 x^2+4 x+1-4 x-2 \\\\ &amp; =4 x^2-1 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2023-12-20 04:36:31',0,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,'subtopic'),(54,1,63,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { Let } f(x)=\\frac{2}{4-x} \\text { and } g(x)=x-3 \\text {. The domain of } f(g(x)) \\text { is: } $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>First, finding the equation for \\(f(g(x))\\) : $$ \\begin{aligned} f(g(x)) &amp; =\\frac{2}{4-(x-3)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{4-x+3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{7-x} \\end{aligned} $$ Since the denominator of a fraction cannot equal 0 , the only restriction is: $$ x \\neq 7 $$ Hence, the domain is all real \\(x, x \\neq 7\\)</p>','2023-12-20 05:15:32',0,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,'subtopic'),(55,1,63,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Let \\(f(x)\\) and \\(g(x)\\) be functions such that \\(f(2)=4, f(3)=2, g(2)=3, g(3)=2\\) and \\(g(4)=1\\). The value of \\(f(g(3))\\) is:</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since \\(g(3)=2\\) : $$ f(g(3))=f(2)=4 $$</p>','2023-12-20 05:23:42',0,1,NULL,50,NULL,'subtopic'),(56,1,63,'mcq',NULL,'<p>It is known that \\(f(x)\\) is an odd function and \\(g(x)\\) is an even function. Given that \\(f(3)=3\\) and \\(g(3)=-3\\), what is the value of \\(f(g(-3))+g(f(-3))\\) ?</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;</p><p>Since \\(f(x)\\) is odd: $$f(-x)=-f(x)$$ $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore f(-3)=-f(3) \\\\ &amp; =-3 \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(g(x)\\) is even: $$ g(x)=g(-x) $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore g(-3) &amp; =g(3) \\\\ &amp; =-3 \\\\ \\therefore f(g(-3))+g(f(-3)) &amp; =f(-3)+g(-3) \\\\ &amp; =-3+(-3) \\\\ &amp; =-6 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the answer is \\(-6\\)</p>','2023-12-20 05:28:39',0,1,NULL,60,NULL,'subtopic'),(57,1,63,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Let \\(f(x)=2-x\\) and \\(g(x)=6+x\\)&nbsp;<br>What is the domain of the function: $$ h(x)=\\ln \\left\\{\\frac{f(-x)}{g(-x)}\\right\\} ? $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>First, simplifying our logarithm using log laws: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\ln \\left\\{\\frac{f(-x)}{g(-x)}\\right\\}=\\ln ( &amp; f(-x))-\\ln (g(-x)) \\\\ f(-x) &amp; =2-(-x) \\\\ &amp; =2+x \\\\ g(-x) &amp; =6+(-x) \\\\ &amp; =6-x \\\\ \\therefore \\ln (f(-x))-\\ln (g(-x)) &amp; =\\ln (2+x)-\\ln (6-x) \\end{aligned} $$ The expression inside a logarithm cannot be negative or equal to 0 . Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 2+x&gt;0 \\\\ &amp; x&gt;-2 \\\\ &amp; 6-x&gt;0 \\\\ &amp; x&lt;6 \\end{aligned} $$ Now combining these two domains simultaneously:<br>$$ \\therefore-2&lt;x&lt;6$$</p>','2023-12-20 05:33:53',0,1,NULL,60,NULL,'subtopic'),(58,1,65,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { Which of the following shows the solution(s) for the equation }|x+1|=9 \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>If we remove the absolute values: $$ \\begin{gathered} x+1= \\pm 9 \\\\ \\therefore x=-9-1 \\text { OR } 9-1 \\\\ x=-10 \\text { OR } 8 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2023-12-20 05:40:15',0,1,NULL,50,NULL,'subtopic'),(59,1,65,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$ \\text { What is the equation of the graph shown below? } $$</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:545/334;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/81887ba42e9dce5fd43ffde1690bc710.png\" width=\"545\" height=\"334\"></figure>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>First of all, the absolute value graph is upside down, meaning that there must be a negative in front.&nbsp;Luckily, all answer options have this.<br><br>Secondly, the vertex of the absolute value is 4 units above the \\(x\\) - axis, meaning that the graph ends in a \\(+4\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Once again, all answer options have this. Thirdly, the vertex is 3 units to the right of the origin, meaning that there must be a transformation of \\(x \\rightarrow x-3\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Finally, to test whether there is vertical dilation, substitute in the \\(y\\) - intercept coordinates, \\((1,0)\\) to check: $$ \\begin{aligned} 1 &amp; =-|0-3|+4 \\\\ &amp; =-3+4 \\\\ &amp; =1 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2023-12-20 05:43:30',0,1,NULL,60,NULL,'subtopic'),(60,1,66,'mcq',NULL,'<p>The graph of \\(y=x^3+5 x^2-2 x+4\\) is reflected about the \\(y\\) - axis. Which of the following represents the equation after the graph is reflected?</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since the graph is reflected about the \\(y\\)-axis, the transformation which occurs is that: $$ x \\rightarrow-x $$ In other words, all the \" \\(x\\) \" change to  \\(-x\\) now: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore y &amp; =(-x)^3+5(-x)^2-2(-x)+4 \\\\ &amp; =-x^3+5 x^2+2 x+4 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2023-12-20 06:09:46',0,1,NULL,60,NULL,'subtopic'),(61,1,66,'mcq',NULL,'<p>The graph of \\(f(x)=\\frac{4 x^3-x^2}{\\sqrt{x^2-1}}\\) is reflected about the \\(x\\)-axis. Which of the following represents the equation after the graph is reflected?</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Since the graph is reflected about the \\(y\\)-axis, the transformation which occurs is that: $$ \\begin{gathered} y \\rightarrow-y \\\\ \\therefore-y=\\frac{4 x^3-x^2}{\\sqrt{x^2-1}} \\\\ y=-\\frac{4 x^3-x^2}{\\sqrt{x^2-1}} \\\\ =\\frac{-4 x^3+x^2}{\\sqrt{x^2-1}} \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2023-12-20 06:13:43',0,1,NULL,60,NULL,'subtopic'),(62,1,18,'mcq',NULL,'Functions Q1',NULL,'2023-12-20 06:15:32',0,1,5,60,'easy','subtopic'),(63,1,66,'freetext','A','<p>The graph of \\(f(x)\\) is shown below:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:383/467;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/b6deedac0b3134fa801f8fa7e4950d8c.png\" width=\"383\" height=\"467\"></figure><p>Which of the following options represent the graph of &nbsp;\\(y=f(-x)\\)?</p><p>a)&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:398/467;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/2b656942dbd2fc26e11c76e2b8ae8717.png\" width=\"398\" height=\"467\"></figure><p>b)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:389/444;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/c2fec3da7040323caa5ad088c47def8b.png\" width=\"389\" height=\"444\"></figure><p>c)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:361/373;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/07ecece70948ecdd1cc27819af85be1c.png\" width=\"361\" height=\"373\"></figure><p>d)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:379/399;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ca3b8fa305b726c4788fc52f7a559a6f.png\" width=\"379\" height=\"399\"></figure>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>We are asked to sketch \\(f(-x)\\), where since \\(x \\rightarrow-x\\), we know that this graph will be the graph of \\(f(x)\\) reflected about the \\(y\\) - axis.&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, the graph which resembles this is shown below:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:540/392;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/acf02bcb3118810786a41cf578adde6b.png\" width=\"540\" height=\"392\"></figure>','2023-12-20 06:17:07',0,1,NULL,60,NULL,'subtopic'),(64,1,18,'mcq',NULL,'Functions Q2',NULL,'2023-12-20 06:42:45',0,1,5,120,'easy','subtopic'),(65,1,18,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Functions Q4</p>','','2023-12-20 06:43:13',0,1,2,50,'easy','subtopic'),(66,1,18,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Functions Q4</p>','','2023-12-20 06:43:24',0,1,2,50,'easy','subtopic'),(70,1,19,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Eighty tickets are sold in a raffle. There are two prizes available. Abraham bought 5 tickets.&nbsp;</p><p>Which expression below gives the probability that Abraham wins both prizes?</p>','<p>Solution:</p><p>The chance of winning the first prize is:</p><p>$$<br>P(\\text {first prize})=\\frac{5}{80}<br>$$</p><p>The chance of winning the second prize AFTER youve won the first prize is</p><p>$$<br>P(\\text {second prize})=\\frac{4}{79}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, the probability of winning both is:</p><p>$$<br>P(\\text {win both})=\\frac{5}{80} \\times \\frac{4}{79}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-20 22:51:51',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(71,1,19,'mcq',NULL,'<p>When three archers take part in an archery competition, their chances of hitting the target are \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\), \\(\\frac{1}{4}\\) and \\(\\frac{1}{5}\\). Calculate the probability that one, and only one, arrow will hit the target if the three archers shoot at the target simultaneously</p>','<p>If only one arrow hits the target then there are 3 possible cases:<br>Case 1: only first archer hits<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(\\text { only first archer hits }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{3}{4} \\times \\frac{4}{5} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{5}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Case 2: only second archer hits<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(\\text { only second archer hits }) &amp; =\\frac{2}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{4} \\times \\frac{4}{5} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{2}{15}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Case 3: only third archer hits<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(\\text { only third archer hits }) &amp; =\\frac{2}{3} \\times \\frac{3}{4} \\times \\frac{1}{5} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{10}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Combining this together:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\text { Answer } &amp; =\\frac{1}{5}+\\frac{2}{15}+\\frac{1}{10} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{13}{30}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-20 23:16:33',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(72,1,19,'mcq',NULL,'<p>n is an integer chosen at random from the set \\(\\{4,12,23,29\\}\\)&nbsp;</p><p>\\(p\\) is chosen at random from the set \\(\\{1,7,13,24,32\\}\\)&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that \\(n+p=36\\)?</p>','<p>First calculating the sample space, the total number of possibilities for \\(n+p\\) is:<br>$$<br>\\text { Sample space }=4 \\times 5=20<br>$$</p><p>Out of these 20 possibilities, we now count how many of them will add up to 36 :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>4+32=36 \\\\<br>12+24=36 \\\\<br>23+13=36 \\\\<br>29+7=36<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, there are 4 possibilities, meaning:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(n+p=36) &amp; =\\frac{4}{20} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{5}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-20 23:21:03',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(73,1,19,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Two ordinary dice are rolled, and the numbers on the top faces are added to make a \"score\".&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that the scores are \\(10\\)?</p>','<p>Sketching a quick table of results:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:789/270;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ab79114b295aad8dc3ae35a0970b6d65.jpeg\" width=\"789\" height=\"270\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The probability of getting a 10 is therefore:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(\\text { score of } 10) &amp; =\\frac{3}{36} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{12}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-20 23:25:02',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(74,1,19,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Forty tickets are sold in a raffle. There are two prizes, first and second. Peter buys 5 tickets.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that he wins the second prize but not the second?</p>','<p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(\\text { lose } 1 \\text {st and win } 2 n d) &amp; =\\frac{35}{40} \\times \\frac{5}{39} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{35}{312}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-20 23:30:14',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(75,1,19,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Quentin has 12 marbles in a bag, 5 of which are green and the rest being yellow. He randomly selects one and takes it out of the bag, notes its colour, and places it back.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the least number of times Quentin will have to take a marble so that he has over 90% chance of getting a green marble at least once?</p>','<p>Considering complementary probability:<br>$$<br>P(\\text {green marble at least once})=1-P(\\text {no green marbles})<br>$$</p><p>On any one draw, the probability of getting a yellow marble is:<br>$$<br>P(\\text {yellow})=\\frac{7}{12}<br>$$</p><p>Assuming that there are \\(n\\) draws, the chance of all selected marbles being yellow is:<br>$$<br>P(\\text {no green marbles})=\\left(\\frac{7}{12}\\right)^n<br>$$</p><p>Hence, since I want \\(P(\\)green marble at least once\\()&gt;0.9\\) :<br>$$<br>\\therefore 1-\\left(\\frac{7}{12}\\right)^n&gt;0.9<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>0.1&gt;\\left(\\frac{7}{12}\\right)^n \\\\<br>\\log _{10} 0.1&gt;\\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{7}{12}\\right)^n \\\\<br>-1&gt;n \\log _{10} \\frac{7}{12} \\\\<br>n \\log _{10} \\frac{7}{12}&lt;-1 \\\\<br>\\therefore n&gt;\\frac{-1}{\\log _{10} \\frac{7}{12}}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Note that the inequality was flipped in the previous step because \\(\\log _{10} \\frac{7}{12}&lt;0\\), and dividing by a negative number always means we must flip the inequality<br>$$<br>\\therefore n&gt;4.27<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the least number of times that Quentin must draw will be 5 times</p>','2023-12-20 23:38:15',0,1,NULL,180,NULL,'subtopic'),(76,1,19,'mcq',NULL,'<p>As part of Year 8, a hundred students in the cohort are to choose at least one of either Japanese or Latin as a subject. There are 55 students who chose Japanese as a subject, and 73 students who chose Latin as a subject. A student is randomly selected out of the 100.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that this student does both languages?</p>','<p>First calculating the number that does both languages:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\text { Number who do both } &amp; =55+73-100 \\\\<br>&amp; =28 \\\\<br>\\therefore P(\\text {both}) &amp; =\\frac{28}{100} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{7}{25}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-20 23:43:40',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(77,1,19,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Hayley has 10 marbles in a bag, 4 of which are red and the rest of which are blue. She randomly draws 1 out of the bag, notes its colour and then puts it back in the bag before drawing another.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that both marbles drawn are the same colour?</p>','<p>There are two possible cases here when considering marbles of the same colour. Either two red marbles or two blue marbles.</p><p>Case 1: Two red marbles<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(R R) &amp; =\\frac{4}{10} \\times \\frac{3}{9} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{12}{90} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{2}{15}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Case 2: Two blue marbles<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(B B) &amp; =\\frac{6}{10} \\times \\frac{5}{9} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{30}{90} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{3}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore P(\\text { two marbles of same colour }) &amp; =\\frac{2}{15}+\\frac{1}{3} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{7}{15}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-20 23:48:28',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(78,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$<br>\\text {Differentiate } y=\\left(3 x^2+7\\right)^4<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering substitution, let \\(u=3 x^2+7\\) :<br>$$<br>\\frac{d u}{d x}=6 x<br>$$</p><p>Moreover:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>y=u^4 \\\\<br>\\frac{d y}{d u}=4 u^3<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, applying chain rule:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{d y}{d u} \\times \\frac{d u}{d x} \\\\<br>&amp; =4 u^3 \\times 6 x \\\\<br>&amp; =24 x\\left(3 x^2+7\\right)^3<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 00:35:40',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(79,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the equation of the tangent to the curve \\(y=x^2-4 x\\) at the point \\((1,-3)\\)?</p>','<p>Finding the derivative function:<br>$$<br>y^{\\prime}=2 x-4<br>$$</p><p>Using this to find the gradient when \\(x=1\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>m &amp; =2(1)-4 \\\\<br>&amp; =-2<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Then applying the point - gradient formula to find the equation of the tangent:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>y-y_1=m\\left(x-x_1\\right) \\\\<br>y--3=-2(x-1) \\\\<br>y+3=-2 x+2 \\\\<br>\\therefore y+2 x+1=0<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 00:49:50',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(80,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p>$$<br>\\text { What is the equation of the normal to the curve } y=x^2-4 x \\text { at the point }(1,-3) ?<br>$$</p>','<p>Finding the derivative function:<br>$$<br>y^{\\prime}=2 x-4<br>$$</p><p>Using this to find the gradient of the tangent when $x=1$ :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>m &amp; =2(1)-4 \\\\<br>&amp; =-2<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Then, finding the gradient of the normal when $x=1$ :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>m_{\\text {normal }} &amp; =-\\frac{1}{-2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Then applying the point - gradient formula to find the equation of the normal:</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>y-y_1=m\\left(x-x_1\\right) \\\\<br>y--3=\\frac{1}{2}(x-1) \\\\<br>y+3=\\frac{1}{2} x-\\frac{1}{2} \\\\<br>2 y+6=x-1 \\\\<br>2 y-x+7=0 \\\\<br>x-2 y-7=0<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 01:03:33',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(81,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [1 mark]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Differentiate } y=\\pi x^\\pi<br>$$</p>','<p>Differentiating using the power rule:</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>y^{\\prime} &amp; =\\pi \\times \\pi x^{\\pi-1} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\pi^2 x^{\\pi-1}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 01:08:04',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(82,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice Question</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text {Find the value of } \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^3-8}{x-2}<br>$$</p>','<p>First factorising and simplifying:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^3-8}{x-2} &amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{(x-2)\\left(x^2+2 x+4\\right)}{x-2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2}\\left(x^2+2 x+4\\right) \\\\<br>&amp; =2^2+2(2)+4 \\\\<br>&amp; =12<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 01:12:59',0,1,NULL,120,NULL,'subtopic'),(83,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Find } f^{\\prime}(2) \\text { if } f(x)=\\frac{3 x-1}{x+1}<br>$$</p>','<p>Recalling quotient rule:<br>$$<br>\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}<br>$$</p><p>For this question, \\(u=3 x-1\\) and \\(v=x+1\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=3 \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=1 \\\\<br>\\therefore f^{\\prime}(x)=\\frac{3(x+1)-1(3 x-1)}{(x+1)^2} \\\\<br>=\\frac{3 x+3-3 x+1}{(x+1)^2} \\\\<br>=\\frac{4}{(x+1)^2}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, evaluating \\(f^{\\prime}(2)\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>f^{\\prime}(2) &amp; =\\frac{4}{(2+1)^2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{4}{9}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 01:15:47',0,1,NULL,240,'medium','subtopic'),(84,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks]</u></p><p>A rectangular box is required to have a volume of \\(48 \\mathrm{~m}^3\\) and its length is to be double its width. The box is also going to be lined with a strip of gold running along all of its edges.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find the dimensions of the box if the total length of gold is to be a minimum.</p>','<p>Starting with a preliminary sketch of the rectangular box:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:271/141;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/65624eb822cd97e977bf64ddc6eddace.png\" width=\"271\" height=\"141\"></figure><p>Since the known volume is \\(48 \\mathrm{~m}^3\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>V=2 x^2 h=48 \\\\<br>x^2 h=24 \\\\<br>h=\\frac{24}{x^2}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Then, considering the expression for perimeter, which is the length of gold strip needed for the box:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P &amp; =4(2 x+x+h) \\\\<br>&amp; =4\\left(3 x+\\frac{24}{x^2}\\right) \\\\<br>&amp; =12 x+\\frac{96}{x^2} \\\\<br>&amp; =12 x+96 x^{-2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>To find the minimum total length of gold, we differentiate \\(P\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d P}{d x} &amp; =12+96 \\times-2 x^{-3} \\\\<br>&amp; =12-\\frac{192}{x^3}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Letting \\(\\frac{d P}{d x}=0\\) to find the stationary point:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>12-\\frac{192}{x^3}=0 \\\\<br>12=\\frac{192}{x^3} \\\\<br>x^3=16 \\\\<br>\\therefore x=2^{\\frac{4}{3}}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>To test if this is a minimum point, consider the second derivative:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d^2 P}{d x^2} &amp; =-192 \\times-3 x^{-4} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{576}{x^4}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>When \\(x=2^{\\frac{4}{3}}\\) :<br>$$<br>\\frac{d^2 P}{d x^2}=\\frac{576}{2^{\\frac{16}{3}}}&gt;0<br>$$</p><p>Since \\(\\frac{d^2 P}{d x^2}&gt;0\\), then \\(x=2^{\\frac{4}{3}}\\) is a minimum turning point</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Therefore, the dimensions of the box will be:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\text { width } &amp; =2^{\\frac{4}{3}} \\\\<br>\\text { length } &amp; =2 \\times 2^{\\frac{4}{3}} \\\\<br>&amp; =2^{\\frac{7}{3}} \\\\<br>\\text { height } &amp; =\\frac{24}{x^2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{24}{2^{\\frac{8}{3}}} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{6}{2^{\\frac{2}{3}}}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 01:23:00',0,1,NULL,540,'hard','subtopic'),(85,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Evaluate } \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{x^3-27}{x-3}<br>$$</p>','<p>Factorising and simplifying the limit:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{x^3-27}{x-3} &amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{(x-3)\\left(x^2+3 x+9\\right)}{x-3} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} x^2+3 x+9 \\\\<br>&amp; =9+9+9 \\\\<br>&amp; =27<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 02:16:12',0,1,NULL,180,'medium','subtopic'),(86,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the equation of the normal to the curve \\(y=x^2-8 x\\) at the point \\((-1,9)?\\)</p>','<p>First finding the derivative function:<br>$$<br>y^{\\prime}=2 x-8<br>$$</p><p>Then finding the gradient of the tangent when $x=-1$ :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>m &amp; =2(-1)-8 \\\\<br>&amp; =-10<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>The gradient of the normal will therefore be:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>m_{\\text {normal }} &amp; =-\\frac{1}{-10} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{10}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Applying point - gradient formula to determine the equation of the normal now:<br>$$<br>y-y_1=m\\left(x-x_1\\right)<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>y-9=\\frac{1}{10}(x--1) \\\\<br>y-9=\\frac{x}{10}+\\frac{1}{10} \\\\<br>10 y-90=x+1 \\\\<br>\\therefore 10 y-x-91=0<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 02:22:29',0,1,NULL,120,'medium','subtopic'),(87,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice Question</u></p><p>The diagram below shows the line \\(l\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:353/246;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/7ff9ba68a906df05d82ee1cfb73e1c22.png\" width=\"353\" height=\"246\"></figure><p>Which option gives the correct slope of the line?</p>','<p>Recall the formula for gradient:<br>$$<br>m=\\tan \\theta<br>$$</p><p>Where \\(\\theta\\) is the angle that a line makes to the POSITIVE \\(x\\) - axis<br>Therefore, in this case, \\(\\theta=135^{\\circ}\\), NOT \\(45^{\\circ}\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore m &amp; =\\tan 135^{\\circ} \\\\<br>&amp; =-1<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 02:25:43',0,1,NULL,120,'hard','subtopic'),(88,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice Question</u></p><p>Which equation below represents the line perpendicular to \\(2 x-5 y=-6\\), passing through the point \\((2,2)\\)?</p>','<p>Rearranging the given line to first determine the gradient:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; 5 y=2 x+6 \\\\<br>&amp; y=\\frac{2}{5} x+\\frac{6}{5}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>The gradient of this line is \\(\\frac{2}{5}\\)<br>The product of the gradients of two perpendicular lines is equal to -1 . i.e.:<br>$$<br>m_t \\times m_n=-1<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the gradient of the perpendicular line will be given as:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>m &amp; =-\\frac{1}{\\frac{2}{5}} \\\\<br>&amp; =-\\frac{5}{2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Now applying the point - gradient formula:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>y-y_1=m\\left(x-x_1\\right) \\\\<br>y-2=-\\frac{5}{2}(x-2) \\\\<br>2 y-4=-5(x-2) \\\\<br>2 y-4=-5 x+10 \\\\<br>\\therefore 5 x+2 y=14<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 02:34:17',0,1,NULL,120,'medium','subtopic'),(89,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Differentiate the following with respect to \\(x\\) :<br>$$<br>y=(5 x+9)^7<br>$$</p>','<p>Remember to use chain rule for this question:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =7(5 x+9)^6 \\times 5 \\\\<br>&amp; =35(5 x+9)^6<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 02:34:17',0,1,NULL,120,'medium','subtopic'),(90,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [1 mark]</u></p><p>Find the derivative of:<br>$$<br>y=\\left(x^2+9 x-5\\right)^3<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering chain rule here:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\left(x^2+9 x-5\\right)^{\\prime}=2 x+9 \\\\<br>\\therefore y^{\\prime}=3\\left(x^2+9 x-5\\right)^2 \\times(2 x+9) &nbsp;[ \\because &nbsp;\\text { chain rule }] \\\\<br>=3(2 x+9)\\left(x^2+9 x-5\\right)^2<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 03:19:24',0,1,NULL,120,'easy','subtopic'),(91,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [1 mark]</u></p><p>Find the derivative of:<br>$$<br>y=\\frac{x}{2 x^2+1}<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering quotient rule:<br>$$<br>\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=x\\) and \\(v=2 x^2+1\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=1 \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=4 x \\\\<br>\\therefore y^{\\prime}=\\frac{1\\left(2 x^2+1\\right)-4 x^2}{\\left(2 x^2+1\\right)^2} \\\\<br>=\\frac{1-2 x^2}{\\left(2 x^2+1\\right)^2}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 03:26:10',0,1,NULL,180,'easy','subtopic'),(92,1,15,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { If } f(x)=\\sqrt{x} \\text {, show that } f^{\\prime}(x)=\\frac{1}{2 \\sqrt{x}} \\text { using first principles }<br>$$</p>','<p>Recall the first principles formula:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sqrt{x+h}-\\sqrt{x}}{h}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Multiplying the top and bottom by the conjugate:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sqrt{x+h}-\\sqrt{x}}{h} \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{x+h}+\\sqrt{x}}{\\sqrt{x+h}+\\sqrt{x}} &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x+h-x}{h(\\sqrt{x+h}+\\sqrt{x})} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{h}{h(\\sqrt{x+h}+\\sqrt{x})} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{(\\sqrt{x+h}+\\sqrt{x})} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{x}+\\sqrt{x}} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2 \\sqrt{x}}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\therefore f^{\\prime}(x)=\\frac{1}{2 \\sqrt{x}}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-21 03:32:42',0,1,NULL,240,'hard','subtopic'),(93,2,19,'mcq',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2023-12-21 07:42:03',0,1,2,240,'easy','subtopic'),(94,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Differentiate } \\ln \\sqrt{x^2+5}<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering applying logarithmic laws first:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>y &amp; =\\ln \\sqrt{x^2+5} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\ln \\left(x^2+5\\right)^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\ln \\left(x^2+5\\right) \\text { [logarithm laws] }<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Then, differentiating whilst applying substitution:<br>Let \\(u=x^2+5\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; \\frac{d u}{d x}=2 x \\\\<br>&amp; y=\\frac{1}{2} \\ln u<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore \\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{d y}{d u} \\times \\frac{d u}{d x} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{u} \\times 2 x \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{x}{u} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{x}{x^2+5}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 06:47:46',0,1,NULL,180,'medium','subtopic'),(95,2,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Differentiate } y=x^2 \\cos x<br>$$</p>','<p>Remembering product rule to apply in this question:<br>$$<br>(u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=x^2\\) and \\(v=\\cos x\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=2 x \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=-\\sin x<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Hence:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\left(x^2 \\cos x\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =2 x(\\cos x)+(-\\sin x) x^2 \\\\<br>&amp; =2 x \\cos x-x^2 \\sin x<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 06:52:32',0,1,NULL,180,'medium','subtopic'),(96,2,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Differentiate } y=\\ln \\left(\\frac{x+1}{x^2}\\right)<br>$$</p>','<p>First applying logarithmic laws to equation $y$ :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>y &amp; =\\ln (x+1)-\\ln \\left(x^2\\right) \\\\<br>&amp; =\\ln (x+1)-2 \\ln x<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Then differentiating:<br>$$<br>y^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{x+1}-\\frac{2}{x}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 07:10:36',0,1,NULL,180,'hard','subtopic'),(97,2,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Differentiate } y=x^2 \\cos 5 x<br>$$</p>','<p>Remembering product rule to apply in this question:<br>$$<br>(u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=x^2\\) and \\(v=\\cos 5 x\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=2 x \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=-5 \\sin 5 x[\\text {don\'t forget chain rule!}]<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Hence:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\left(x^2 \\cos 5 x\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =2 x(\\cos 5 x)+(-5 \\sin 5 x) x^2 \\\\<br>&amp; =2 x \\cos 5 x-5 x^2 \\sin 5 x<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 08:23:53',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(98,2,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Differentiate the following expression:<br>$$<br>y=x \\tan 4 x<br>$$</p>','<p>Remembering product rule to apply in this question:<br>$$<br>(u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=x\\) and \\(v=\\tan 4 x\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=1 \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=4 \\sec ^2 x[\\text { don\'t forget chain rule }]<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Hence:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>(x \\tan 4 x)^{\\prime} &amp; =1(\\tan 4 x)+\\left(4 \\sec ^2 x\\right) x \\\\<br>&amp; =\\tan 4 x+4 x \\sec ^2 x<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 08:29:56',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(99,2,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Differentiate the following expression:<br>$$<br>y=\\ln \\left(\\frac{x+1}{\\sqrt{x-1}}\\right)<br>$$</p>','<p>First applying logarithmic laws:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>y &amp; =\\ln (x+1)-\\ln (x-1)^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\ln (x+1)-\\frac{1}{2} \\ln (x-1)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Then, differentiating:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{1}{x+1}-\\frac{1}{2(x-1)} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{2(x-1)-(x+1)}{2(x-1)(x+1)} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{x-3}{2\\left(x^2-1\\right)}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 09:10:48',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(100,2,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { If } y=\\ln (\\ln x) \\text {, then } \\frac{d y}{d x} \\text { is: }<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering substitution:<br>Let \\(u=\\ln x\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\frac{d u}{d x}=\\frac{1}{x} \\\\<br>y=\\ln u \\\\<br>\\therefore \\frac{d y}{d u}=\\frac{1}{u}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Then considering chain rule:$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{d y}{d u} \\times \\frac{d u}{d x} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{u} \\times \\frac{1}{x} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{\\ln x} \\times \\frac{1}{x} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{x \\ln x}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 09:34:37',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(101,2,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { If } f(x)=\\frac{1}{\\cot 3 x} \\text {, then } f^{\\prime}(x) \\text { is: }<br>$$</p>','<p>Since \\(\\cot 3 x=\\frac{1}{\\tan 3 x}\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>f(x)=\\frac{1}{\\frac{1}{\\tan 3 x}} \\\\<br>=\\tan 3 x \\\\<br>\\therefore f^{\\prime}(x)=3 \\sec ^2 3 x[\\because \\text {chain rule}]<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 09:40:22',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(102,2,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Find the derivative of } \\cos ^2 4 x \\text { with respect to } x<br>$$</p>','<p>Differentiating using chain rule:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\left(\\cos ^2 4 x\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =2 \\cos 4 x \\times-4 \\sin 4 x \\\\<br>&amp; =-8 \\sin 4 x \\cos 4 x<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>If we would like to do this using substitution:<br>Let \\(u=\\cos 4 x\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\frac{d u}{d x}=-4 \\sin 4 x \\\\<br>y=u^2<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; \\frac{d y}{d u}=2 u \\\\<br>\\therefore \\frac{d y}{d x}= &amp; \\frac{d y}{d u} \\times \\frac{d u}{d x} \\\\<br>= &amp; 2 u \\times-4 \\sin 4 x \\\\<br>= &amp; -8 \\sin 4 x \\cos 4 x<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 09:46:26',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(103,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A particle moves so that its velocity function at time $t$ seconds, is given by:<br>$$<br>v=2 e^{-t}(2-t)<br>$$Find the time when the acceleration is zero</p>','<p>Considering product rule:<br>$$<br>(u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u<br>$$</p><p>Where \\(u=2 e^{-t}$ and $v=(2-t)\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=-2 e^{-t} \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=-1 \\\\<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore a &amp; =-2 e^{-t}(2-t)+(-1) 2 e^{-t} \\\\<br>&amp; =-2 e^{-t}(2-t)-2 e^{-t} \\\\<br>&amp; =-4 e^{-t}+2 t e^{-t}-2 e^{-t} \\\\<br>&amp; =-6 e^{-t}+2 t e^{-t} \\\\<br>&amp; =2 e^{-t}(t-3)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, acceleration is equal to 0 when \\(t=3\\)</p>','2023-12-22 18:35:35',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(104,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Differentiate } y=\\frac{\\sin x}{1+\\cos x} \\text { and simplify }<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering quotient rule:<br>$$<br>\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}<br>$$</p><p>Letting \\(u=\\sin x\\) and \\(v=1+\\cos x\\):$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=\\cos x \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=-\\sin x \\\\<br>\\therefore y^{\\prime}=\\frac{\\cos x(1+\\cos x)--\\sin x \\sin x}{(1+\\cos x)^2} \\\\<br>=\\frac{\\cos x+\\cos ^2 x+\\sin ^2 x}{(1+\\cos x)^2} \\\\<br>=\\frac{1+\\cos x}{(1+\\cos x)^2} \\\\<br>=\\frac{1}{1+\\cos x}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 18:50:23',0,1,2,240,'hard','subtopic'),(105,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [6 marks total]</u></p><p>A particle moves along the \\(x\\) - axis, starting from the origin. Its velocity - time equation is given as:<br>$$<br>v=1-2 \\sin t<br>$$</p><p>Where \\(t\\) is time in seconds</p><p><br>Let \\(t_1\\) and \\(t_2\\) be the first two times that the particle comes to rest</p><p><br>i. Find the values of \\(t_1\\) and \\(t_2\\)<br><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p><p><br>ii. Sketch the velocity function for \\(0 \\leq t \\leq 2 \\pi\\)<br><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p><p><br>iii. Find the acceleration at times \\(t_1\\) and \\(t_2\\)<br><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>','<p>i. The particle will come to rest when \\(v=0\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>0=1-2 \\sin t \\\\<br>2 \\sin t=1 \\\\<br>\\therefore \\sin t=\\frac{1}{2}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>The first two times for this to occur will therefore be:$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>t_1=\\frac{\\pi}{6} \\\\<br>t_2=\\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{6} \\\\<br>=\\frac{5 \\pi}{6}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>ii. Sketching the velocity function:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:523/260;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f646385496cafac5e911d7e70b84c446.png\" width=\"523\" height=\"260\"></figure><p>iii. The acceleration function is the derivative of the velocity:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>a &amp; =(1-2 \\sin t)^{\\prime} \\\\<br>&amp; =-2 \\cos t<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, when \\(t=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>a &amp; =-2 \\cos \\frac{\\pi}{6} \\\\<br>&amp; =-2 \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\<br>&amp; =-\\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, when \\(t=\\frac{5 \\pi}{6}\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>a &amp; =-2 \\cos \\frac{5 \\pi}{6} \\\\<br>&amp; =-2 \\times-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-22 18:59:40',0,1,6,600,'hard','subtopic'),(106,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { What is the derivative of } \\frac{2 x}{\\cos x} \\text {? }<br>$$</p>','<p>Recalling quotient rule:<br>$$<br>\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=2 x\\) and \\(v=\\cos x\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=2 \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=-\\sin x \\\\<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore\\left(\\frac{x}{\\cos x}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{2(\\cos x)--\\sin x(2 x)}{\\cos ^2 x} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{2 \\cos x+2 x \\sin x}{\\cos ^2 x}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-23 07:43:25',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(107,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Differentiate the following function with respect to \\(x\\) :<br>$$<br>f(x)=\\cos \\left(\\frac{x-1}{x^2}\\right)<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering substitution, let \\(u=\\frac{x-1}{x^2}\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d u}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{1\\left(x^2\\right)-2 x(x-1)}{x^4}[\\because \\text { quotient rule }] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{x^2-2 x^2+2 x}{x^4} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{2 x-x^2}{x^4}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>y=\\cos u \\\\<br>\\frac{d y}{d u}=-\\sin u<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Now using chain rule:</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore \\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{d y}{d u} \\times \\frac{d u}{d x} \\\\<br>&amp; =-\\sin u \\times \\frac{2 x-x^2}{x^4} \\\\<br>&amp; =-\\sin \\left(\\frac{x-1}{x^2}\\right) \\times \\frac{2-x}{x^3} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{x-2}{x^3} \\sin \\left(\\frac{x-1}{x^2}\\right)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-23 07:52:56',0,1,2,240,'hard','subtopic'),(108,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Differentiate the following function with respect to \\(t\\):<br>$$<br>p=t^2 e^{-t}<br>$$</p>','<p>Recalling product rule:<br>$$<br>(u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u<br>$$</p><p>In this case let \\(u=t^2\\) and \\(v=e^{-t}\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=2 t \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=-e^{-t}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore \\frac{d p}{d t} &amp; =2 t e^{-t}+-e^{-t} t^2 \\\\<br>&amp; =2 t e^{-t}-t^2 e^{-t} \\\\<br>&amp; =t e^{-t}(2-t)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-23 08:02:30',0,1,2,180,'easy','subtopic'),(109,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p>An object travels in a straight line, with its velocity \\(v\\) at any given time \\(t\\) being given by:<br>$$<br>v=\\left(3 t^2-9 t+6\\right) m / s<br>$$</p><p>Where \\(t\\) is time in seconds</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Find the expression for the object\'s acceleration in terms of \\(t\\)&nbsp;</p><p><strong>[1 mark]</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. At what time(s) is the object at rest?<br><strong>[1 mark]</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Draw a velocity - time graph representing the motion of this object, showing all important features<br><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>','<p>i. Finding the acceleration expression by differentiating:<br>$$<br>a=6 t-9 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2<br>$$<br>ii. Object will be at rest when \\(v=0\\):</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>0 &amp; =3 t^2-9 t+6 \\\\<br>&amp; =3\\left(t^2-3 t+2\\right) \\\\<br>&amp; =3(t-2)(t-1)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\therefore t=1 \\text { or } 2<br>$$</p><p>iii. Finding the vertex of the parabola:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>x &amp; =-\\frac{b}{2 a} \\\\<br>&amp; =-\\frac{-9}{6} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{3}{2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>When \\(x=\\frac{3}{2}, y=-\\frac{3}{4}\\)</p><p><br>Therefore, now sketching the curve for \\(v\\) :</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:223/417;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/bb95dbc9b5bdd6ea5ce81d6402589139.png\" width=\"223\" height=\"417\"></figure>','2023-12-23 08:14:11',0,1,4,480,'medium','subtopic'),(110,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [7 marks total]</u></p><p>Jack the lumberjack wishes to craft a rectangular beam out of a cylindrical log of wood. The beam will be cut such that it has a width of \\(w \\mathrm{~cm}\\) and a depth of \\(d \\mathrm{~cm}\\).</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:281/173;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/013e00160b6d35d0145f19574b63222b.png\" width=\"281\" height=\"173\"></figure><p>The diameter of the cross section of his log is \\(15 \\mathrm{~cm}\\), and the strength of the beam, which is the amount of weight it can withstand, is proportional to the product of its width and the square of its depth:<br>$$<br>S=k d^2 w<br>$$</p><p>Where \\(k\\) is a positive constant of proportionality</p><p>i. Show that \\(S=k\\left(225 w-w^3\\right)\\)<br><strong>[1 mark]</strong></p><p><br>ii. Find the exact dimensions that will maximise the strength of Jack\'s beam. Provide reasoning for your answer<br><strong>[3 marks]</strong></p><p><br>iii. Find the strength of the beam in terms of \\(k\\) if its depth is double its width. Leave your answer in exact form<br><strong>[1 mark]</strong></p><p><br>iv. Express as a percentage how much stronger the beam of maximum strength is compared to the beam with dimensions outlined in part iii). Round your answer to the nearest percentage.<br><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>','<p>i. Since the diameter of the circle is 15cm, then the diagonal of the rectangle is 15cm<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\therefore w^2+d^2=15^2 \\text { (Pythagoras Theorem) } \\\\<br>d^2=225-w^2<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Plugging this into the strength formula:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S &amp; =k\\left(225-w^2\\right) w \\\\<br>&amp; =k\\left(225 w-w^3\\right)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>ii. To determine the exact dimensions that maximise the strength of Jack\'s beam, we must find the maximum turning point for $S$.</p><p>Hence considering \\(\\frac{d S}{d w}\\) :<br>$$<br>\\frac{d S}{d w}=k\\left(225-3 w^2\\right)<br>$$</p><p>To determine stationary points, find the value of \\(w\\) for which \\(\\frac{d S}{d w}=0\\):$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>k\\left(225-3 w^2\\right)=0 \\\\<br>3 k\\left(75-w^2\\right)=0 \\\\<br>\\therefore w^2=75<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>w &amp; = \\pm \\sqrt{75} \\\\<br>&amp; = \\pm 5 \\sqrt{3}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Since \\(w&gt;0\\), then \\(w=5 \\sqrt{3}\\) ONLY<br>Evaluating whether this is a maximum turning point, we determine the second derivative:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d^2 S}{d w^2} &amp; =k \\times-6 w \\\\<br>&amp; =-6 k w<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>When \\(w=5 \\sqrt{3}\\):<br>$$<br>\\frac{d^2 S}{d w^2}=-30 k \\sqrt{3}<br>$$</p><p>Since \\(k\\) is positive, then \\(\\frac{d^2 S}{d w^2}&lt;0\\)</p><p>$$<br>\\therefore w=5 \\sqrt{3} \\text { is a maximum turning point }<br>$$</p><p>When \\(w=5 \\sqrt{3}\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>d &amp; =\\sqrt{225-w^2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\sqrt{225-75} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\sqrt{150} \\\\<br>&amp; =5 \\sqrt{6}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the dimension is:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; w=5 \\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\<br>&amp; d=5 \\sqrt{6} \\mathrm{~cm}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>iii. If \\(d=2 w\\), then:<br>$$<br>d^2=225-w^2<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>4 w^2=225-w^2 \\\\<br>5 w^2=225 \\\\<br>w^2=45<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>w &amp; =\\sqrt{45} \\\\<br>&amp; =3 \\sqrt{5}(\\because w&gt;0)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>d=6 \\sqrt{5}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, finding strength:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S &amp; =k d^2 w \\\\<br>&amp; =k(6 \\sqrt{5})^2(3 \\sqrt{5}) \\\\<br>&amp; =540 k \\sqrt{5}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>iv. Calculating the beam of maximum strength, sub \\(w=5 \\sqrt{3}\\) and \\(d=5 \\sqrt{6}\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S &amp; =k d^2 w \\\\<br>&amp; =k(5 \\sqrt{6})^2 5 \\sqrt{3} \\\\<br>&amp; =750 k \\sqrt{3}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$Therefore, calculating part iii) as a percentage of this:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{540 k \\sqrt{5}}{750 k \\sqrt{3}} \\times 100 \\% &amp; =92.952 \\% \\\\<br>&amp; \\approx 93 \\%<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-23 09:03:16',0,1,7,780,'hard','subtopic'),(111,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The displacement \\(x\\) metres of a particle moving in a straight line at time \\(t\\) seconds is given by the following equation:$$<br>x=2 t-4 \\ln (2 t+1)<br>$$</p><p>Which of the following statements is false?</p>','<p>Calculating the velocity equation:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>v=\\frac{d x}{d t} &amp; =2-\\frac{4}{2 t+1} \\times 2 \\\\<br>&amp; =2-\\frac{8}{2 t+1} \\\\<br>&amp; =2-8(2 t+1)^{-1}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Then calculating the acceleration equation:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>a &amp; =-8 \\times-(2 t+1)^{-2} \\times 2 \\\\<br>&amp; =16(2 t+1)^{-2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{16}{(2 t+1)^2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>The acceleration is therefore always positive since \\((2 t+1)^2&gt;0\\)</p><p>When \\(t=0\\), calculating the velocity:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>v &amp; =2-\\frac{8}{1} \\\\<br>&amp; =-6 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>The initial velocity is therefore \\(-6 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\\)</p><p>When \\(t=0\\), calculating the displacement:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>x &amp; =0-4 \\ln 1 \\\\<br>&amp; =0<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>The initial starting position is therefore the origin</p><p>As \\(t \\rightarrow \\infty\\) :<br>$$<br>x \\rightarrow \\infty<br>$$</p><p>However:<br>$$<br>v \\rightarrow 2-0=2<br>$$</p><p>Hence, this is the false statement</p>','2023-12-23 09:54:45',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(112,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Find the derivative of the following, factorising as much as possible:<br>$$<br>f(x)=(x+4) e^{3 x}<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering product rule:<br>$$<br>(u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=(x+4)\\) and \\(v=e^{3 x}\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=1 \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=3 e^{3 x}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =1 \\times e^{3 x}+(x+4) 3 e^{3 x} \\\\<br>&amp; =e^{3 x}+3 x e^{3 x}+12 e^{3 x} \\\\<br>&amp; =e^{3 x}(13+3 x)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-23 10:06:48',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(113,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Find the derivative of the following:<br>$$<br>f(x)=\\frac{2+e^x}{\\ln x}<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering quotient rule:<br>$$<br>\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=2+e^x\\) and \\(v=\\ln x\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; u^{\\prime}=e^x \\\\<br>&amp; v^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{x}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\frac{e^x \\ln x-\\frac{1}{x}\\left(2+e^x\\right)}{(\\ln x)^2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{e^x \\ln x-\\frac{2}{x}-\\frac{e^x}{x}}{(\\ln x)^2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{\\frac{x e^x \\ln x-2-e^x}{x}}{(\\ln x)^2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{x e^x \\ln x-2-e^x}{x(\\ln x)^2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-23 19:31:07',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(114,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) is shown below:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:383/259;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/5f57c25356abb763917a1d2e7caa9c88.png\" width=\"383\" height=\"259\"></figure><p>Which of the following statements is true?</p>','<p>When \\(x=a\\):<br>The curve is concave down, meaning that:<br>$$<br>f^{\\prime \\prime}(a)&lt;0<br>$$</p><p>Additionally, since the curve is decreasing:<br>$$<br>f^{\\prime}(a)&lt;0<br>$$</p>','2023-12-23 19:49:51',0,1,1,120,'easy','subtopic'),(115,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Find the equation of the tangent to the curve } y=e^{2 x} \\text { at the point where } x=1<br>$$</p>','<p>Finding the derivative function:<br>$$<br>\\frac{d y}{d x}=2 e^{2 x}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, finding the gradient when \\(x=1\\) :<br>$$<br>m=2 e^2<br>$$</p><p>To find the equation of the tangent, consider point - gradient formula:<br>$$<br>y-y_1=m\\left(x-x_1\\right)<br>$$</p><p>When \\(x=1, y=e^2\\)$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>y-e^2=2 e^2(x-1) \\\\<br>y-e^2=2 e^2 x-2 e^2 \\\\<br>\\therefore y=2 e^2 x-e^2<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-23 20:15:10',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(116,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Differentiate the following function:<br>$$<br>f(x)=x e^{-2 x}<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering product rule for this question:<br>$$<br>(u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=x\\) and \\(v=e^{-2 x}\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=1 \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=-2 e^{-2 x}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, differentiating:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =1 \\times e^{-2 x}+\\left(-2 e^{-2 x}\\right) x \\\\<br>&amp; =e^{-2 x}-2 x e^{-2 x} \\\\<br>&amp; =e^{-2 x}(1-2 x)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-28 11:26:45',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(117,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Differentiate the following function with respect to \\(x\\):<br>$$<br>y=\\frac{\\cot x}{x}<br>$$</p>','<p>Considering quotient rule:<br>$$<br>\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}<br>$$</p><p>In this case, \\(u=\\cot x\\) and \\(v=x\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>u^{\\prime}=-\\operatorname{cosec}^2 x \\\\<br>v^{\\prime}=1<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore:</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>y^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{-\\operatorname{cosec}^2 x(x)+1(\\cot x)}{x^2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{-x \\operatorname{cosec}^2 x+\\cot x}{x^2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-28 11:36:08',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(118,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [8 marks total]</u></p><p>Consider the curve \\(f(x)=7+4 x^3-3 x^4\\):</p><p>i. Find the coordinates of any stationary points</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Determine the nature of the stationary points</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Find all points of inflection</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. Sketch the curve over the domain \\(-1 \\leq x \\leq 2\\). Please show all stationary points, you do NOT need to show intercepts</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Differentiating to determine stationary points:<br>$$<br>f^{\\prime}(x)=12 x^2-12 x^3<br>$$</p><p>Stationary points occur when \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=0\\):<br>$$<br>0=12 x^2(1-x)<br>$$</p><p>Hence, stationary points occur when \\(x=0\\) and when \\(x=1\\)</p><p>Now finding the \\(y\\) - coordinate for each point:</p><p><br>When \\(x=0, f(0)=7\\)<br>$$<br>\\therefore(0,7) \\text { is a stationary point }<br>$$</p><p>When \\(x=1, f(1)=7+4-3=8\\)<br>$$<br>\\therefore(1,8) \\text { is a stationary point }<br>$$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. To determine the nature of the stationary points, we can either construct a sign table or use the second derivative.</p><p>In this case, using the second derivative may be slightly more efficient as the function is relatively straightforward to differentiate:<br>$$<br>f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)=24 x-36 x^2<br>$$</p><p>When \\(x=0\\):</p><p>$$<br>f^{\\prime \\prime}(0)=0<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the point \\((0,7)\\) will be a horizontal point of inflection because \\(f^{\\prime}(0)=0\\) and \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(0)=0\\)</p><p>When \\(x=1\\):$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>f^{\\prime \\prime}(1) &amp; =24-36 \\\\<br>&amp; =-12 \\\\<br>&amp; &lt;0<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$<br>\\(\\therefore\\) concave down<br>Hence, the stationary point \\((1,8)\\) will be a maximum turning point</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Points of inflection will occur when \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)=0\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)=24 x-36 x^2=0 \\\\<br>12 x(2-3 x)=0 \\\\<br>\\therefore x=0 \\text { OR } \\frac{2}{3}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Checking if these points are points of inflection via a sign table:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:803/82;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9e1b6a0c711988e5dc5bdbd2e89179a6.png\" width=\"803\" height=\"82\"></figure><p>Since a change of concavity can be seen, then \\(x=0\\) and \\(x=\\frac{2}{3}\\) are both point of inflections!<br>When \\(x=0, y=7\\)<br>When \\(x=\\frac{2}{3}, y=\\frac{205}{27}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. Sketching the curve:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1920/1103;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/8b646143a1d900a13b922f5c255f6723.png\" width=\"1920\" height=\"1103\"></figure>','2023-12-28 11:42:30',0,1,8,900,'medium','subtopic'),(119,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>A particle moves along a line and has position \\(x\\) metres at time \\(t\\) seconds given by:<br>$$<br>x=2 \\sin t-\\frac{3}{2} t, \\quad t \\geq 0<br>$$</p><p>i. Where is the particle initially?<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find an expression for the velocity of the particle<br>[1 mark]</p><p><br>iii. What is the velocity of the particle initially?<br>[1 mark]</p><p><br>iv. Determine the time at which the particle first comes to rest<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. When \\(t=0\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>x &amp; =2 \\sin 0-\\frac{3}{2}(0) \\\\<br>&amp; =0<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Hence the particle is initially at the origin</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Differentiating the displacement equation:<br>$$<br>v=2 \\cos t-\\frac{3}{2}<br>$$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. When \\(t=0\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>v &amp; =2 \\cos 0-\\frac{3}{2} \\\\<br>&amp; =2-\\frac{3}{2} \\\\<br>&amp; =0.5 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. The particle comes to rest when \\(v=0\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>v=2 \\cos t-\\frac{3}{2}=0 \\\\<br>2 \\cos t=\\frac{3}{2} \\\\<br>\\cos t=\\frac{3}{4}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-29 06:48:09',0,1,5,540,'hard','subtopic'),(120,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=-e^x\\) is:</p>','<p>&nbsp;</p><p>Note for this question that \"monotonically\" means \"always\".&nbsp;</p><p>First differentiating:$$<br>y^{\\prime}=-e^x<br>$$</p><p>Since \\(-e^x\\) is always negative for all \\(x\\), then this means that \\(y^{\\prime}&lt;0\\) for all \\(x\\) values.</p><p><br>Therefore, the graph is ALWAYS decreasing \\(\\left(\\because y^{\\prime}&lt;0\\right)\\), or in other words, monotonically decreasing.</p>','2023-12-29 07:11:56',0,1,1,120,'easy','subtopic'),(121,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p>Suppose that the point \\(P(k, f(k))\\) lies on the curve \\(y=f(x)\\). If it is known that \\(f^{\\prime}(k)=0\\) and \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(k)&lt;0\\), which of the following statements describes the point \\(P\\) on the graph of \\(y=f(x)\\)?</p>','<p>Since \\(f^{\\prime}(k)=0\\), the point \\(P\\) will be a stationary point</p><p>Moreover, since \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(k)&lt;0\\), then we know the curve is concave down and hence, the point \\(P\\) is a maximum turning point</p>','2023-12-29 07:30:20',0,1,1,120,'easy','subtopic'),(122,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [1 mark]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text {Find } \\frac{d}{d x}\\left(\\cos ^2 x\\right)<br>$$</p>','<p>Letting \\(u=\\cos x\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\therefore \\frac{d u}{d x}=-\\sin x \\\\<br>y=u^2 \\\\<br>\\frac{d y}{d u}=2 u<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, considering chain rule:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{d y}{d u} \\times \\frac{d u}{d x} \\\\<br>&amp; =2 u \\times-\\sin x \\\\<br>&amp; =2 \\cos x \\times-\\sin x \\\\<br>&amp; =-2 \\sin x \\cos x<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-29 07:50:57',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(123,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>The velocity, \\(\\dot{x}\\), in \\(m / s\\) of an object that moves in a straight line is given by:<br>$$<br>\\dot{x}=1-2 \\sin t, \\quad \\text { for } 0 \\leq t \\leq 2 \\pi<br>$$</p><p>i. At what time(s) is the acceleration zero?<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. What is the maximum velocity of the object during this period?<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Find the first time that the object changes direction during this period<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>i. Finding the acceleration by differentiating velocity:<br>$$<br>\\ddot{x}=-2 \\cos t<br>$$</p><p>To find when acceleration is zero:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>-2 \\cos t=0 \\\\<br>\\therefore t=\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\text { OR } \\frac{3 \\pi}{2}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>ii. No calculus is actually needed for this question. Instead, we consider:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>-1 \\leq \\sin t \\leq 1 \\\\<br>-1 \\leq-\\sin t \\leq 1 \\\\<br>-2 \\leq-2 \\sin t \\leq 2 \\\\<br>-1 \\leq 1-2 \\sin t \\leq 3<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the maximum speed is \\(3 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. The object will change direction when its velocity changes sign (from positive to negative or from negative to positive). Hence, finding when velocity is equal to 0 :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>1-2 \\sin t=0 \\\\<br>\\sin t=\\frac{1}{2} \\\\<br>\\therefore t=\\frac{\\pi}{6} \\text { OR } \\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{6}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the FIRST time the object changes direction will occur when \\(t=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)</p>','2023-12-29 08:03:51',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(124,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { Given the function } y=\\frac{10}{3+2 \\cos x} \\text { in the domain } 0 \\leq x \\leq 2 \\pi<br>$$</p><p>i. Find the location and nature of all the stationary points in the domain&nbsp;</p><p>[3 marks]</p><p><br>ii. Graph the function in the given domain</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. First rewriting the equation for \\(y\\)<br>$$<br>y=10(3+2 \\cos x)^{-1}<br>$$</p><p>Then considering substitution before we differentiate:<br>Let \\(u=3+2 \\cos x\\)$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{d u}{d x} &amp; =-2 \\sin x \\\\<br>y &amp; =10 u^{-1}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore \\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{d y}{d u} \\times \\frac{d u}{d x} \\\\<br>&amp; =-10 u^{-2} \\times-2 \\sin x \\\\<br>&amp; =20 \\sin x u^{-2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{20 \\sin x}{(3+2 \\cos x)^2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>To find the stationary points, let \\(y^{\\prime}=0\\) and solve for \\(x\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\frac{20 \\sin x}{(3+2 \\cos x)^2}=0 \\\\<br>\\therefore \\sin x=0 \\\\<br>x=0, \\pi \\text { OR } 2 \\pi<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Then, creating a sign table to determine the nature of each stationary point:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:801/190;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f2773ef05e22f9e4881436c6c2d70f3c.png\" width=\"801\" height=\"190\"></figure><p>When \\(x=0\\):<br>$$<br>y=2<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the point \\((0,2)\\) is a minimum turning point<br>When \\(x=\\pi\\):<br>$$<br>y=10<br>$$Hence, the point \\((\\pi, 10)\\) is a maximum turning point<br>When \\(x=2 \\pi\\):<br>$$<br>y=2<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the point \\((2 \\pi, 2)\\) is a minimum turning point</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Sketching the graph of the function:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1920/1094;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/5ea0cae9f4d41cb049a599d76f005f73.png\" width=\"1920\" height=\"1094\"></figure><p>Note here that the 3 stationary points are plotted on the graph</p>','2023-12-29 08:35:32',0,1,5,600,'hard','subtopic'),(125,1,21,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [8 marks total]</u></p><p>Two particles \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) start moving on the \\(x\\) - axis at time \\(t=0\\). The position of particle \\(p\\) at time \\(t\\) is given by \\(x_p=-6+2 t-\\frac{1}{2} t^2\\), and the position of particle \\(q\\) at time \\(t\\) is given by \\(x_q=4 \\sin t\\)</p><p>i. Find expressions for the velocities of the two particles<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Why are there exactly two occasions, \\(t_1\\) and \\(t_2\\), when the two particles have the same velocity?<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Show that the total distance travelled by particle \\(p\\) between these two occasions is:<br>$$<br>4-2\\left(t_1+t_2\\right)+\\frac{1}{2}\\left(t_1^2+t_2^2\\right)<br>$$[3 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. Explain why the two particles can never meet<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Differentiating both expressions:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\dot{x_p}=2-t \\\\<br>\\dot{x_q}=4 \\cos t<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Considering the intersection points of the two graphs \\(\\dot{x}_p\\) and \\(\\dot{x_q}\\):</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:66.91%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1920/1097;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a684a8beb7febafe5e1eb4b481b5d6a7.png\" width=\"1920\" height=\"1097\"></figure><p>As can be seen, there will only be two intersections, so there are exactly two occasions where particles \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) have the same velocity</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Again, considering the velocity graph for particle \\(p\\):<br>$$<br>x_p=2-t<br>$$</p><p>Recall that the area underneath a velocity graph gives the displacement of a particle.</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:73.95%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1920/1097;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/cb8f23f3aaf966783aa4a78eff48ecb1.png\" width=\"1920\" height=\"1097\"></figure><p>The distance travelled is the total shaded area of both triangles. Therefore, calculating the area of the first triangle:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\text { Area } &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\text { base } \\times \\text { height } \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times\\left(2-t_1\\right) \\times\\left(2-t_1\\right) \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times\\left(4-4 t_1+t_1^2\\right)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Then calculating the area of the second triangle:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\text { Area } &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\text { base } \\times \\text { height } \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times\\left(t_2-2\\right) \\times-\\left(2-t_2\\right)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Note here that we must do \\(-\\left(2-t_2\\right)\\) for the height of this triangle because the \\(y\\) - value, \\(\\left(2-t_2\\right)$ is negative, and to make it positive (since height of a triangle must be positive), we multiply by -1.</p><p>Therefore, adding the two areas:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\frac{1}{2} \\times\\left(4-4 t_1+t_1^2\\right)+\\frac{1}{2} \\times\\left(t_2^2-4 t_2+4\\right) &amp; =2-2 t_1+\\frac{1}{2} t_1^2+\\frac{1}{2} t_2^2-2 t_2+2 \\\\<br>&amp; =4-2\\left(t_1+t_2\\right)+\\frac{1}{2}\\left(t_1^2+t_2^2\\right)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>iv. Considering the equation for \\(x_p\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>x_p &amp; =-6+2 t-\\frac{1}{2} t^2 \\\\<br>&amp; =-\\frac{1}{2}\\left[t^2-4 t+12\\right] \\\\<br>&amp; =-\\frac{1}{2}(t-2)^2-4<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>This is a concave down parabola with vertex at \\((2,-4)\\).</p><p>When \\(t=2\\) for \\(x_q\\):<br>$$<br>x_q=4 \\sin 2<br>$$</p><p>Which is a positive value, meaning it\'s above the \\(x\\) - axis.<br>Hence, the two particles will never touch because their two displacement graphs will never intersect. The two graphs are shown below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:78.93%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1920/1097;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a4d36b7b92457ef3ccecc62f86a00482.png\" width=\"1920\" height=\"1097\"></figure>','2023-12-29 09:18:17',0,1,8,900,'hard','subtopic'),(126,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>Jack tosses an unbiased coin continuously, until, for the first time, the same result occurs twice in a row (so 2 heads or 2 tails in a row).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Find the probability that the game ends within the first 3 tosses for Jack&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Jack decides that he will \"win\" if the game ends after an even number of throws, and that he will \"lose\" if the game ends after an odd number of throws. Find the probability that Jack wins the game</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. There are two possible cases for the game to end within the first 3 tosses:</p><p><strong>Case 1: </strong>First 2 flips are the same<br>The first flip can be any result, but the second flip has to be the same, which is purely a \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\) chance<br>$$<br>\\therefore P(\\text { first } 2 \\text { flips same })=\\frac{1}{2}<br>$$</p><p><strong>Case 2:</strong> First flip is not the same as the second and third flip<br>The first flip can be any result, but the second flip has to be different, which is a $\\frac{1}{2}$ chance, and the third flip has to be the same as the second flip, which is also a \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\) chance</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore P(1 \\text { st flip not the same as } 2 \\text { nd and } 3 r d) &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{4}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, adding these two cases together:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(\\text { game ends within } 3 \\text { tosses }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{2}+\\frac{1}{4} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{3}{4}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Since Jack wins if the game ends after an even number of throws:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(\\text { even number of throws }) &amp; =P(2 \\text { throws })+P(4 \\text { throws })+P(6 \\text { throws })+\\cdots \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2}+1 \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2}+1 \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2}+\\cdots \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2}+\\frac{1}{8}+\\frac{1}{32}+\\cdots<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Notice that this is a limiting sum of a geometric series, where:</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>a &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\\\<br>r &amp; =\\frac{1}{4} \\\\<br>\\therefore S_{\\infty} &amp; =\\frac{a}{1-r} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{\\frac{1}{2}}{1-\\frac{1}{4}} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{2}{3}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-30 10:00:56',0,1,4,480,'hard','subtopic'),(127,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Find the non - zero values of \\(x\\) for which the geometric series below has a limiting sum:<br>$$<br>3-9 x+27 x^2-\\cdots<br>$$</p>','<p>For a geometric series to have a limiting sum, its common ratio must have magnitude less than 1 . In this case:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>r &amp; =-\\frac{9 x}{3} \\\\<br>&amp; =-3 x<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Since we want \\(|r|&lt;1\\):</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>|-3 x|&lt;1 \\\\<br>-1&lt;-3 x&lt;1 \\\\<br>-\\frac{1}{3}&lt;x&lt;\\frac{1}{3}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>However, don\'t also forget the restriction that \\(x \\neq 0\\), because if \\(x=0\\) then \\(r=0\\), so your final answer must be:</p><p>$$<br>-\\frac{1}{3}&lt;x&lt;\\frac{1}{3}, \\quad x \\neq 0<br>$$</p><p>If you forgot the \\(x \\neq 0\\) restriction, then 1 mark will be deducted</p>','2023-12-30 11:29:26',0,1,2,240,'hard','subtopic'),(128,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks]</u></p><p>A polygon has 60 sides. The lengths of the sides, starting from the smallest, is given to be in an arithmetic sequence. The perimeter of the polygon is \\(1770 \\mathrm{cms}\\), and the length of the longest side is known to be three times the length of the shortest side.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find the lengths of the two longest sides</p>','<p>Since the perimeter of the polygon is known to be \\(1770 \\mathrm{cms}\\), then the arithmetic series of 60 terms will equal to 1770 :<br>$$<br>S_{60}=1770<br>$$</p><p>Recalling the arithmetic series formula:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>S_n=\\frac{n}{2}[2 a+(n-1) d] \\\\<br>\\therefore S_{60}=\\frac{60}{2}[2 a+59 d]=1770<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Additionally, for an arithmetic sequence:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; T_n=a+(n-1) d \\\\<br>&amp; \\therefore T_{60}=a+59 d<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Since \\(T_{60}\\) is three times the shortest length:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>a+59 d=3 a \\\\<br>\\therefore 59 d=2 a<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Substituting this into my equation for \\(S_{60}\\):<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>S_{60}=30[59 d+59 d]=1770 \\\\<br>30(118 d)=1770<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore d &amp; =\\frac{1770}{30(118)} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Since \\(a=\\frac{59}{2} d\\):</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore a &amp; =\\frac{59}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{59}{4}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Now calculating the length of the two longest sides:</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>T_{60} &amp; =a+59 d \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{59}{4}+59 \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{177}{4}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>T_{59} &amp; =a+58 d \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{59}{4}+58 \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{175}{4}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-30 11:43:43',0,1,4,420,'hard','subtopic'),(129,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p>If it is given that \\(a, b\\) and \\(c\\) are consecutive terms in a geometric sequence, where \\(a, b, c&gt;0\\), then show that \\(\\log a, \\log b\\) and \\(\\log c\\) are consecutive terms in an arithmetic sequence</p>','<p>Since \\(a, b\\) and \\(c\\) are in a geometric sequence:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>b=a r \\\\<br>c=a r^2<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Where \\(r\\) is a common ratio<br>Therefore:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\log b &amp; =\\log a r \\\\<br>&amp; =\\log a+\\log r[\\because \\text { logarithmic law }]<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\log c &amp; =\\log a r^2 \\\\<br>&amp; =\\log a+\\log r^2[\\because \\text { logarithmic law }] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\log a+2 \\log r[\\because \\text { logarithmic law }]<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, \\(\\log a, \\log b\\) and \\(\\log c\\) form an arithmetic sequence where:$$<br>\\text { first term }=\\log a<br>$$$$<br>\\text { common difference }=\\log r<br>$$</p>','2023-12-30 11:54:05',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(130,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>An infinite geometric series has a first term of 8 and a limiting sum of 12. What is the common ratio?</p>','<p>It is known that:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>a=8 \\\\<br>S_{\\infty}=\\frac{a}{1-r}=12<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; \\frac{8}{1-r}=12 \\\\<br>&amp; \\frac{8}{12}=1-r \\\\<br>&amp; \\frac{2}{3}=1-r<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore r &amp; =1-\\frac{2}{3} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{3}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-30 12:03:28',0,1,1,120,'easy','subtopic'),(131,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>The fifth term of an arithmetic sequence is -9 and the eleventh term is 24 .&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Calculate the value of the nineteenth term</p>','<p>The nth term of an arithmetic sequence is:<br>$$<br>T_n=a+(n-1) d<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, since we know the values of the fifth and eleventh terms:</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>T_5=a+4 d=-9 \\\\<br>T_{11}=a+10 d=24<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore T_{11}-T_5 &amp; =(a+10 d)-(a+4 d) \\\\<br>&amp; =6 d \\\\<br>&amp; =24--9 \\\\<br>&amp; =33<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\therefore 6 d=33<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>d &amp; =\\frac{33}{6} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{11}{2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$Since \\(d=\\frac{11}{2}\\), finding the value of \\(a\\) :<br>$$<br>a+4\\left(\\frac{11}{2}\\right)=-9<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>a+22=-9 \\\\<br>\\therefore a=-31<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, finding the value of the nineteenth term, \\(T_{19}\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>T_{19} &amp; =a+18 d \\\\<br>&amp; =-31+18\\left(\\frac{11}{2}\\right) \\\\<br>&amp; =-31+99 \\\\<br>&amp; =68<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 00:10:19',0,1,2,180,'easy','subtopic'),(132,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>An avid gardener plants turnips in rows. Their first row has 33 turnips, the second row has 38 turnips and each succeeding row has five more turnips than the previous row.</p><p>i. Calculate the number of turnips in the \\(13^{\\text {th }}\\) row<br>[2 marks]</p><p><br>ii. In this plan, which row would be the first to contain more than 300 turnips?<br>[1 mark]</p><p><br>iii. Unfortunately, the farmer finished up only having planted 21 rows. How many turnips did they plant?<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. The farmer plants turnips in rows that follow an arithmetic sequence where:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>a=33 \\text { and } d=5 \\\\<br>T_n=a+(n-1) d<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore T_{13} &amp; =33+12(5) \\\\<br>&amp; =33+60 \\\\<br>&amp; =93<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$ii. Letting the nth row be the first to contain more than 300 :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>T_n&gt;300 \\\\<br>a+(n-1) d&gt;300 \\\\<br>33+5(n-1)&gt;300 \\\\<br>33+5 n-5&gt;300 \\\\<br>5 n&gt;372 \\\\<br>n&gt;\\frac{372}{5}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$$$<br>\\therefore n&gt;74.4<br>$$</p><p>Hence, the \\(75^{\\text {th }}\\) row will be the first to contain more than 300 turnips</p><p><br>iii. Recalling the arithmetic series formula:<br>$$<br>S_n=\\frac{n}{2}[2 a+(n-1) d]<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_{21} &amp; =\\frac{21}{2}[2(33)+20(5)] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{21}{2}[66+100] \\\\<br>&amp; =1743<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 00:20:09',0,1,4,480,'medium','subtopic'),(133,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Marcus dropped a certain ball that always bounces back up to \\(\\frac{2}{5}\\) of the height of its previous bounce. After the first bounce it reaches a height of \\(140 \\mathrm{~cm}\\).&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">How high in \\(\\mathrm{cms}\\) will it reach after its fifth bounce?</p>','<p>This is a geometric sequence where \\(a=140\\) and \\(r=\\frac{2}{5}\\)<br>$$<br>\\therefore T_n=a r^{n-1}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>T_5 &amp; =a r^4 \\\\<br>&amp; =140\\left(\\frac{2}{5}\\right)^4 \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{448}{125}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 00:44:22',0,1,1,120,'easy','subtopic'),(134,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Evaluate the following expression:<br>$$<br>\\sum_{n=4}^{25}(2 n-6)<br>$$</p>','<p>Expanding the sigma notation:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\sum_{n=4}^{25}(2 n-6) &amp; =(8-6)+(10-6)+(12-6)+\\cdots+(50-6) \\\\<br>&amp; =2+4+6+\\cdots+44<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Notice that this is an arithmetic sequence, where:<br>$$<br>a=2, d=2 \\text { and } n=22<br>$$</p><p>Recall the arithmetic series formula:<br>$$<br>S_n=\\frac{n}{2}[2 a+(n-1) d]<br>$$</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore S_{22} &amp; =\\frac{22}{2}[2(2)+21(2)] \\\\<br>&amp; =11[4+42] \\\\<br>&amp; =11 \\times 46 \\\\<br>&amp; =506<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 00:50:44',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(135,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Danny planted a bed of tulips in rows on his farm. There were 15 tulips in the first row, 22 in the second row, and so on. Each succeeding row had 7 more tulips than the previous row.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">If Danny wanted to plant at least 1500 tulips, how many rows will he need?</p>','<p>This is an arithmetic sequence where:<br>$$<br>a=15, d=7<br>$$</p><p>Recalling the arithmetic sequence formula:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_n &amp; =\\frac{n}{2}[2 a+(n-1) d] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{n}{2}[30+7(n-1)] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{n}{2}[30+7 n-7] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{n}{2}[23+7 n]<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$Letting \\(S_n=1500\\) and solving for \\(n\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>1500=\\frac{n}{2}[23+7 n] \\\\<br>3000=n(23+7 n) \\\\<br>3000=23 n+7 n^2 \\\\<br>7 n^2+23 n-3000=0<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore n &amp; =\\frac{-23 \\pm \\sqrt{23^2+4(3000)(7)}}{14} \\\\<br>&amp; =19.12 \\text { ONLY }(\\because n&gt;0)<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, Danny needs to plant 20 rows to ensure he has at least 1500 tulips (must round up!)</p>','2023-12-31 03:20:59',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(136,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks total]</u></p><p>For the series \\(4-2+1-\\frac{1}{2}+\\cdots\\)</p><p>i. Find the \\(9^{\\text {th }}\\) term of the series<br>[1 mark]</p><p><br>ii. Find the limiting sum of the series<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. Notice this is a geometric sequence, where:<br>$$<br>a=4 \\text { and } r=-\\frac{1}{2}<br>$$</p><p>For the nth term:<br>$$<br>T_n=a r^{n-1}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore T_9 &amp; =a r^8 \\\\<br>&amp; =4\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^8 \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{64}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>ii. The limiting sum formula is:<br>$$<br>S_{\\infty}=\\frac{a}{1-r}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_{\\infty} &amp; =\\frac{4}{1--\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{8}{3}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 03:24:55',0,1,2,180,'easy','subtopic'),(137,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$<br>\\text { What is the limiting sum of the series } 45-15+5-\\frac{5}{3}+\\cdots ?<br>$$</p>','<p>In this geometric sequence:<br>$$<br>a=45, r=-\\frac{1}{3}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_{\\infty} &amp; =\\frac{a}{1-r} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{45}{1--\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{45}{\\frac{4}{3}} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{135}{4}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 03:39:16',0,1,1,120,'easy','subtopic'),(138,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Two employees are paid daily with two different contracts. The first employee receives a payment that is 3 times more than what he was paid the day before. The second employee receives a payment that is \\(\\$ 60\\) more than what he was paid the day before. Both employees were paid the same amount in day 1 and the same amount in total after 7 days of work.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Calculate how much the two employees got paid on day 1 , give your answer correct to the nearest cent</p>','<p>For the first employee, their pay follows a geometric sequence where:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\text { first payment }=a \\\\<br>r=3<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Their total pay after 7 days will be:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; S_n=\\frac{a\\left(r^n-1\\right)}{r-1} \\\\<br>&amp; S_7=\\frac{a\\left(3^7-1\\right)}{2}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$For the second employee, their pay follows an arithmetic sequence where:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\text { first payment }=a \\\\<br>d=60<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Their total pay after 7 days will be:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_n= &amp; \\frac{n}{2}[2 a+(n-1) d] \\\\<br>\\therefore S_7 &amp; =\\frac{7}{2}[2 a+6(60)] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{7}{2}[2 a+360]<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$Since their total pay after 7 days is equal:<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\frac{a\\left(3^7-1\\right)}{2}=\\frac{7}{2}[2 a+360] \\\\<br>1093 a=7 a+1260 \\\\<br>1086 a=1260<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore a &amp; =\\frac{1260}{1086} \\\\<br>&amp; \\approx \\$ 1.16 \\text { (rounded to nearest cent) }<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 03:47:23',0,1,3,420,'hard','subtopic'),(139,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>In an arithmetic series, the eight term is \\(T_8=150\\), and the sum of the first fourteen terms is \\(S_{14}=546\\).&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find the value of the twentieth term, \\(T_{20}\\)</p>','<p>The nth term of an arithmetic series can be given as:<br>$$<br>T_n=a+(n-1) d<br>$$</p><p>The eighth term is therefore:<br>$$<br>T_8=150=a+7 d(1)<br>$$</p><p>The sum of \\(n\\) terms in an arithmetic series is:<br>$$<br>S_n=\\frac{n}{2}[2 a+(n-1) d]<br>$$</p><p>Therefore, the sum of the first fourteen terms is:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_{14}=546 &amp; =\\frac{14}{2}[2 a+13 d] \\\\<br>&amp; =7[2 a+13 d]<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\therefore 78=2 a+13 d(2)<br>$$</p><p>From equation (1):<br>$$<br>a=150-7 d<br>$$</p><p>Substituting this into equation (2):<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>78 &amp; =2(150-7 d)+13 d \\\\<br>&amp; =300-14 d+13 d \\\\<br>&amp; =300-d<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\therefore d=222 \\\\<br>\\therefore a=150-7(222) \\\\<br>=-1404<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$Therefore, calculating the value of \\(T_{20}\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>T_{20} &amp; =a+19 d \\\\<br>&amp; =-1404+19(222) \\\\<br>&amp; =2814<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 04:03:51',0,1,3,420,'medium','subtopic'),(140,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">For what values of \\(k\\) will the geometric series \\(1+2 k^2+4 k^4+\\cdots\\) have a limiting sum?</p>','<p>The common ratio here is:<br>$$<br>r=2 k^2<br>$$</p><p>In order for a geometric sequence to have a limiting sum, \\(|r|&lt;1\\)<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\therefore\\left|2 k^2\\right|&lt;1 \\\\<br>-1&lt;2 k^2&lt;1 \\\\<br>-\\frac{1}{2}&lt;k^2&lt;\\frac{1}{2}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p><p>Since a square number cannot be negative, \\(k^2&gt;0\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>0&lt;k^2&lt;\\frac{1}{2} \\\\<br>\\therefore-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}&lt;k&lt;\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 04:08:39',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(141,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>The sum to nth term of a series is given by the following:<br>$$<br>S_n=3 n^2-2 n+1<br>$$</p><p>i. Use the formula \\(T_n=S_n-S_{n-1}\\) to show that the \\(n\\)th term of the series is given by<br>$$<br>T_n=6 n-5<br>$$[2 marks]</p><p><br>ii. It can be shown that the sum of this series is actually given by \\(S_n=C+T_1+\\) \\(T_2+T_3+\\cdots+T_n\\) where \\(C\\) is a constant (do NOT prove this formula). Find the value of \\(C\\)<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Considering \\(S_{n-1}\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_{n-1} &amp; =3(n-1)^2-2(n-1)+1 \\\\<br>&amp; =3\\left(n^2-2 n+1\\right)-2 n+2+1 \\\\<br>&amp; =3 n^2-6 n+3-2 n+3 \\\\<br>&amp; =3 n^2-8 n+6<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_n-S_{n-1} &amp; =3 n^2-2 n+1-\\left(3 n^2-8 n+6\\right) \\\\<br>&amp; =3 n^2-2 n+1-3 n^2+8 n-6 \\\\<br>&amp; =6 n-5<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$<br>ii. Since \\(T_n=6 n-5\\) [from part i]<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore T_1 &amp; =6-5 \\\\<br>&amp; =1<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore T_2 &amp; =12-5 \\\\<br>&amp; =7 \\\\<br>\\therefore T_3 &amp; =18-5 \\\\<br>&amp; =13<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Calculating \\(S_2\\):</p><p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_2 &amp; =3(2)^2-2(2)+1 \\\\<br>&amp; =12-4+1 \\\\<br>&amp; =9<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Also:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>S_2 &amp; =C+T_1+T_2 \\\\<br>&amp; =C+1+7 \\\\<br>&amp; =C+8<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{gathered}<br>\\therefore 9=C+8 \\\\<br>C=1<br>\\end{gathered}<br>$$</p>','2023-12-31 10:31:26',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(142,1,30,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>The triangle \\(\\mathrm{ABC}\\) has right angle at \\(B, \\angle B A C=\\theta\\) and \\(A B=6\\), as shown in the diagram below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:36.81%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:2805/1540;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f1c0de36cd6e34e4d3e14b16aa4853a9.png\" width=\"2805\" height=\"1540\"></figure><p>The line \\(\\mathrm{BD}\\) is drawn perpendicular to \\(\\mathrm{AC}\\) and the line \\(\\mathrm{DE}\\) is drawn perpendicular to \\(B C\\). This process continues indefinitely, as shown in the diagram. It may be assumed that other angles are equal to \\(\\theta\\) without proof</p><p><br>i. Find the length of the interval \\(B D\\), and hence show that the length of the interval \\(\\mathrm{EF}\\) is \\(6 \\sin ^3 \\theta\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p><br>ii. Show that the limiting sum \\(B D+E F+G H+\\cdots\\) is given by \\(6 \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta\\)<br>[3 marks]</p>','<p>i. Considering triangle \\(\\mathrm{ABD}\\) :<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; \\sin \\theta=\\frac{B D}{6} \\\\<br>\\therefore &amp; BD=6 \\sin \\theta<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$Therefore, for triangle DEB now:<br>$$<br>\\angle D B E=\\theta<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\sin \\theta &amp; =\\frac{D E}{B D} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{D E}{6 \\sin \\theta}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\therefore D E=6 \\sin ^2 \\theta<br>$$Considering triangle DEF now:<br>$$<br>\\angle F D E=\\theta<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\sin \\theta &amp; =\\frac{E F}{D E} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{E F}{6 \\sin ^2 \\theta}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\therefore E F=6 \\sin ^3 \\theta<br>$$</p><p><br>ii. The sum:$$<br>B D+E F+G H+\\cdots<br>$$</p><p>Is a geometric series where:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp; a=6 \\sin \\theta \\\\<br>&amp; r=\\sin ^2 \\theta<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>\\therefore S_{\\infty} &amp; =\\frac{a}{1-r} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{6 \\sin \\theta}{1-\\sin ^2 \\theta} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{6 \\sin \\theta}{\\cos ^2 \\theta}\\left[\\because \\sin ^2 \\theta+\\cos ^2 \\theta=1\\right] \\\\<br>&amp; =6 \\times \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} \\times \\frac{1}{\\cos \\theta} \\\\<br>&amp; =6 \\tan \\theta \\sec \\theta<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p><p>Hence, limiting sum is \\(6 \\tan \\theta \\sec \\theta\\)</p>','2023-12-31 10:44:38',0,1,5,600,'hard','subtopic'),(143,1,33,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The value of the limit shown below will be: $$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x^2-5}{x+2} $$</p>','<p>Solution:<br>For these basic limit questions, since we can\'t factorise or simplify our expression, we can directly just apply our limit: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x^2-5}{x+2} &amp; =\\frac{0-5}{0+2} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{5}{2} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-01 03:45:00',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(144,1,33,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { The limit of } \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{3 x(x-2)}{x-2} \\text { is: } $$</p>','<p>Solution:<br>First simplifying the limit: $$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{3 x(x-2)}{x-2}=\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{3 x}{1} $$ Then applying our limit: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} 3 x &amp; =3 \\times 2 \\\\ &amp; =6 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-01 03:56:11',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(145,1,33,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>\\(\\text{Evalute the limit:}\\)$$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow -3} \\frac{x^2-9}{x+3} $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Before applying our limit, we should factorise and simplify the expression: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow -3} \\frac{x^2-9}{x+3} &amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow -3} \\frac{(x+3)(x-3)}{x+3} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow -3} x-3 \\end{aligned} $$ Now applying the limit as \\(x \\rightarrow -3\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\lim _{x \\rightarrow -3} x-3 &amp; =-3-3 \\\\ &amp; =-6&nbsp;\\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-04 23:15:23',0,1,2,120,'medium','subtopic'),(146,1,33,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Evaluate } \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{x^3-27}{x^2-9} $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Factorising the numerator and denominator first: $$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{x^3-27}{x^2-9}=\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{(x-3)\\left(x^2+3 x+9\\right)}{(x-3)(x+3)} $$ We can then simplify our limit: $$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{(x-3)\\left(x^2+3 x+9\\right)}{(x-3)(x+3)}=\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{\\left(x^2+3 x+9\\right)}{(x+3)} $$ Before finally applying our limit: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{\\left(x^2+3 x+9\\right)}{(x+3)} &amp; =\\frac{3^2+3(3)+9}{3+3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{9+9+9}{6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{27}{6} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-04 23:24:29',0,1,2,180,'hard','subtopic'),(147,1,33,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Evaluate } \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x-2}{2 x^2-x-6} $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Factorising the denominator \\(2 x^2-x-6\\) first using cross multiplication method: $$ \\begin{array}{cc} 2 &amp; 3 \\\\ 1 &amp; -2 \\end{array} $$$$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 2 x^2-x-6=(2 x+3)(x-2) \\\\ \\therefore \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x-2}{2 x^2-x-6}=\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x-2}{(2 x+3)(x-2)} \\end{gathered} $$ We can then simplify our limit: $$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x-2}{(2 x+3)(x-2)}=\\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{1}{(2 x+3)} $$ Before finally applying our limit: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{1}{(2 x+3)} &amp; =\\frac{1}{2(2)+3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{7} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-04 23:27:53',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(148,1,33,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>\\(\\text{Evaluate the limit:}\\)<br>$$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow-1} \\frac{2(x+1)\\left(x^2-1\\right)}{(x+1)^2} $$</p>','<p>Solution:<br>First applying the difference of squares to the numerator: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow-1} \\frac{2(x+1)\\left(x^2-1\\right)}{(x+1)^2} &amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow-1} \\frac{2(x+1)(x+1)(x-1)}{(x+1)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow-1} \\frac{2(x+1)^2(x-1)}{(x+1)^2} \\end{aligned} $$ Then simplifying the limit: $$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow-1} \\frac{2(x+1)^2(x-1)}{(x+1)^2}=\\lim _{x \\rightarrow-1} 2(x-1) $$ Finally, applying our limit: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow-1} 2(x-1) &amp; =2(-1-1) \\\\ &amp; =-4&nbsp;\\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-04 23:37:14',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(149,1,33,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Evaluate} \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{16-(4-h)^2}{h} $$</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Expanding the numerator before simplifying: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{16-(4-h)^2}{h} &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{16-\\left(16-8 h+h^2\\right)}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{16-16+8 h-h^2}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{8 h-h^2}{h} \\end{aligned} $$ Then factorising out \\(h\\) to simplify: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{8 h-h^2}{h} &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{h(8-h)}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} 8-h \\end{aligned} $$ Finally applying our limit: $$ \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} 8-h=8 $$</p>','2024-01-04 23:41:25',0,1,2,180,'hard','subtopic'),(150,1,34,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the correct expression for differentiating \\(f(x)=x^2-4 x\\) from first principles?</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Recalling the first principles formula: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{gathered} f(x)=x^2-4 x \\\\ f(x+h)=(x+h)^2-4(x+h) \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, substituting this into first principles: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{(x+h)^2-4(x+h)-\\left(x^2-4 x\\right)}{h} $$</p>','2024-01-04 23:51:54',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(151,1,34,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the correct expression for differentiating \\(f(x)=\\frac{2}{x}\\) from first principles?</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Recalling the first principles formula: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{gathered} f(x)=\\frac{2}{x} \\\\ f(x+h)=\\frac{2}{x+h} \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, substituting this into first principles: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{2}{x+h}-\\frac{2}{x}}{h} $$</p>','2024-01-05 00:09:17',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(152,1,34,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Given that } f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\text {, differentiate } y=\\frac{3}{x} \\text { from first principles } $$</p>','<p>First off, we determine that: $$ \\begin{aligned} f(x) &amp; =\\frac{3}{x} \\\\ f(x+h) &amp; =\\frac{3}{x+h} \\end{aligned} $$ Then substituting this into the given formula, we aim to simplify and eventually cancel out the \\(h\\) on the denominator: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{3}{x+h}-\\frac{3}{x}}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{3 x-3(x+h)}{x(x+h)}}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{3 x-3 x-3 h}{h x(x+h)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-3 h}{x h(x+h)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-3}{x(x+h)} \\end{aligned} $$ Finally, applying our limit: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-3}{x(x+h)}=-\\frac{3}{x^2} \\\\ \\therefore y^{\\prime}=-\\frac{3}{x^2} \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-05 00:16:12',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(153,1,34,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Differentiate } f(x)=x^2-3 x \\text { from first principles } $$</p>','<p>Recalling the first principles formula: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} $$ Since $f(x)=x^2-3 x$ $$ \\begin{aligned} f(x+h) &amp; =(x+h)^2-3(x+h) \\\\ &amp; =x^2+2 x h+h^2-3 x-3 h \\end{aligned} $$ Substituting this into the formula: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\left(x^2+2 x h+h^2-3 x-3 h\\right)-\\left(x^2-3 x\\right)}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x^2+2 x h+h^2-3 x-3 h-x^2+3 x}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{2 x h+h^2-3 h}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{h(2 x+h-3)}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0}(2 x+h-3) \\end{aligned} $$ Then finally applying our limit: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0}(2 x+h-3)=2 x-3 \\\\ \\therefore f^{\\prime}(x)=2 x-3 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-05 00:25:05',0,1,2,240,'hard','subtopic'),(154,1,34,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>A function is given by \\(f(x)=2 x^2+3 x\\)</p><p>i. Determine whether the function is odd, even or neither, providing reasoning for your answer&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p><br>ii. Show that \\(f(x+h)=2 x^2+4 x h+2 h^2+3 x+3 h\\)</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p><br>iii. Hence, find \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\) from first principles</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Determining the expression for \\(f(-x)\\) : $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =2(-x)^2+3(-x) \\\\ &amp; =2 x^2-3 x \\end{aligned} $$ Determining the expression for \\(-f(x)\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} -f(x) &amp; =-\\left(2 x^2+3 x\\right) \\\\ &amp; =-2 x^2-3 x \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(f(x) \\neq f(-x), f(x)\\) is NOT even&nbsp;<br>Since \\(f(-x) \\neq-f(x), f(x)\\) is NOT odd&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, we can determine that \\(f(x)\\) is neither even nor odd</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Since \\(f(x)=2 x^2+3 x\\) : $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore f(x+h) &amp; =2(x+h)^2+3(x+h) \\\\ &amp; =2\\left(x^2+2 x h+h^2\\right)+3 x+3 h \\\\ &amp; =2 x^2+4 x h+2 h^2+3 x+3 h \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Substituting our expressions for \\(f(x)\\) and \\(f(x+h)\\) into the first principles formula in order to simplify our expression and cancel out the \\(h\\) on the denominator: $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\left(2 x^2+4 x h+2 h^2+3 x+3 h\\right)-\\left(2 x^2+3 x\\right)}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{2 x^2+4 x h+2 h^2+3 x+3 h-2 x^2-3 x}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{4 x h+2 h^2+3 h}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{h(4 x+2 h+3)}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0}(4 x+2 h+3) \\end{aligned} $$ Finally, applying our limit: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0}(4 x+2 h+3)=4 x+3 \\\\ \\therefore f^{\\prime}(x)=4 x+3 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-05 00:32:44',0,1,5,600,'hard','subtopic'),(155,1,34,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Differentiate } y=\\frac{1}{3 x^2} \\text { from first principles } $$</p>','<p>First off, we determine that: $$ f(x)=\\frac{1}{3 x^2} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned} f(x+h) &amp; =\\frac{1}{3(x+h)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3\\left(x^2+2 x h+h^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2} \\end{aligned} $$ Then substituting this into the given formula, we aim to simplify and eventually cancel out the \\(h\\) on the denominator: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{1}{3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2}-\\frac{1}{3 x^2}}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{3 x^2-\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)}{3 x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)}}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{3 x^2-3 x^2-6 x h-3 h^2}{3 h x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-6 x h-3 h^2}{3 h x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-3 h(2 x+h)}{3 h x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-(2 x+h)}{x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} \\end{aligned} $$Finally, applying our limit: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-(2 x+h)}{x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} &amp; =\\frac{-(2 x+0)}{x^2\\left(3 x^2+0+0\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{2 x}{3 x^4} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{2}{3 x^3} \\\\ \\therefore y^{\\prime}=- &amp; \\frac{2}{3 x^3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-05 00:54:50',0,1,3,300,'hard','subtopic'),(156,1,35,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the derivative of \\(y=x^5\\)?</p>','<p>$$ y=x^5 $$ Using the fact that if \\(y=x^n, y^{\\prime}=n x^{n-1}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =5 x^{5-1} \\\\ &amp; =5 x^4 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 05:39:15',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(157,1,35,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { If } y=-\\frac{1}{2} x^3 \\text {, then the value of } \\frac{d y}{d x} \\text { will be? } $$</p>','<p>$$ y=-\\frac{1}{2} x^3 $$ Given the fact that if \\(y=a x^n, \\frac{d y}{d x}=a \\cdot n x^{n-1}\\), where \\(a\\) is a constant: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =-\\frac{1}{2} \\cdot 3 x^2 \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{3}{2} x^2 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 05:52:17',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(158,1,35,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { The derivative of } y=\\sqrt{x} \\text { is: } $$</p>','<p>First expressing \\(y\\) with fractional indices: $$ y=x^{\\frac{1}{2}} $$ Then differentiating using the fact that if \\(y=x^n, y^{\\prime}=n x^{n-1}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} x^{\\frac{1}{2}-1} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} x^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2 \\sqrt{x}} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 05:56:30',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(160,1,35,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Given that } f(x)=x^2-3 x+2 \\text {, what is the expression for } f^{\\prime}(x) \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Given the fact that if \\(y=x^n, y^{\\prime}=n x^{n-1}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =2 x-3+0(\\text { derivative of a constant is } 0) \\\\ &amp; =2 x-3 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 06:10:13',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(163,1,35,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Differentiate } y=(x-3)(x+1) $$</p>','<p>First expanding \\(y\\):: $$ \\begin{aligned} y &amp; =x^2+x-3 x-3 \\\\ &amp; =x^2-2 x-3 \\end{aligned} $$ Then, differentiating by using the fact that if \\(y=x^n, y^{\\prime}=n x^{n-1}\\): $$ y^{\\prime}=2 x-2 $$</p>','2024-01-06 06:37:35',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(164,1,35,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Find the derivative of } y=\\frac{x^2-1}{x-1} $$</p>','<p>First factorising \\(y\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y &amp; =\\frac{(x+1)(x-1)}{x-1} \\\\ &amp; =x+1 \\end{aligned} $$ Then, differentiating by using the fact that if \\(y=x^n, y^{\\prime}=n x^{n-1}\\): $$y=1$$</p>','2024-01-06 06:41:18',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(165,1,35,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Given that } v=3 \\sqrt{t}-\\sqrt[3]{t} \\text {, find the expression for } \\frac{d v}{d t} \\text {: } $$</p>','<p>First express \\(v\\) in indices form: $$ v=3 t^{\\frac{1}{2}}-t^{\\frac{1}{3}} $$ Then, differentiating by using the fact that if \\(v=t^n, \\frac{d v}{d t}=n t^{n-1}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d v}{d t} &amp; =3 \\cdot \\frac{1}{2} t^{\\frac{1}{2}-1}-\\frac{1}{3} t^{\\frac{1}{3}-1} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3}{2} t^{-\\frac{1}{2}}-\\frac{1}{3} t^{-\\frac{2}{3}} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 06:44:13',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(166,1,36,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Given that } f(x)=(3 x-5)^4 \\text {, what is the expression for } f^{\\prime}(x) \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Recalling the chain rule:&nbsp;</p><p>If \\(f(x)=(a x+b)^n\\), then \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=a \\cdot n(a x+b)^{n-1}\\)&nbsp;</p><p>Then therefore: $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =3 \\cdot 4(3 x-5)^{4-1} \\\\ &amp; =12(3 x-5)^3 \\\\ &amp;&nbsp; \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 06:53:32',0,1,1,120,'easy','subtopic'),(167,1,36,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { If } y=x^3(x-2)^2, \\text { then } \\frac{d y}{d x}=&nbsp;? $$</p>','<p>Using the product rule \\((u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(x^3(x-2)^2\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\left(x^3\\right)^{\\prime}(x-2)^2+\\left((x-2)^2\\right)^{\\prime} x^3 \\\\ &amp; =3 x^2(x-2)^2+2(x-2) x^3 \\\\ &amp; =3 x^2(x-2)^2+2 x^3(x-2) \\\\ &amp; =x^2(x-2)(3(x-2)+2x) \\\\ &amp; =x^2(x-2)(3 x-6+2x) \\\\ &amp; =x^2(x-2)(5&nbsp;x-6) \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 06:59:04',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(168,1,36,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { If } f(x)=(x-3)^4(x+1)^5 \\text {, then find the expression for } f^{\\prime}(x) $$</p>','<p>Using the product rule \\((u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\left((x-3)^4\\right)^{\\prime}(x+1)^5+\\left((x+1)^5\\right)^{\\prime}(x-3)^4 \\\\ &amp; =4(x-3)^3(x+1)^5+5(x+1)^4(x-3)^4 \\\\ &amp; =(x-3)^3(x+1)^4(4(x+1)+5(x-3)) \\\\ &amp; =(x-3)^3(x+1)^4(4 x+4+5 x-15) \\\\ &amp; =(x-3)^3(x+1)^4(9 x-11) \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 09:33:15',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(169,1,36,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Which of the following is the derivative of } y=\\frac{4 x^3}{x+1} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Using the quotient rule \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(\\frac{4 x^3}{x+1}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{\\left(4 x^3\\right)^{\\prime}(x+1)-(x+1)^{\\prime} 4 x^3}{(x+1)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{12 x^2(x+1)-4 x^3}{(x+1)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{12 x^3+12 x^2-4 x^3}{(x+1)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{8 x^3+12 x^2}{(x+1)^2} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 09:35:42',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(170,1,36,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Given that } g(x)=\\frac{(x+4)^4}{(x-1)^2} \\text {, which of the following is the expression for } g^{\\prime}(x) \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Using the quotient rule \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} g^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\frac{\\left((x+4)^4\\right)^{\\prime}(x-1)^2-\\left((x-1)^2\\right)^{\\prime}(x+4)^4}{(x-1)^4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{4(x+4)^3(x-1)^2-2(x-1)(x+4)^4}{(x-1)^4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{(x+4)^3(x-1)[4(x-1)-2(x+4)]}{(x-1)^4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{(x+4)^3(x-1)[4 x-4-2 x-8]}{(x-1)^4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{(x+4)^3(x-1)[2 x-12]}{(x-1)^4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2(x+4)^3(x-1)(x-6)}{(x-1)^4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2(x+4)^3(x-6)}{(x-1)^3}\\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 09:40:22',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(171,1,36,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { For the function } f(x)=\\left(x^3+x\\right)^4 \\text {, which of the following is } f^{\\prime}(x) \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Doing this question by substitution:&nbsp;</p><p>Let \\(u=x^3+x\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} \\frac{d u}{d x}=3 x^2+1 \\\\ y=f(x)=u^4 \\\\ \\frac{d y}{d u}=4 u^3 \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, by the chain rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d y}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{d y}{d u} \\times \\frac{d u}{d x} \\\\ &amp; =4 u^3 \\times\\left(3 x^2+1\\right) \\\\ &amp; =4\\left(3 x^2+1\\right) u^3 \\\\ &amp; =4\\left(3 x^2+1\\right)\\left(x^3+x\\right)^3 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 09:43:24',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(172,1,36,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { What is the derivative of } y=(4 x-3)^5(x-2)^2 \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Using the product rule \\((u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u\\) $$ y^{\\prime}=\\left((4 x-3)^5\\right)^{\\prime}(x-2)^2+\\left((x-2)^2\\right)^{\\prime}(4 x-3)^5 $$ Now using the chain rule formula for \\(y=(a x+b)^n\\), we know that \\(y^{\\prime}=a n(a x+b)^{n-1}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =4 \\cdot 5(4 x-3)^4(x-2)^2+2(x-2)(4 x-3)^5 \\\\ &amp; =20(4 x-3)^4(x-2)^2+2(x-2)(4 x-3)^5 \\\\ &amp; =(x-2)(4 x-3)^4[20(x-2)+2(4 x-3)] \\\\ &amp; =(x-2)(4 x-3)^4[20 x-40+8 x-6] \\\\ &amp; =(x-2)(4 x-3)^4[28 x-46] \\end{aligned} $$ Note that this question is tricky because it tests both chain rule and product rule!</p>','2024-01-06 09:45:30',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(173,1,36,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { What is the derivative of } f(x)=\\frac{\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^3} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Using the quotient rule \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}\\): $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\frac{\\left(\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2\\right)^{\\prime}(2 x-1)^3-\\left((2 x-1)^3\\right)^{\\prime}\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^6} $$ Remember that for chain rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\left(\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2\\right)^{\\prime}=2(2 x-1)\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^1 \\\\ &amp; \\left((2 x-1)^3\\right)^{\\prime}=2 \\cdot 3(2 x-1)^2=6(2 x-1)^2 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\frac{2(2 x-1)\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)(2 x-1)^3-6(2 x-1)^2\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^6} \\\\ f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\frac{2\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)(2 x-1)^4-6(2 x-1)^2\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^6} \\end{aligned} $$ No need to simplify or factorise any further since this is one of our answer options! Note that this question is tricky because it tests both chain rule and quotient rule!</p>','2024-01-06 09:47:41',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(174,1,37,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the gradient of the tangent to \\(y=x^3-x^2+1\\) when the \\(x\\) - coordinate is 3?</p>','<p>For tangent questions, we first differentiate&nbsp;\\(y\\) to find \\(y^{\\prime}\\): $$ y^{\\prime}=3 x^2-2 x $$ Then, finding the gradient of the tangent when \\(x=3\\) by substituting into \\(y^{\\prime}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} m &amp; =3(3)^2-2(3) \\\\ &amp; =27-6 \\\\ &amp; =21 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 09:54:36',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(175,1,37,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>For the function \\(f(x)=\\frac{x^3}{3}-6 x^2+3 x+3\\), the gradient is \\(-8\\) at two points. What are the values of the \\(x\\) - coordinates at these points?&nbsp;</p>','<p>For gradient questions, differentiate first: $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =3 \\times \\frac{x^2}{3}-2 \\times 6 x+3 \\\\ &amp; =x^2-12 x+3 \\end{aligned} $$ Next, letting \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=-8\\) and solving for \\(x\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} -8=x^2-12 x+3 \\\\ x^2-12 x+11=0 \\\\ (x-11)(x-1)=0 \\\\ \\therefore x=1 \\text { OR } 11 \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, the answer is \\(1\\) or \\(11\\)</p>','2024-01-06 09:57:17',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(177,1,37,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { At what angle is the line } y=-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} x+2 \\text { inclined to the positive side of the } x-\\text { axis? } $$</p>','<p>Since the line is in the form \\(y=m x+b\\), the gradient of the line is: $$ m=-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} $$ Then, using the equation \\(m=\\tan \\theta\\) to find the angle: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; -\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}=\\tan \\theta \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\theta=180^{\\circ}-30^{\\circ}[2 \\text { nd quadrant angle } \\because \\tan \\theta&lt;0] \\\\ &amp; =150^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 10:03:08',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(178,1,37,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the angle of inclination of the line \\(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} x-y+3 \\sqrt{3}=0\\) with respect to the positive \\(x\\) - axis ?</p>','<p>Rearranging the equation into the form \\(y=m x+b\\): $$ y=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} x+3 \\sqrt{3} $$ Hence, the gradient of the line is \\(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\)&nbsp;</p><p>Since \\(m=\\tan \\theta\\), where \\(\\theta\\) is the angle of inclination: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}=\\tan \\theta \\\\ \\therefore \\theta=30^{\\circ}&nbsp;\\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-06 10:08:16',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(179,1,37,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Find the equation of the tangent to the curve } y=2 x^3-x+3 \\text { at } x=1$$</p>','<p>For tangent questions, we differentiate first: $$ y^{\\prime}=6 x^2-1 $$ When \\(x=1\\), the gradient is: $$ m=6(1)^2-1=5 $$ When \\(x=1, y=2(1)^3-1+3=4\\)</p><p>Finally using the point - gradient formula to find the equation of the tangent: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; y-y_1=m\\left(x-x_1\\right) \\\\ &amp; y-4=5(x-1) \\\\ &amp; y-4=5 x-5 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore y=5 x-1 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-06 10:18:46',0,1,2,180,'hard','subtopic'),(180,1,38,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) is shown below. For which interval is \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0\\)?</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:55.23%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1360/715;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e2ef57900bbbc36472aa5062bf60e6c5.png\" width=\"1360\" height=\"715\"></figure>','<p>Since we are looking for when \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0\\), this is when the graph is increasing.&nbsp;<br><br>Notice that the graph is increasing when \\(x&lt;-2\\) and when \\(x&gt;4\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, in interval notation this may be expressed as: $$ (-\\infty,-2) \\cup(4, \\infty) $$</p>','2024-01-06 12:38:13',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(181,1,38,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given \\(f(x)=x^2+6 x\\), for what values of \\(x\\) is \\(f(x)\\) increasing?</p>','<p>There are two methods we may complete this question:&nbsp;<br><br><strong><u>Method 1: Using Differentiation&nbsp;</u></strong><br><br>Differentiating \\(f(x)\\): $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=2 x+6 $$ If \\(f(x)\\) is increasing, then \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0\\). Therefore, to find the domain for \\(x\\): $$ f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0 $$$$ \\begin{gathered} 2 x+6&gt;0 \\\\ 2 x&gt;-6 \\\\ \\therefore x&gt;-3 \\end{gathered} $$<strong><u>Method 2: Sketching the graph</u></strong>&nbsp;<br>Sketching the parabola \\(y=x^2+6 x=x(x+6)\\) with \\(x\\)-intercepts 0 and -6:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:420/450;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/6b78af4436d799882762be5cd54f5c7b.png\" width=\"420\" height=\"450\"></figure><p>The vertex of the parabola exists at \\(x=-3\\). As can be seen from the graph, the part of the graph to the right of the vertex is increasing.&nbsp;<br><br>In other words, the graph is increasing for the domain \\(x&gt;-3\\)</p>','2024-01-06 12:41:33',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(182,1,38,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>The following graph shows the function \\(y=f(x)\\) with a horizontal asymptote at \\(y=1\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:552/271;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/6fc3bc752fe8ad1e73a4c4b09e72e55d.png\" width=\"552\" height=\"271\"></figure><p>Hence, sketch the graph of \\(y=f^{\\prime}(x)\\)</p>','<p>There is a visible stationary point at \\(x=0\\), and the graph for \\(f(x)\\) is becoming increasing flat as \\(x \\rightarrow \\infty\\) and \\(x \\rightarrow-\\infty\\), which means that \\(f^{\\prime}(x) \\rightarrow 0\\) as \\(x \\rightarrow \\infty\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Moreover, on the left half of the graph \\(f(x)\\) is increasing so \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0\\) and on the right half \\(f(x)\\) is decreasing so \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&lt;0\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, graphically \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\) looks like:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:475/430;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/af74f5c727cb8fdb8edf112363f3799e.png\" width=\"475\" height=\"430\"></figure>','2024-01-06 12:45:38',0,1,2,180,'hard','subtopic'),(183,1,39,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A chocolate factory\'s production each day is modelled by the equation: $$ N=3 t^2+2 t+2 $$ Where \\(N\\) is the amount of chocolate produced and $t$ is the number of hours after the factory opens each day.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">At what rate is the factory producing chocolate 5 hours after opening today?</p>','<p>When we think of rates, first consider the derivative: $$ \\frac{d N}{d t}=6 t+2 $$ Hence, five hours after opening when \\(t=5\\), the rate or \\(\\frac{d N}{d t}\\) will equal: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d N}{d t} &amp; =6(5)+2 \\\\ &amp; =32 \\end{aligned} $$ Thus, the factor will be producing 32 chocolates per hour, 5 hours after opening.</p>','2024-01-07 00:32:17',0,1,1,120,'easy','subtopic'),(184,1,39,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>A water tank is holding \\(9025 L\\) of water. The water is slowly drained out of the tank, such that the following equation predicts that the volume, \\(V\\) litres, or water that will remain in the tank after \\(t\\) minutes is given by: $$ V=9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 $$i. How long until the tank is empty?&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]<br><br>ii. What volume of water is predicted to remain after half an hour?&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]<br><br>iii. At what rate does the model predict that the water will be draining from the tank after 40 minutes?<br>[2 marks]</p><p><br>iv. At what time will the water drain from the tank the fastest?&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. The tank is empty when \\(V=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} 0= &amp; 9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; \\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)=0 \\\\ &amp; 1=\\frac{t}{95} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=95 \\end{aligned} $$ It therefore takes 95 minutes for the tank to be empty<br><br>ii. When \\(t=30\\), finding the value of \\(V\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} V &amp; =9025\\left(1-\\frac{30}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; =9025\\left(\\frac{65}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; =4225 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, there will be \\(4225 \\mathrm{~L}\\) of water left in the tank after 30 minutes<br><br>iii. Considering the first derivative of \\(V\\) in rate of change: $$ \\begin{aligned} V &amp; =9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ V^{\\prime} &amp; =9025 \\times 2 \\times-\\frac{1}{95}\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right) \\text { [Chain Rule] } \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; =-190\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =-190+2 t \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, to find the rate it is draining when \\(t=40\\), sub into \\(V^{\\prime}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} V^{\\prime} &amp; =-190+2(40) \\\\ &amp; =-110 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the rate of drainage should be \\(110 \\mathrm{~L} / \\mathrm{min}\\) when \\(t=40\\). Note that we do not include the negative sign since drainage already represents a decrease in volume.<br><br>iv. The question is asking us when the water drains from the tank the fastest. In other words, we are finding when \\(V^{\\prime}\\) has the most negative value [Since draining is a rate of decrease, it is negative and we want our value to be as negative as possible] $$ V^{\\prime}=-190+2 t $$ Since \\(V^{\\prime}\\) is a straight line, it is most negative when \\(t=0\\), where: $$ V^{\\prime}=-190+0=-190 $$ Hence, drainage is fastest when \\(t=0\\)<br><strong>Tricky question!</strong></p>','2024-01-07 04:11:35',0,1,5,540,'hard','subtopic'),(185,1,39,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>A large fishbowl which contains \\(L\\) litres of dirty fish water is being drained. The amount of water in the bowl after \\(t\\) minutes is given by: $$ L=50(15-t)^2 $$</p><p>&nbsp;i. At what rate is the water draining out of the fishbowl after 6 minutes? &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; [2 marks]&nbsp;</p><p><br>ii. How long until the tank is completely empty?&nbsp;<br>[ 1 mark]</p>','<p>i. To find the rate of drainage, differentiate first: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; L=50\\left(225-30 t+t^2\\right) \\\\ &amp; L=11250-1500 t+50 t^2 \\\\ &amp; L^{\\prime}=-1500+100 t \\end{aligned} $$ When \\(t=6\\), finding the value of \\(L^{\\prime}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} L^{\\prime} &amp; =-1500+100(6) \\\\ &amp; =-900 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the rate that the water is draining out when \\(t=6\\) is \\(900 \\mathrm{~L} / \\mathrm{min}\\)<br><br>ii. For \\(L=0\\): $$ L=50(15-t)^2=0 $$ This occurs when \\(t=15\\). Hence, it takes 15 minutes for the tank to be empty</p>','2024-01-07 04:30:40',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(186,1,39,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A swimming pool is being emptied for renovations. The quantity of water, \\(Q\\) litres, remaining in the pool at the time \\(t\\) minutes after it starts being drained, is given by: $$ Q(t)=3000(20-t)^2, t \\geq 0 $$</p><p>i. How long before half of the water is removed from the pool? Give your answer correct to 1 decimal place</p><p>[2 marks]&nbsp;</p><p><br>ii. At what time is the water draining out the pool at a rate of \\(30000 \\mathrm{~L} /\\)minute</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. First finding the initial volume of water in the pool by letting \\(t=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} Q(0) &amp; =3000(20-0)^2 \\\\ &amp; =1200000 \\end{aligned} $$ Then, letting \\(Q(t)=600000\\) [half of initial volume] and solving for \\(t\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 600000=3000(20-t)^2 \\\\ &amp; 200=(20-t)^2 \\\\ &amp; \\sqrt{200}=20-t[\\because t&gt;0] \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=20-\\sqrt{200} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 5.9 \\text { minutes } \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$ ii. To find the rate of drainage, differentiate first: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; Q(t)=3000(20-t)^2 \\\\ &amp; Q(t)=3000\\left(400-40 t+t^2\\right) \\\\ &amp; Q(t)=1200000-120000 t+3000 t^2 \\\\ &amp; Q^{\\prime}(t)=-120000+6000 t \\end{aligned} $$ When the rate of drainage is \\(30000 \\mathrm{~L} / \\mathrm{min}\\), then \\(Q^{\\prime}(t)=-30000\\). Note that \\(Q^{\\prime}(t)&lt;0\\) since this is a rate of decrease. Therefore, solving for \\(t\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; -30000=-120000+6000 t \\\\ &amp; 90000=6000 t \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=15 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, when \\(t=15\\) minutes, the rate of drainage is \\(30000 \\mathrm{~L} / \\mathrm{min}\\)</p>','2024-01-07 04:38:48',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(187,1,40,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The displacement of an object \\(x\\) metres from the origin after \\(t\\) seconds is given by the expression: $$ x=t^2-6 t+5 $$ When 3 seconds has passed, what is the object\'s displacement?</p>','<p>Letting \\(t=3\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} x &amp; =(3)^2-6(3)+5 \\\\ &amp; =9-18+5 \\\\ &amp; =-9+5 \\\\ &amp; =-4 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the displacement here is \\(-4 m\\)&nbsp;</p><p>Note that for this question, we are asked for displacement. Hence, since displacement has a direction, our answer must include a negative sign!</p>','2024-01-07 10:43:22',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(188,1,40,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A particle\'s displacement measured in \\(x\\) metres after \\(t\\) minutes is given by the equation: $$ x=6 t^2-5 t+6 $$ Which of the following is the equation for the velocity of this object?</p>','<p>The velocity of a particle is defined as the rate of change of its displacement. Hence \\(v=\\frac{d x}{d t}\\), so differentiating $x$ : $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{d x}{d t}=12 t-5 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore v=12 t-5 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-07 10:48:27',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(189,1,40,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>An object\'s displacement measured in \\(x\\) metres after \\(t\\) seconds is given by the equation: $$ x=2 t^3+3 t^2-t+5 $$ Which of the following is the expression for the acceleration of this object?</p>','<p>First, differentiating \\(x\\) to find the velocity equation: $$ v=\\frac{d x}{d t}=6 t^2+6 t-1 $$ Then differentiating again to find the acceleration equation: $$ a=\\frac{d v}{d t}=\\frac{d^2 x}{d t^2}=12 t+6 $$ Hence, the expression for acceleration is: $$ a=12 t+6 $$</p>','2024-01-07 10:58:51',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(190,1,40,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A particle\'s velocity is given by the equation: $$ v=t^2-4 t-5 $$ Where \\(v\\) is the velocity of the particle and \\(t\\) is the time in seconds after the object begins moving&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">At what time is the particle stationary?</p>','<p>First, factorising our velocity equation: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; v=t^2-4 t-5 \\\\ &amp; v=(t-5)(t+1) \\end{aligned} $$ A particle is considered stationary when \\(v=0\\), hence: $$ t=5 \\text { or } t=-1 $$ However, \\(t&gt;0\\) so: $$ &nbsp;\\therefore t=5 \\text { ONLY } $$</p>','2024-01-07 11:14:48',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(191,1,40,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A particle moves such that its velocity at a time \\(t\\) seconds is given by \\(\\dot{x}=4 t^2-6 t\\).<br>i. Find when the particle is at rest&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]</p><p><br>ii. Derive an expression for \\(\\ddot{x}\\)&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]<br><br>iii. What is the velocity when acceleration \\(\\ddot{x}=10 \\mathrm{~ms}^{-2}\\)?&nbsp;<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Note that \\(\\dot{x}=v\\)&nbsp;<br>A particle is at rest when \\(\\dot{x}=0\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 4 t^2-6 t=0 \\\\ &amp; 2 t(2 t-3)=0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=0 \\text { OR } \\frac{3}{2} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the particle is at rest when \\(t=0\\) and when \\(t=\\frac{3}{2}\\)<br>&nbsp;</p><p><br>ii. Differentiating \\(\\dot{x}\\): $$ \\ddot{x}=8 \\mathrm{t}-6 $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. When \\(\\ddot{x}=10\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 10=8 t-6 \\\\ &amp; 16=8 t \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=2 \\end{aligned} $$ When \\(t=2\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\dot{x} &amp; =4(2)^2-6(2) \\\\ &amp; =16-12 \\\\ &amp; =4 \\mathrm{~ms}^{-1} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-07 11:27:22',0,1,4,420,'hard','subtopic'),(192,1,41,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { What is the exact value of } \\cos 45^{\\circ} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>This is just one of the exact values students are expected to remember: $$ \\cos 45^{\\circ}=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} $$</p>','2024-01-07 22:49:36',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(193,1,41,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { What is the exact value of } \\sec 60^{\\circ}+\\tan 60^{\\circ} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\sec 60^{\\circ} &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\cos 60^{\\circ}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\ &amp; =2 \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{gathered} \\tan 60^{\\circ}=\\sqrt{3} \\\\ \\therefore \\sec 60^{\\circ}+\\tan 60^{\\circ}=2+\\sqrt{3} \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-07 22:49:36',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(194,1,41,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { If } \\sin A=\\frac{3}{5} \\text { and } 0^{\\circ}&lt;A&lt;90^{\\circ}&nbsp;\\text { , which of the following represents the value of } \\cot A ?$$</p>','<p>Since \\(\\sin A=\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { hypotenuse }}=\\frac{3}{5}\\), we can draw a right - angle triangle:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:360/167;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/0374bb6c98aa54e29980275dc2e01a8a.jpeg\" width=\"360\" height=\"167\"></figure><p>By Pythagoras theorem: $$ \\text { Adjacent side }=\\sqrt{5^2-3^2}=\\sqrt{16}=4 $$ Since \\(\\cot A=\\frac{\\text { adjacent }}{\\text { opposite }}\\) $$ \\therefore \\cot A=\\frac{4}{3} $$</p>','2024-01-07 22:59:45',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(195,1,41,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Given the diagram of \\(\\triangle A B C\\) below, find the value of angle \\(A\\) to the nearest minute</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:221/264;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a3f7e17462ad7209097e0b6a4edd3c0c.png\" width=\"221\" height=\"264\"></figure>','<p>Using our trigonometric ratios: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\tan A &amp; =\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { adjacent }} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{21}{13} \\\\ \\therefore A &amp; =\\tan ^{-1} \\frac{21}{13} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 58^{\\circ} 14^{\\prime \\prime}(\\text { nearest minute }) \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-07 23:08:28',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(196,1,41,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer</u></p><p>Consider the exact values \\(\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{8}=\\frac{\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}}}{2}\\) and \\(\\cos \\frac{\\pi}{8}=\\frac{(\\sqrt{2}-1)(\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}})}{2}\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Find the exact value of \\(-\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{8}-\\cos \\frac{\\pi}{8}\\)</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} -\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{8}-\\cos \\frac{\\pi}{8} &amp; =-\\frac{\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}}}{2}-\\frac{(\\sqrt{2}-1)(\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}})}{2} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}}}{2}-\\frac{\\sqrt{2} \\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}}-\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}}}{2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{-\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}}-\\sqrt{2}(\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}})--\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}}}{2} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{\\sqrt{2}(\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2}})}{2} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{\\sqrt{4+2 \\sqrt{2}}}{2} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-07 23:29:49',0,1,2,240,'hard','subtopic'),(197,1,42,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Given that } \\sin \\theta=\\frac{4}{9} \\text { and } 90^{\\circ}&lt;\\theta&lt;180^{\\circ} \\text {, what is the value of } \\tan \\theta ? $$</p>','<p>Since \\(\\sin \\theta=\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { hypotenuse }}=\\frac{4}{9}\\), we can sketch the right - angled triangle:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:245/154;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/39b0eefc0b1f3ddedd60bfa3deeeef66.jpeg\" width=\"245\" height=\"154\"></figure><p>Using Pythagoras theorem: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { adjacent side } &amp; =\\sqrt{9^2-4^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{81-16} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{65} \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(90^{\\circ}&lt;\\theta&lt;180^{\\circ}, \\tan \\theta&lt;0\\), meaning: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\tan \\theta &amp; =-\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { adjacent }} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{4}{\\sqrt{65}} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 00:14:25',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(198,1,42,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { What is the exact value of } \\cos 225^{\\circ} ? $$</p>','<p>\\(\\cos 225^{\\circ}\\) is in the third quadrant, meaning that \\(\\cos \\theta&lt;0\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Since \\(\\cos 225^{\\circ}=\\cos (180+45)\\): $$ \\cos 225^{\\circ}=-\\cos 45^{\\circ}=-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} $$</p>','2024-01-08 00:33:49',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(199,1,42,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Evaluate } \\cot 210^{\\circ} \\times \\sin 240^{\\circ} $$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{gathered} \\cot 210^{\\circ}=\\frac{1}{\\tan 210^{\\circ}} \\\\ \\tan 210^{\\circ}=\\tan 30^{\\circ}=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\\\ \\therefore \\cot 210^{\\circ}=\\frac{1}{\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}}=\\sqrt{3} \\\\ \\sin 240^{\\circ}=-\\sin 60^{\\circ}=-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\ \\therefore \\cot 210^{\\circ} \\times \\sin 240^{\\circ}=\\sqrt{3} \\times-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\ =-\\frac{3}{2} \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-08 00:49:42',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(200,1,42,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { If } \\tan x=4 \\text { and } \\sin x&lt;0 \\text {, find the exact value of } \\cos x \\text {&nbsp;} $$</p>','<p>Since \\(\\tan x=\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { adjacent }}=\\frac{4}{1}\\), we can draw the right - angle triangle:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:208/233;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e9ca33326fc69537f7121c1488f63c7c.jpeg\" width=\"208\" height=\"233\"></figure><p>By Pythagoras theorem: $$ \\text { Hypotenuse }=\\sqrt{1^2+4^2}=\\sqrt{17} $$ Note however in this question, that \\(\\sin x&lt;0\\) and \\(\\tan x&gt;0\\), meaning that \\(x\\) is actually in the \\(3^{\\text {rd }}\\) quadrant where \\(\\cos x&lt;0\\) $$ \\therefore \\cos x=-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{17}} $$</p>','2024-01-08 00:57:49',0,1,2,240,'medium','subtopic'),(201,1,42,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { If } \\cos \\alpha=-\\frac{5}{8} \\text { and } \\sin \\alpha&lt;0 \\text {, find the exact value of } \\tan \\alpha $$</p>','<p>Since \\(\\cos \\alpha=\\frac{\\text { adjacent }}{\\text { hypotenuse }}\\), we can draw the right - angled triangle:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:226/228;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/49ef9a3e3aa0776ea504923a183e6fe0.jpeg\" width=\"226\" height=\"228\"></figure><p>By Pythagoras theorem: $$ \\text { opposite side }=\\sqrt{8^2-5^2}=\\sqrt{39} $$ Since \\(\\cos \\alpha&lt;0\\) and \\(\\sin \\alpha&lt;0\\), then this means that \\(\\alpha\\) must be in the \\(3^{\\text {rd }}\\) quadrant and so \\(\\tan \\alpha&gt;0\\) $$ \\therefore \\tan \\alpha=\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { adjacent }}=\\frac{\\sqrt{39}}{5} $$</p>','2024-01-08 01:07:26',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(202,1,43,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { What is the correct expression for the value of } x \\text { in } \\triangle A B C \\text { ? } $$</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:37.98%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:707/543;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/70df6d5e9cfca6ce20021cc8bdaee217.png\" width=\"707\" height=\"543\"></figure>','<p>Considering the sine rule: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\frac{x}{\\sin 58^{\\circ}}=\\frac{19}{\\sin 47^{\\circ}} \\\\ \\therefore x=\\frac{19 \\sin 58^{\\circ}}{\\sin 47^{\\circ}} \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-08 04:16:24',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(203,1,43,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Determine the size of angle } A \\text { in the following triangle: } $$</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:43.55%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:713/528;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/33e42779bc6630dbe639a34a8d11c6c4.png\" width=\"713\" height=\"528\"></figure>','<p>Recalling the cosine rule: $$ c^2=a^2+b^2-2 a b \\cos \\theta $$ Rearranging to make \\(\\cos \\theta\\) the subject: $$ \\cos \\theta=\\frac{a^2+b^2-c^2}{2 a b} $$ Therefore, for this question: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos A &amp; =\\frac{10.2^2+11.8^2-12.1^2}{2 \\times 10.2 \\times 11.8} \\\\ &amp; =0.4024177468 \\\\ \\therefore A= &amp; 66^{\\circ} 16^{\\prime \\prime} \\text { (nearest minute) } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 08:19:51',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(204,1,43,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Find the value of \\(x\\), correct to the nearest whole number</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1088/421;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/21f4bf866ca1511b24b9413dbcb97dbb.png\" width=\"1088\" height=\"421\"></figure>','<p>Recalling the cosine rule: $$ c^2=a^2+b^2-2 a b \\cos \\theta $$ Therefore, using the cosine rule for this question: $$ \\begin{aligned} x^2 &amp; =29^2+19^2-2 \\times 29 \\times 19 \\times \\cos 124^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =1818.23 \\\\ \\therefore x &amp; \\approx 43 \\mathrm{~cm} \\text { (nearest whole number) } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 08:26:59',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(205,1,43,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>In the diagram below, use the sine rule to find the value of \\(\\theta\\), correct to the nearest minute</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:40.87%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:683/517;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a7c526260317ee61d3092a42d4c1b82d.png\" width=\"683\" height=\"517\"></figure>','<p>Recalling the sine rule for finding angles: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{17}=\\frac{\\sin 33^{\\circ}}{11} \\\\ \\therefore \\sin \\theta=17 \\times \\frac{\\sin 33^{\\circ}}{11} \\\\ =0.8417148723 \\\\ \\therefore \\theta=57^{\\circ} 19^{\\prime} \\text { (nearest minute) } \\end{gathered} $$However, checking ambiguous case for sine rule: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\theta=180^{\\circ}-57^{\\circ} 19^{\\prime} \\\\ =122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime} \\\\ 122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime}+33^{\\circ}&lt;180^{\\circ} \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, since \\(122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime}+33^{\\circ}&lt;180^{\\circ}\\), then \\(\\theta\\) can also equal to \\(122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime}\\) as a solution. $$ \\therefore \\theta=57^{\\circ} 19^{\\prime} \\text{ OR } 122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime} $$ Note for this question that forgetting to check the ambiguous case would result in 1 mark lost!</p>','2024-01-08 08:58:51',0,1,3,300,'hard','subtopic'),(206,1,43,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>A circular clock face with centre \\(\\mathrm{O}\\), has a minute hand \\(\\mathrm{OA}\\) and an hour hand \\(\\mathrm{OB}\\). It is known that \\(OA=12 \\mathrm{~cm}\\) and \\(OB=9 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). Calculate the length of \\(\\mathrm{AB}\\) when the hands show 4 o\'clock, giving your answer correct to 1 decimal place</p>','<p>Since the clock is showing 4 o\'clock, we now know that \\(\\angle A O B=30^{\\circ} \\times 4=120^{\\circ}$&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, considering the cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} A B^2 &amp; =O A^2+O B^2-2(O A)(O B) \\cos \\angle A O B \\\\ &amp; =12^2+9^2-2(12)(9) \\cos 120^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =333 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore A B \\approx 18.2 \\mathrm{~cm}[\\text {nearest } 1 \\text { d.p.}] \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 09:15:50',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(207,1,43,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answers [3 marks]</u></p><p>In triangle \\(A B C: A B=13 \\mathrm{~cm}, B C=22 \\mathrm{~cm}\\) and \\(A C=26 \\mathrm{~cm}\\).&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find the exact area of the triangle&nbsp;</p>','<p>Sketching a diagram first to help us visualise the problem:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:851/638;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/3e431538faf2066ba48c970e660a56f3.png\" width=\"851\" height=\"638\"></figure><p>To calculate the area of this triangle, we aim to use the formula: $$ \\text { Area }=\\frac{1}{2} A B \\sin \\theta $$ Therefore, for this question: $$ \\text { Area } \\triangle A B C=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 13 \\times 26 \\times \\sin A $$ Notice that we need to first find angle \\(A\\) to apply this formula. Therefore, we use the cosine rule to try find the value of angle \\(A\\), where we recall that: $$ B C^2=A B^2+A C^2-2(A B)(A C) \\cos A $$Rearranging to make \\(\\cos A\\) the subject: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\cos A &amp; =\\frac{A B^2+A C^2-B C^2}{2(A B)(A C)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{13^2+26^2-22^2}{2(13)(26)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{361}{676} \\end{aligned} $$ To find \\(\\sin A\\), we can use our calculator to find \\(A=\\cos ^{-1} \\frac{363}{676}\\) and then calculate \\(\\sin A\\) using the result, but a better way here (since we want exact) would be to sketch the right-angle triangle.&nbsp;<br><br>Since \\(\\cos A=\\frac{\\text { adjacent }}{\\text { hypotenuse }}=\\frac{361}{676}\\), we can sketch:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:796/567;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/5b444f8b6b2eb5fe28497d049f923259.png\" width=\"796\" height=\"567\"></figure><p>Notice here that we have used Pythagoras to find the exact length of the opposite side: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { opposite length } &amp; =\\sqrt{676^2-361^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{326655} \\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\therefore \\sin A=\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { hypotenuse }}=\\frac{\\sqrt{326655}}{676} $$ Substituting this back into our initial area formula: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\text { Area } \\triangle A B C &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times 13 \\times 26 \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{326655}}{676} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\sqrt{326655}}{4} \\text { units }^2 \\end{aligned} $$ Note that any answer without surds will be deducted a mark! (since the question asked for exact area)</p>','2024-01-08 09:34:20',0,1,3,500,'hard','subtopic'),(208,1,44,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Which of the following is } \\tan \\frac{\\pi}{3} \\text { equal to? } $$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\tan \\frac{\\pi}{3} &amp; =\\tan 60^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 10:19:33',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(209,1,44,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { What is the exact value of } \\sec \\frac{\\pi}{6} \\text {? } $$</p>','<p>Recall that \\(\\sec \\theta=\\frac{1}{\\cos \\theta}\\) $$ \\therefore \\sec \\frac{\\pi}{6}=\\frac{1}{\\cos \\frac{\\pi}{6}} $$ Since \\(\\cos \\frac{\\pi}{6}=\\cos 30^{\\circ}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\frac{1}{\\cos \\frac{\\pi}{6}} &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{\\sqrt{3}} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 10:28:39',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(210,1,44,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Which of the following is } 145^{\\circ} \\text { in radian measure?} $$</p>','<p>$$ 145 \\times \\frac{\\pi}{180}=\\frac{29}{36} \\pi $$</p>','2024-01-08 10:33:22',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(211,1,44,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text { If } \\cos \\theta=\\frac{13}{18}, \\text { find the exact value of } \\sin \\theta \\text { given that } \\frac{3 \\pi}{2} \\leq \\theta \\leq 2 \\pi $$</p>','<p>Since \\(\\cos \\theta=\\frac{\\text { adjacent }}{\\text { hypotenuse }}\\) and in this case \\(\\cos \\theta=\\frac{13}{18}\\), we can sketch the right - angled triangle:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:637/463;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/09691f29cf30c0b4c0da955a1a37189e.png\" width=\"637\" height=\"463\"></figure><p>Notice here that using Pythagoras theorem to find the value of the opposite side: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Opposite side } &amp; =\\sqrt{18^2-13^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{155} \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(\\frac{3 \\pi}{2} \\leq \\theta \\leq 2 \\pi\\), this means that \\(\\theta\\) is in the fourth quadrant where \\(\\sin \\theta&lt;0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\sin \\theta &amp; =-\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { hypotenuse }} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{\\sqrt{155}}{18} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 10:40:23',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(212,1,44,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Evaluate } \\cot \\frac{4 \\pi}{3} \\times \\sin \\frac{5 \\pi}{4} $$</p>','<p>$$ \\cot \\frac{4 \\pi}{3} \\times \\sin \\frac{5 \\pi}{4}=\\frac{1}{\\tan \\frac{4 \\pi}{3}} \\times \\sin \\frac{5 \\pi}{4} $$ Recall that since \\(\\frac{4 \\pi}{3}\\) is in the \\(3^{\\text {rd }}\\) quadrant where \\(\\tan \\theta&gt;0\\): $$ \\tan \\frac{4 \\pi}{3}=\\tan \\frac{\\pi}{3} $$ Moreover, since \\(\\frac{5 \\pi}{4}\\) is in the \\(3^{\\text {rd }}\\) quadrant where \\(\\sin \\theta&lt;0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\sin \\frac{5 \\pi}{4} &amp; =-\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\\\ \\therefore \\frac{1}{\\tan \\frac{4 \\pi}{3}} \\times \\sin \\frac{5 \\pi}{4} &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\tan \\frac{\\pi}{3}} \\times-\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\times-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{6}} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 10:48:56',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(213,1,46,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {What is the perimeter } P \\text { of the sector given below with angle } 42^{\\circ} \\text { and radius } 15 \\mathrm{~cm} \\text { ? } $$</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:241/279;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a063ab9e8405036c2eb0d2bb4bfc25c0.png\" width=\"241\" height=\"279\"></figure>','<p>For the length of the straight edges: $$ 15+15=30 \\mathrm{~cm} $$ For the length of the curved edge: $$ l=r \\theta $$ Note however that \\(\\theta\\) must be in radians:&nbsp;$$ \\begin{aligned} 42^{\\circ} &amp; =42 \\times \\frac{\\pi}{180} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{7 \\pi}{30} \\\\ \\therefore l &amp; =15 \\times \\frac{7 \\pi}{30} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{7 \\pi}{2} \\mathrm{~cm} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore \\text { Total Perimeter }=30+\\frac{7 \\pi}{2} \\mathrm{~cm} $$</p>','2024-01-08 10:56:53',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(214,1,46,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { The area of a minor segment of a circle pictured below is } 50 \\pi \\text { metres squared. } $$</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:947/449;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f3edbd37c873b5d491244a0d8c395279.png\" width=\"947\" height=\"449\"></figure><p>$$ \\text {Which of the following is the exact expression for the radius of the circle? } $$</p>','<p>The area of a minor segment is given as: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area of Segment } &amp; =\\text { Area of Sector }- \\text { Area of Triangle } \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta-\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\sin \\theta \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} r^2(\\theta-\\sin \\theta) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, since the area of the segment in this case is \\(50 \\pi\\) and \\(\\theta=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 50 \\pi=\\frac{1}{2} r^2\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{3}-\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{3}\\right) \\\\ &amp; 100 \\pi=r^2\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{3}-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right) \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 100 \\pi=r^2\\left(\\frac{2 \\pi-3 \\sqrt{3}}{6}\\right) \\\\ &amp; r^2=100 \\pi \\times \\frac{6}{2 \\pi-3 \\sqrt{3}} \\\\ &amp; r^2=\\frac{600 \\pi}{2 \\pi-3 \\sqrt{3}} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore r=\\frac{10 \\sqrt{6 \\pi}}{\\sqrt{2 \\pi-3 \\sqrt{3}}} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 10:59:37',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(215,1,46,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>Kate has a backyard as shown in the diagram below by shape \\(\\mathrm{ABCD}\\). The sector \\(\\mathrm{BCD}\\) has a centre \\(\\mathrm{B}\\), and \\(A B=A D=4 \\mathrm{~m}\\).</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:584/306;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/68fa1593f6ffa517d4ea67c154b634a6.png\" width=\"584\" height=\"306\"></figure><p>i. Find the length of \\(\\mathrm{DB}\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the total area of the backyard, leaving your answer in exact form&nbsp;<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Considering \\(\\triangle A B D\\) and knowing that \\(\\angle D B A=\\pi-\\frac{5 \\pi}{6}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\).</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:340/274;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/5e4d2e1bf7d34f27b7654daef2efe0b4.jpeg\" width=\"340\" height=\"274\"></figure><p>Since \\(\\triangle A B D\\) is isosceles, \\(\\angle A D B=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\) (equal angles opposite equal sides) $$ \\therefore \\angle A D B=\\frac{2 \\pi}{3} $$ By the cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} D B^2= &amp; A D^2+A B^2-2(A D)(A B) \\cos \\angle D A B \\\\ = &amp; 4^2+4^2-2 \\times 4 \\times 4 \\times \\cos \\frac{2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ = &amp; 32-32\\left(-\\frac{1}{2}\\right) \\\\ = &amp; 48 \\\\ &amp; \\quad \\therefore D B=\\sqrt{48}=4 \\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~m} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. The area of the backyard may be split into two parts, sector \\(\\mathrm{DBC}\\) and triangle DAB.</p><p><br>Finding the area of sector DBC first: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Sector Area } &amp; =\\frac{1}{2}r^2 \\theta \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times (4 \\sqrt{3})^2 \\times \\frac{5 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times 48 \\times \\frac{5 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; =20 \\pi \\mathrm{m}^2 \\end{aligned} $$ Then finding the area of \\(\\triangle D A B\\): $$ &nbsp;\\begin{aligned} &amp; \\triangle D A B=\\frac{1}{2} a b \\sin \\theta \\\\ &amp;=\\frac{1}{2} \\times(A B) \\times(A D) \\times \\sin \\angle D A B \\\\ &amp;=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 4 \\times 4 \\times \\sin \\frac{2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp;=8 \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\ &amp;=4 \\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~m}^2 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\text { Total Area }=20 \\pi+4 \\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~m}^2 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 11:22:49',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(216,1,46,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>In the diagram below, \\(\\triangle A B C\\) is right angled at \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), with \\(\\angle B A C=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\) and \\(A B=6 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). RP is a circular arc with centre at \\(A\\) and RQ is a circular arc with centre at \\(B\\). If \\(A R\\) has length \\(x \\mathrm{~cm}\\), find the value of \\(x\\) for which the areas of the sectors ARP and BRQ are equal</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:594/358;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f6be37042842db26c29962df502692d7.png\" width=\"594\" height=\"358\"></figure>','<p>Since \\(A R=x\\), then \\(R B=6-x\\) Since \\(\\angle C A B=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\), then \\(\\angle C B A=\\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Considering that the area of a sector is given as \\(\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area of Sector } A P R &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ \\text { Area of Sector } B R Q &amp; =\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ Since we want the two areas to equal:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6}=\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; x^2 \\pi=(6-x)^2 \\pi \\\\ &amp; x^2=(6-x)^2 \\\\ &amp; x^2=36-12 x+x^2 \\\\ &amp; 36-12 x=0 \\\\ &amp; 12(3-x)=0 \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore x=3$$</p>','2024-01-08 11:39:38',0,1,3,300,'hard','subtopic'),(217,1,46,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>A necklace is made in the form of a sector of a circle, as shown in the diagram below:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:228/261;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/966d9f1c98f50321b2ba26e7112854fb.png\" width=\"228\" height=\"261\"></figure><p>i. If the radius is known to be \\(3.5 \\mathrm{~cm}\\), what is the angle \\(\\theta\\), in radians to the nearest 3 decimal places, so that the area is \\(8 \\mathrm{~cm}^2 ?\\)</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Another necklace has the same total perimeter, but with radius \\(3 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). What is the required angle \\(\\alpha\\) for this other necklace, in radians?&nbsp;</p><p>[3 marks]</p>','<p>i. The area of the sector is known to be \\(8 \\mathrm{~cm}^2\\).<br><br>Hence, using the area formula: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 8=\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta \\ [\\theta \\text { is in radians }] \\\\ &amp; 16=r^2 \\theta \\\\ &amp; 16=(3.5)^2 \\theta \\\\ &amp; \\theta=\\frac{16}{3.5^2} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\theta \\approx 1.306[\\text { nearest } 3 \\text { d.p.] }] \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. The perimeter of the necklace is: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Perimeter } &amp; =3.5+3.5+r \\theta \\ [\\text { length of curve is } l \\theta] \\\\ &amp; =7+3.5(1.306) \\ [\\text { From part } i] \\\\ &amp; =11.571 \\mathrm{~cm} \\end{aligned} $$For the second necklace with radius \\(3 \\mathrm{~cm}\\), its perimeter expression may be given as: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Perimeter } &amp; =3+3+r \\alpha \\\\ &amp; =6+3 \\alpha \\end{aligned} $$ Since the perimeter of both necklaces are the same: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 11.571=6+3 \\alpha \\\\ &amp; 3 \\alpha=5.571 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\alpha=1.857 \\text { radians } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 11:48:04',0,1,5,480,'medium','subtopic'),(218,1,46,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>A sector has an arc length \\(l\\) of \\(3.5 \\pi \\mathrm{cm}\\) and an area \\(A\\) of \\(36 \\pi \\mathrm{cm}^2\\). The radius of the sector is given as \\(r \\mathrm{~cm}\\). Hence, find the central angle, \\(\\theta\\), of the sector in exact form</p>','<p>Considering formulas for arc length and sector area: $$ \\begin{gathered} l=r \\theta \\\\ A=\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta \\\\ \\therefore r \\theta=3.5 \\pi(1) \\\\ \\therefore \\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta=36 \\pi(2) \\end{gathered} $$Hence, solving simultaneously: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta=36 \\pi \\\\ &amp; \\frac{1}{2} r \\times r \\theta=36 \\pi \\\\ &amp; \\frac{1}{2} r \\times(3.5 \\pi)=36 \\pi[\\text { Substituting equation (1)] } \\\\ &amp; r=\\frac{36 \\pi}{3.5 \\pi} \\times 2 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore r=\\frac{144}{7} \\mathrm{~cm} \\end{aligned} $$Since \\(r=\\frac{144}{7}\\), from equation 1: $$ \\frac{144}{7} \\theta=3.5 \\pi $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\theta &amp; =3.5 \\pi \\times \\frac{7}{144} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{49}{288} \\pi \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 11:57:42',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(219,1,46,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>The diagram below shows sector \\(\\mathrm{OAB}\\) centred at \\(O\\). The line segment \\(\\mathrm{AC}\\) divides the sector and is \\(8 \\mathrm{~cm}\\) long, with \\(\\angle A O B\\) given as \\(28^{\\circ}\\) and \\(\\angle A C B\\) given as \\(58^{\\circ}\\).</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:49.41%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:956/904;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/091b98039eea0cb1d9df1d40baa099fc.png\" width=\"956\" height=\"904\"></figure><p>i. Find the length of \\(\\mathrm{OA}\\) correct to 2 decimal places&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Hence, or otherwise, find the area of the shaded region to the nearest \\(\\mathrm{cm}^2 \\\\)&nbsp;</p><p>[3&nbsp;marks]</p>','<p>i. Since \\(\\angle A C B=58^{\\circ}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle A C O &amp; =180^{\\circ}-58^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =122^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$ Considering the sine rule:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{O A}{\\sin \\angle A C O}=\\frac{8}{\\sin \\angle C O A} \\\\ &amp; \\frac{OA}{\\sin 122^{\\circ}}=\\frac{8}{\\sin 28^{\\circ}} \\\\ &amp; \\begin{array}{c} \\therefore O A=\\sin 122^{\\circ} \\times \\frac{8}{\\sin 28^{\\circ}} \\\\ =14.45 m \\end{array} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>ii. To calculate the shaded area:&nbsp;<br>$$ \\text { Shaded Area }=\\text { Sector } O A B-\\triangle A C O $$We must first convert our angle in degrees into radians: $$ \\begin{aligned} 28^{\\circ} &amp; =28 \\times \\frac{\\pi}{180} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 0.4887 \\end{aligned} $$ The area of sector \\(O A B\\) is given as:$$ &nbsp;\\begin{aligned}Sector \\&nbsp; O A B &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2}(O A)^2 0.4887 \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times 14.45^2 \\times 0.4887 \\\\ &amp; \\approx 51.02 \\mathrm{~cm}^2 \\end{aligned} $$The area of \\(\\triangle A C O\\) is given as: $$ \\text { Area of } \\triangle A C O=\\frac{1}{2}(O A)(A C) \\sin \\angle O C A $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle O C A &amp; =180^{\\circ}-28^{\\circ}-122^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =30^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$$$&nbsp; \\begin{aligned} Area \\ of\\ \\triangle A C O &amp; =\\frac{1}{2}(14.45)(8) \\sin 30^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =28.9 \\mathrm{~cm}^2 \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\text { Shaded area } &amp; =51.02-28.9 \\\\ &amp; \\approx 22 \\mathrm{~cm}^2\\left[\\text { nearest } \\mathrm{cm}^2\\right] \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-08 12:07:46',0,1,5,540,'hard','subtopic'),(220,1,46,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A circle has centre \\(\\mathrm{O}\\) and a radius of \\(14 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). A chord \\(\\mathrm{AB}\\) of the circle is drawn, making triangle \\(A O B\\) an equilateral triangle.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:359/277;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/8737ef90cc98b7c1bf8664d121ad3067.jpeg\" width=\"359\" height=\"277\"></figure><p>i. State in radians, the size of angle AOB&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Calculate the area of the minor segment&nbsp;<br>[3 marks]</p>','<p>i. Since we know \\(\\triangle A O B\\) is equilateral: $$ \\therefore \\angle A O B=\\frac{\\pi}{3} $$</p><p>ii. For the area of a minor segment: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area } &amp; =\\text { Area of Sector }- \\text { Area of } \\triangle A O B \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta-\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\sin \\theta \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} r^2(\\theta-\\sin \\theta) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2}(14)^2\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{3}-\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{3}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2}(196)\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{3}-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =98\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{3}-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right) \\mathrm{cm}^2 \\end{aligned} $$ Must give your answer in exact values!</p>','2024-01-08 12:16:09',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(221,1,47,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Which of the following is the correct simplification of } \\frac{\\sec x \\operatorname{cosec} x}{1+\\tan ^2 x} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{\\sec x \\operatorname{cosec} x}{1+\\tan ^2 x} &amp; =\\frac{\\sec x \\operatorname{cosec} x}{\\sec ^2 x}\\left[\\because 1+\\tan ^2 x=\\sec ^2 x\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\operatorname{cosec} x}{\\sec x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\frac{1}{\\sin x}}{\\frac{1}{\\cos x}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\cos x}{\\sin x} \\\\ &amp; =\\cot x \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 03:19:43',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(222,1,47,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { What is equivalent to } \\sin ^2 3 x ? $$</p>','<p>Since we know that \\(\\sin ^2 \\theta+\\cos ^2 \\theta=1\\): $$ \\therefore \\sin ^2 3 x=1-\\cos ^2 3 x \\ [\\because \\text { pythagorean identity}] $$</p>','2024-01-09 03:27:03',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(223,1,47,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Prove that } \\tan \\theta \\sin \\theta+\\cos \\theta=\\sec \\theta $$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { LHS } &amp; =\\tan \\theta \\sin \\theta+\\cos \\theta \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} \\sin \\theta+\\cos \\theta \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\sin ^2 \\theta}{\\cos \\theta}+\\cos \\theta \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\sin ^2 \\theta+\\cos ^2 \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\cos \\theta}\\left[\\because \\sin ^2 \\theta+\\cos ^2 \\theta=1\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\sec \\theta \\\\ &amp; =\\text { RHS } \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore \\text { LHS }=\\text {RHS }$$&nbsp;</p>','2024-01-09 03:33:20',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(224,1,47,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Simplify the following: $$ (3 \\cos x+2 \\sin x)^2+(2 \\cos x-3 \\sin x)^2 $$</p>','<p>First expanding the expression: $$ 9 \\cos ^2 x+12 \\sin x \\cos x+4 \\sin ^2 x+4 \\cos ^2 x-12 \\sin x \\cos x+9 \\sin ^2 x $$ Then cancelling terms: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 9 \\cos ^2 x+4 \\sin ^2 x+4 \\cos ^2 x+9 \\sin ^2 x \\\\ &amp; 9 \\cos ^2 x+9 \\sin ^2 x+4 \\sin ^2 x+4 \\cos ^2 x \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(\\sin ^2 x+\\cos ^2 x=1\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore 9\\left(\\sin ^2 x+\\cos ^2 x\\right)+4\\left(\\sin ^2 x+\\cos ^2 x\\right) &amp; =9+4 \\\\ &amp; =13 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 03:35:36',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(225,1,47,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Prove that } \\frac{\\sec \\theta-\\sec \\theta \\cos ^4 \\theta}{1+\\cos ^2 \\theta}=\\sin \\theta \\tan \\theta $$</p><p>Select the most appropriate FIRST step you conducted to get this question correct</p>','<p>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>&amp;\\begin{aligned}<br>\\text { LHS } &amp; =\\frac{\\sec \\theta-\\sec \\theta \\cos ^4 \\theta}{1+\\cos ^2 \\theta} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{\\sec \\theta\\left(1-\\cos ^4 \\theta\\right)}{1+\\cos ^2 \\theta} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{\\sec \\theta\\left(1+\\cos ^2 \\theta\\right)\\left(1-\\cos ^2 \\theta\\right)}{1+\\cos ^2 \\theta}[\\because \\text { difference of squares }] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\sec \\theta\\left(1-\\cos ^2 \\theta\\right) \\\\<br>&amp; =\\sec \\theta-\\cos \\theta\\left[\\because \\sec \\theta=\\frac{1}{\\cos \\theta}\\right] \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1}{\\cos \\theta}-\\cos \\theta \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{1-\\cos \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{\\sin 2 \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\sin \\theta \\times \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\sin \\theta \\tan \\theta \\\\<br>&amp; =R H S<br>\\end{aligned}\\\\<br>&amp;<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$$$\\therefore \\text {LHS}=\\text {RHS }$$</p>','2024-01-09 03:37:54',0,1,3,300,'hard','subtopic'),(226,1,47,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Prove that } \\frac{1-\\sin ^2 x \\cos ^2 x}{\\sin ^2 x}=\\cot ^2 x+\\sin ^2 x&nbsp;\\text {&nbsp; } $$</p><p>Select the most appropriate FIRST step you conducted to get this question correct</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { LHS } &amp; =\\frac{1-\\sin ^2 x \\cos ^2 x}{\\sin ^2 x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1-\\sin ^2 x\\left(1-\\sin ^2 x\\right)}{\\sin ^2 x}\\left[\\because \\cos ^2 x=1-\\sin ^2 x\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1-\\sin ^2 x+\\sin ^4 x}{\\sin ^2 x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\cos ^2 x+\\sin ^4 x}{\\sin ^2 x}\\left[\\because 1-\\sin ^2 x=\\cos ^2 x\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\cos ^2 x}{\\sin ^2 x}+\\frac{\\sin ^4 x}{\\sin ^2 x} \\\\ &amp; =\\cot ^2 x+\\sin ^2 x\\left[\\because \\cot x=\\frac{\\cos x}{\\sin x}\\right] \\\\ &amp; =R H S \\quad&nbsp; \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore L H S=R H S $$</p>','2024-01-09 04:53:15',0,1,2,180,'hard','subtopic'),(227,1,47,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Fully simplify } \\frac{\\sec ^2 x}{\\tan ^2 x}$$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { LHS } &amp; =\\frac{\\sec ^2 x}{\\tan ^2 x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\frac{1}{\\cos ^2 x}}{\\frac{\\sin ^2 x}{\\cos ^2 x}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\cos ^2 x} \\times \\frac{\\cos ^2 x}{\\sin ^2 x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\sin ^2 x} \\\\ &amp; =\\operatorname{cosec}^2 x \\\\ &nbsp;\\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 05:08:23',0,1,2,180,'easy','subtopic'),(228,1,48,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {What are the solutions of } 2 \\sin x=-\\sqrt{3} \\text { for } 0 \\leq x \\leq 2 \\pi \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 2 \\sin x=-\\sqrt{3} \\\\ &amp; \\sin x=-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\end{aligned} $$\\(\\sin x&lt;0\\) in the \\(3^{\\text {rd }}\\) and \\(4^{\\text {th }}\\) quadrant. Since \\(\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore x &amp; =\\pi+\\frac{\\pi}{3} \\text { OR } 2 \\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{4 \\pi}{3} \\text { OR } \\frac{5 \\pi}{3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 05:19:07',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(229,1,48,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>How many solutions of the equation \\((2 \\sin x)\\left(\\cos x-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right)=0\\) lie between \\(0\\) and \\(2 \\pi\\)?</p>','<p>Solving the equation: $$ \\begin{gathered} (2 \\sin x)\\left(\\cos x-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right)=0 \\\\ \\sin x=0 \\text { OR } \\cos x=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\ \\therefore x=0, \\pi, 2 \\pi \\text { OR } x=\\frac{\\pi}{6}, \\frac{11 \\pi}{6} \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, there are 5 solutions</p>','2024-01-09 05:23:52',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(230,1,48,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {How many solutions does the equation } \\cos 3 x=0 \\text { have for } 0 \\leq x \\leq \\pi \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>When the domain restriction is \\(0 \\leq x \\leq \\pi\\): $$ 0 \\leq 3 x \\leq 3 \\pi $$ Hence, there will be 3 solutions since \\(3 x=\\frac{\\pi}{2}, \\frac{3 \\pi}{2}, \\frac{5 \\pi}{2}\\) $$\\therefore x=\\frac{\\pi}{6}, \\frac{\\pi}{2}, \\frac{5\\pi}{6}$$</p>','2024-01-09 05:26:13',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(231,1,48,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Solve the equation } 4 \\sin x+2 \\sqrt{3}=0 \\text {, where } 0 \\leq x \\leq 2 \\pi $$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 4 \\sin x+2 \\sqrt{3}=0 \\\\ &amp; 4 \\sin x=-2 \\sqrt{3} \\\\ &amp; \\sin x=-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\end{aligned} $$Since \\(\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\):$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore x &amp; =\\pi+\\frac{\\pi}{3} \\text { OR } 2 \\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{3}[\\because \\sin x \\text { is negative in } 3 \\text {rd and } 4 \\text {th quadrants }] \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{4 \\pi}{3} \\text { OR } \\frac{5 \\pi}{3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 06:11:41',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(232,1,48,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Solve } \\sin \\left(\\frac{x}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{4}\\right)=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\text { for } 0 \\leq x \\leq 2 \\pi $$</p>','<p>Considering the domain restriction:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 0 \\leq x \\leq 2 \\pi \\\\ &amp; 0 \\leq \\frac{x}{2} \\leq \\pi \\\\ &amp; -\\frac{\\pi}{4} \\leq \\frac{x}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{4} \\leq \\frac{3 \\pi}{4} \\end{aligned} $$Since \\(\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\):$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\frac{x}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{4} &amp; =\\frac{\\pi}{3} \\text { OR } \\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{3}[\\sin \\theta&gt;0 \\text { in } 1 s t, 2 \\text {nd quadrant }] \\\\ &amp; \\frac{x}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{4}=\\frac{\\pi}{3} \\text { OR } \\frac{2 \\pi}{3} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{x}{2}=\\frac{\\pi}{3}+\\frac{\\pi}{4} \\text { OR } \\frac{2 \\pi}{3}+\\frac{\\pi}{4} \\\\ &amp; \\frac{x}{2}=\\frac{7 \\pi}{12} \\text { OR } \\frac{11 \\pi}{12} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore x &amp; =\\frac{14 \\pi}{12} \\text { OR } \\frac{22 \\pi}{12} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{7 \\pi}{6} \\text { OR } \\frac{11 \\pi}{6} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 06:27:51',0,1,3,360,'hard','subtopic'),(233,1,48,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Solve } \\frac{\\sin ^3 x}{\\cos x}+\\sin x \\cos x=1 \\text { in the domain } 0 \\leq x \\leq 2 \\pi $$</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{\\sin ^3 x+\\sin x \\cos ^2 x}{\\cos x}=1 \\\\ &amp; \\frac{\\sin x\\left(\\sin ^2 x+\\cos ^2 x\\right)}{\\cos x}=1 \\\\ &amp; \\frac{\\sin x}{\\cos x}=1\\left[\\because \\sin ^2 x+\\cos ^2 x=1\\right] \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore \\tan x=1 $$Hence, for first and third quadrant angles: $$ x=\\frac{\\pi}{4} \\text{ OR } \\frac{5 \\pi}{4} $$</p>','2024-01-09 06:57:08',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(234,1,48,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Determine the number of solutions for \\(\\sin \\theta=-0.25\\), where \\(\\theta \\in[0,73 \\pi]\\) and provide reasons for your answer</p>','<p>\\(\\sin \\theta=-0.25\\) occurs twice in each period, as shown in the diagram below:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:642/244;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/fa1c8b5309c6760edcb5858c69ebfe09.png\" width=\"642\" height=\"244\"></figure><p>And since the period of a \\(\\sin \\theta\\) function is \\(2 \\pi\\):&nbsp;<br><br>For \\(\\theta \\in[0,72 \\pi]\\) there are 36 complete periods, meaning 72 solutions&nbsp;<br>For \\(\\theta \\in[72 \\pi, 73 \\pi]\\), since this is only in the first 2 quadrants, \\(\\sin \\theta&gt;0\\), meaning no solution occurs here&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, a total of 72 solutions exist</p>','2024-01-09 07:11:26',0,1,3,360,'hard','subtopic'),(235,1,48,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks]</u></p><p>Solve the equation \\(\\operatorname{cosec} \\theta+6 \\sin \\theta=5\\) for \\(0 \\leq \\theta \\leq 2 \\pi\\), giving your answer in radians and correct to the nearest 2 decimal places if necessary</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\operatorname{cosec} \\theta+6 \\sin \\theta=5 \\\\ &amp; \\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta}+6 \\sin \\theta=5 \\\\ &amp; \\frac{1+6 \\sin ^2 \\theta}{\\sin \\theta}-5=0 \\\\ &amp; \\frac{1+6 \\sin ^2 \\theta-5 \\sin \\theta}{\\sin \\theta}=0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore 6 \\sin ^2 \\theta-5 \\sin \\theta+1=0 \\end{aligned} $$Solving using the quadratic formula: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\sin \\theta &amp; =\\frac{5 \\pm \\sqrt{(-5)^2-4(6)(1)}}{2(6)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5 \\pm \\sqrt{1}}{12} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5 \\pm 1}{12} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\text { OR } \\frac{1}{3} \\end{aligned} $$For \\(\\sin \\theta=\\frac{1}{2}\\): $$ \\therefore \\theta=\\frac{\\pi}{6} \\text { OR } \\frac{5 \\pi}{6} $$ For \\(\\sin \\theta=\\frac{1}{3}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\theta &amp; =0.34 \\text { OR } \\pi-0.34 \\\\ &amp; =0.34 \\text { OR } 2.80 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 07:19:42',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(236,1,49,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>\\(\\text {A jogger runs on a bearing of } 120^{\\circ} \\text { from point } \\mathrm{A} \\text { to point } \\mathrm{B}\\)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:275/269;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9010ea142d06c892db131bbcae1bfc9e.jpeg\" width=\"275\" height=\"269\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the true bearing of point A from point B?</p>','<p>Given that \\(\\mathrm{N}\\) is any point in the Northern direction: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle A B N &amp; =180^{\\circ}-120^{\\circ}[ \\ \\because \\text { co }- \\text { interior angles are supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =60^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the bearing of A from \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) will be: $$ 360^{\\circ}-60^{\\circ}=300^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T} $$</p>','2024-01-09 08:05:55',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(237,1,49,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>Hank leaves island \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) in a canoe and rows \\(136 \\mathrm{~km}\\) on a bearing of \\(75^{\\circ}\\) to island \\(\\mathrm{B} . \\mathrm{He}\\) then rows on a bearing of \\(203^{\\circ}\\) for \\(186 \\mathrm{~km}\\) to island C, as shown in the diagram below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:41.91%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:746/1017;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9c0d79c66b6f4510140fa17f3374db3a.png\" width=\"746\" height=\"1017\"></figure><p>i. Show that the size of \\(\\angle A B C=x^{\\circ} \\ \\)<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the distance from island \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) to island \\(\\mathrm{A}\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Hanks wants to row from island \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) directly to island \\(\\mathrm{A}\\). On what bearing will he row? Give your answer to the nearest minute<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. \\(\\quad\\) Since \\(AN\\) and \\(BN\\) are parallel: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle A B N &amp; =180^{\\circ}-\\angle N A B[\\because \\text { Collinear angles supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =180^{\\circ}-75^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =105^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle A B C &amp; =360^{\\circ}-105^{\\circ}-203^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =52^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Considering \\(\\triangle A B C\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:236/268;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e1855a84d6c366ea78d0735edfa9ad95.jpeg\" width=\"236\" height=\"268\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{aligned} A C^2 &amp; =A B^2+B C^2-2(A B)(B C) \\cos 52^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =136^2+186^2-2 \\times 136 \\times 186 \\cos 52^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 21944.45 \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore A C=148 \\mathrm{~km} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. To find the bearing, we need to first find the value of \\(\\angle A C B, \\angle N C B\\) and \\(\\angle N C A\\)</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:43.97%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:751/1102;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/308e45c0b4f56c10de555edcec8c8391.png\" width=\"751\" height=\"1102\"></figure><p>Finding \\(\\angle A C B\\) using cosine rule:$$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos \\angle A C B &amp; =\\frac{(A C)^2+(B C)^2-(A B)^2}{2(A C)(B C)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{148^2+186^2-136^2}{2 \\times 148 \\times 186} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3167}{4588} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore \\angle A C B=46^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime} $$Next, we can find the value of \\(\\angle N C B\\) using collinear angles for parallel lines: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle N C B &amp; =180^{\\circ}-\\angle C B N \\\\ &amp; =180^{\\circ}-\\left(360^{\\circ}-203^{\\circ}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =180^{\\circ}-157^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =23^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle A C N &amp; =\\angle A C B-\\angle N C B \\\\ &amp; =46^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime}-23^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =23^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime} \\end{aligned} $$Hence, since \\(\\angle A C N=23^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime}\\), the bearing of \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) from \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) will be: $$ 360^{\\circ}-23^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime}=336^{\\circ} 39^{\\prime} T $$</p>','2024-01-09 08:15:34',0,1,5,540,'hard','subtopic'),(238,1,49,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>A horizontal bridge is built between the points A and B. The bridge has multiply vertical pylons, one of which is ST and supported by cables SP and SR which are attached to its top.</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:71.91%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1321/546;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/4a8c893a4969ff8ec92d010cc5d0a7da.png\" width=\"1321\" height=\"546\"></figure><p>The section of the pylon, SQ which is above the bridge is \\(11 \\mathrm{~m}\\) long and \\(\\angle S R Q=58^{\\circ}\\). The distance \\(\\mathrm{AQ}\\) is \\(26 \\mathrm{~m}\\), and \\(P\\) is the midpoint of \\(\\mathrm{AQ}\\)</p><p>i. Find the length of the cable SR to the nearest metre&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the size of \\(\\angle S P Q\\) to the nearest minute&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Considering \\(\\triangle S Q R\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:270/315;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/5596ec3a78b7d2e47429ae6deda113fb.jpeg\" width=\"270\" height=\"315\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\sin 52^{\\circ}=\\frac{11}{S R} \\\\ &amp; S R=\\frac{11}{\\sin 52^{\\circ}} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore S R \\approx 14 m \\text { [nearest metre] } \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>ii. Since \\(\\mathrm{P}\\) is the midpoint of \\(\\mathrm{AQ}\\), then \\(P Q=\\frac{26}{2}=13 \\mathrm{~m}\\)&nbsp;<br>Hence, considering \\(\\triangle S P Q\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:354/239;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/3d57b24f287b0ce4bd6b8c8cd4dbc404.jpeg\" width=\"354\" height=\"239\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\tan x^{\\circ}=\\frac{11}{13} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x \\approx 40^{\\circ} 14^{\\prime \\prime} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the size of \\(\\angle S P Q\\) is \\(40^{\\circ} 14^{\\prime \\prime}\\)</p>','2024-01-09 09:57:06',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(239,1,49,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A hiker walks \\(6 \\mathrm{~km}\\) from camp (point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) ) to point \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) in a direction of \\(N 46^{\\circ} E\\). He then walks \\(4 \\mathrm{~km}\\) due east to point \\(\\mathrm{B}\\), as shown in the diagram below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:68.02%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1072/813;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/11b3043a0041521679899c81b3df8023.png\" width=\"1072\" height=\"813\"></figure><p>i. Calculate the shortest distance between point B and the camp, giving your answer to the nearest 3 significant figures&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Calculate the bearing of the hiker at point $\\mathrm{B}$ from the camp, giving your answer to the nearest degree&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. To calculate the value of \\(\\mathrm{BC}\\) using cosine rule, we must first find the value of \\(\\angle B A C\\)<br><br>To do so, construct interval \\(A N_1\\) such that it points to North:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:484/389;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e950cbff57958e67df366a453f700e8a.png\" width=\"484\" height=\"389\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle C A N_1 &amp; =180^{\\circ}-46^{\\circ}[\\because \\text { co }- \\text { interior angles supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =134^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) is due east of \\(\\mathrm{A}, \\angle N_1 A B=90^{\\circ}\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle C A B &amp; =360^{\\circ}-134^{\\circ}-90^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =136^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Hence, now using cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} B C^2 &amp; =A C^2+A B^2-2(A C)(A B) \\cos \\angle C A B \\\\ B C^2 &amp; =6^2+4^2-2(6)(4) \\cos 136^{\\circ} \\\\ B C^2 &amp; \\approx 86.52831 \\\\ \\therefore B C &amp; \\approx 9.30 \\mathrm{~km}[\\text { nearest } 3 \\text { sig fig }] \\end{aligned} $$ii. To find the bearing of \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) from \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), we must first find \\(\\angle A C B\\) To do so, we will use cosine rule [sine rule may be used too, but we must check for ambiguous case!]$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\cos \\angle A C B &amp; =\\frac{A C^2+B C^2-A B^2}{2(A C)(B C)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{6^2+9.3^2-4^2}{2(6)(9.3)} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 0.9542 \\\\ \\therefore \\angle A C B &amp; \\approx 17.4055^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Note that it is good habit to avoid rounding too much during our working out to avoid getting an inaccurate answer Hence, the bearing of \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) from \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) may be given as: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Bearing } &amp; =46^{\\circ}+17.4055^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 63^{\\circ}[\\text {nearest degree}] \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 10:20:09',0,1,4,420,'hard','subtopic'),(240,1,49,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A ship sails \\(120 \\mathrm{~km}\\) from point A to point B on a bearing of \\(145^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T}\\). The ship then sails from point \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) on a bearing of \\(060^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T}\\) to point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) which is \\(150 \\mathrm{~km}\\) away.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:643/283;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/3a81732e4bc9d227942026cfc58ed49b.jpeg\" width=\"643\" height=\"283\"></figure><p>i. Find the distance from point \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) to point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), giving your answer correct to two decimal places &nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the bearing of point \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) from point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), giving your answer correct to the nearest degree&nbsp; &nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. First filling in the diagram with the given information:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:731/309;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/468d965b18a625e0d4c795b9c2d84418.jpeg\" width=\"731\" height=\"309\"></figure><p>Since \\(\\angle N A B=145^{\\circ}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle N B A &amp; =180^{\\circ}-145^{\\circ}[\\text { co }- \\text { interior angles supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =35^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle A B C &amp; =60^{\\circ}+35^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =95^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Considering the cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} A C^2= &amp; A B^2+B C^2-2(A B)(A C) \\cos \\angle A B C \\\\ = &amp; 120^2+150^2-2(120)(150) \\cos 95^{\\circ} \\\\ = &amp; 40037.6 \\\\ &amp; \\quad \\therefore A C \\approx 200.09 \\mathrm{~km} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. The logic behind this is that if we are able to determine the value of \\(\\angle N C A\\), then the bearing would equal to \\(360^{\\circ}-\\angle N C A\\). To find \\(\\angle N C A\\), we must find \\(\\angle N A C\\) since \\(\\angle N C A=180^{\\circ}-\\angle N A C[\\) co-interior \\(]\\).&nbsp;<br><br>To find \\(\\angle N A C\\), we must find \\(\\angle C A B\\) since \\(\\angle N A C=145^{\\circ}-\\angle C A B\\).</p><p><br>Hence, to find \\(\\angle C A B\\), we consider the cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos \\angle C A B &amp; =\\frac{A C^2+A B^2-B C^2}{2(A C)(A B)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{200.09^2+120^2-150^2}{2(200.09)(120)} \\\\ &amp; =0.665 \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore \\angle C A B \\approx 48^{\\circ} \\text { [nearest degree] } $$ Thus, we can find \\(\\angle N A C\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle N A C &amp; =145^{\\circ}-48^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =97^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Thus, we can find \\(\\angle N C A\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle N C A &amp; =180^{\\circ}-97^{\\circ}[\\text { co }- \\text { interior angles supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =83^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the bearing will be: $$ 360^{\\circ}-83^{\\circ}=277^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T} $$</p>','2024-01-09 10:30:50',0,1,4,480,'hard','subtopic'),(241,1,49,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [7 marks total]</u></p><p>A boat leaves port \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) on a bearing of \\(300^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T}\\) and sails for four hours at an average speed of \\(12 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}\\) until point \\(X\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Simultaneously, Michael Phelps also leaves from port A and travels due North to island \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) which is \\(25 \\mathrm{~km}\\) from port \\(\\mathrm{A}\\).</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:404/245;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/588de62730755b9a9029df80ab133c0e.jpeg\" width=\"404\" height=\"245\"></figure><p>i. Calculate the distance between point \\(X\\) and island B&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the bearing of island B from point \\(X\\) to the nearest degree&nbsp;</p><p>[3 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. After spending several hours doing push ups on the island, Michael Phelps swims due South back to point A. How far North of the port will Michael Phelps be when he is directly East of the boat?&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. 4 hours at an average speed of \\(12 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}\\) means that the distance \\(\\mathrm{XA}\\) is \\(4 \\times 12=\\) \\(48 \\mathrm{~km}\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Moreover, \\(\\angle B A X=360^{\\circ}-300^{\\circ}=60^{\\circ}\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, to find the value of \\(\\mathrm{BX}\\) we consider the cosine rule: $$ \\begin{gathered} B X^2=A B^2+A X^2-2(A B)(A X) \\cos \\angle B A X \\\\ B X^2=25^2+48^2-2(25)(48) \\cos \\angle 60^{\\circ} \\\\ B X^2=1729 \\\\ \\quad \\therefore B X=\\sqrt{1729} \\mathrm{~km} \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Let NX be an interval in the northern direction:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:386/223;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/039d246856cf39f7e1212297ac5ec5d3.jpeg\" width=\"386\" height=\"223\"></figure><p>The bearing of \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) from \\(\\mathrm{X}\\) is given as the angle \\(\\angle N X B\\) To find \\(\\angle N X B\\), we must consider \\(\\angle N X A-\\angle B X A=\\angle N X B\\) $$ \\begin{gathered} \\angle B A X=360^{\\circ}-300^{\\circ}=60^{\\circ} \\\\ \\therefore \\angle N X A=180^{\\circ}-60^{\\circ}=120^{\\circ}[\\text { co - interior angles supplementary }] \\end{gathered} $$ To find \\(\\angle B X A\\), consider the cosine rule:$$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos \\angle B X A &amp; =\\frac{B X^2+X A^2-A B^2}{2(B X)(X A)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1729+48^2-25^2}{2 \\sqrt{1729}(48)} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 0.85375 \\end{aligned} $$\\(\\angle B X A \\approx 31^{\\circ}\\) [nearest degree] Hence, \\(\\angle N X B=120^{\\circ}-31^{\\circ}=89^{\\circ}\\) $$ \\therefore \\text { Bearing }=089^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Let the point where Michael Phelps is directly east of point \\(\\mathrm{X}\\) be point \\(\\mathrm{E}\\), with \\(\\angle A E X=90^{\\circ}\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, sketching the diagram:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:366/198;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/7c3897bbc2df0e22596446f85fc609c9.jpeg\" width=\"366\" height=\"198\"></figure><p>Note that \\(\\angle X A E=\\angle X A B=60^{\\circ}\\)&nbsp;<br>Since we need to find the value of AE, consider: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos 60^{\\circ} &amp; =\\frac{A E}{A X} \\\\ \\therefore A E &amp; =A X \\cos 60^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =48 \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\ &amp; =24 \\mathrm{~km} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-09 10:45:37',0,1,7,840,'hard','subtopic'),(242,1,50,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>OT is a tower on horizontal group. \\(\\triangle O T A\\) is a right - angle triangle at \\(\\angle A O T\\). Two straight cables, \\(AT\\) and \\(BT\\) connect the top of the tower to the ground.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:447/236;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e91b30c4e4067138e4c59472649fc0de.jpeg\" width=\"447\" height=\"236\"></figure><p>AT and BT make angles with the ground of \\(34^{\\circ}\\) and \\(44^{\\circ}\\) respectively. BT is \\(20 \\mathrm{~m}\\) closer to the base of the tower compared to AT.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the length of the cable AT, correct to 2 significant figures?</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle A B T &amp; =180^{\\circ}-44^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =136^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle A T B &amp; \\left.=180^{\\circ}-34^{\\circ}-136^{\\circ} \\text { [interior angle sum of triangle }\\right] \\\\ &amp; =10^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Therefore, considering sine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{A T}{\\sin 136^{\\circ}}=\\frac{A B}{\\sin 10^{\\circ}} \\\\ &amp; A T=\\frac{20}{\\sin 10^{\\circ}} \\times \\sin 136^{\\circ} \\\\ &nbsp;\\end{aligned} $$</p><p>$$\\therefore A T \\approx 80 m [2 \\operatorname{sig} \\text { figs}]$$</p>','2024-01-11 22:00:03',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(243,1,50,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A tourist who is \\(y\\) metres due south of a tower sees the top of it with an angle of elevation \\(10^{\\circ}\\). A second tourist is \\(x\\) metres due east of the tower and sees the top of it with an angle of elevation \\(13^{\\circ}\\). The two tourists are known to be \\(880 \\mathrm{~m}\\) apart</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:52.33%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:764/574;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/6b087b186cb07839281cb29e49087c05.png\" width=\"764\" height=\"574\"></figure><p>i. Show that \\(y=\\frac{h}{\\tan 10^{\\circ}}\\)<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the height \\((h)\\) of the tower to the nearest metre<br>[3 marks]</p>','<p>i. Considering the triangle below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:47.45%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:734/384;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ec7c7a4adab3b32d3e4e2d3ab62f182d.png\" width=\"734\" height=\"384\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\tan 10^{\\circ}=\\frac{h}{y} \\\\ y=\\frac{h}{\\tan 10^{\\circ}} \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>$ \\text {ii. Considering the other triangle in our diagram: } $</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:51.4%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:863/443;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/02f550d2bbfde90795588daac0c093fa.png\" width=\"863\" height=\"443\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\tan 13^{\\circ}=\\frac{h}{x} \\\\ x=\\frac{h}{\\tan 13^{\\circ}} \\end{gathered} $$ Finally, considering the bottom triangle:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:44.06%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:779/520;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f552a847406f2d411fa2a67787944727.png\" width=\"779\" height=\"520\"></figure><p>Hence, considering the pythagoras theorem: $$ \\begin{gathered} x^2+y^2=880^2 \\\\ \\left(\\frac{h}{\\tan 13}\\right)^2+\\left(\\frac{h}{\\tan 10}\\right)^2=880^2 \\\\ \\frac{h^2}{\\tan ^2 13}+\\frac{h^2}{\\tan ^2 10}=880^2 \\\\ h^2\\left(\\frac{1}{\\tan ^2 13}+\\frac{1}{\\tan ^2 10}\\right)=880^2 \\\\ h^2=\\frac{880^2}{\\left(\\frac{1}{\\tan ^2 13}+\\frac{1}{\\tan ^2 10}\\right)} \\\\ =15206.64043 \\\\ \\end{gathered} $$$$\\therefore h \\approx 123 m \\text { (nearest metre) }$$</p>','2024-01-11 22:13:21',0,1,4,420,'hard','subtopic'),(244,0,50,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>Alberto stands at a point A, \\(150 \\mathrm{~m}\\) east of the tower OT which stands at a height of \\(h\\) metres. The angle of elevation of \\(\\mathrm{T}\\) from point \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) is \\(20^{\\circ}\\). Ben stands at point \\(\\mathrm{B}\\), due south of the tower OT. The angle of elevation to the top of the tower from B is \\(12^{\\circ}\\).</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:372/428;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/1ad351be433241e44eee5b224aea225b.png\" width=\"372\" height=\"428\"></figure><p>i. Find the height of the tower, h, correct to 3 significant figures</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find how far Ben is from the bottom of the tower, giving your answer correct to 3 significant figures&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. What is the bearing of Ben from Alberto? Give your answer to the nearest minute&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Considering &nbsp;\\(\\triangle A T O\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:368/235;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/147ebb3298e02bf937b86421ef8b7045.jpeg\" width=\"368\" height=\"235\"></figure><p>Since \\(\\sin 20^{\\circ}=\\frac{h}{150}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore h &amp; =150 \\times \\sin 20^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 51.3 m \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Now knowing that \\(h=51.3\\), considering \\(\\triangle B T O\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:474/259;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/c9571429be2a726ec0b2f9a15de77419.jpeg\" width=\"474\" height=\"259\"></figure><p>Since \\(\\tan 12^{\\circ}=\\frac{51.3}{B O}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore B O &amp; =\\frac{51.3}{\\tan 12^{\\circ}} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 241 m \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Drawing line \\(\\mathrm{AN}\\) to represent the North direction on the diagram:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:49.5%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1047/854;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/81ce88a9e116e93559226ddf00787e03.png\" width=\"1047\" height=\"854\"></figure><p>Now consider \\(\\triangle A B O\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:433/257;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e11348d3e1541bee63e22cf1a9fd9e78.jpeg\" width=\"433\" height=\"257\"></figure><p>To find \\(\\angle A B O\\):$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\tan \\angle A B O=\\frac{150}{241} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\angle A B O \\approx 31^{\\circ} 54^{\\prime} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, since \\(\\mathrm{BO}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{AN}\\) are parallel lines: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle B A N &amp; =180^{\\circ}-\\angle A B O \\\\ &amp; =180^{\\circ}-31^{\\circ} 54^{\\prime} \\\\ &amp; =148^{\\circ} 6^{\\prime} \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the bearing of point B from A will be: $$ 360^{\\circ}-148^{\\circ} 6=211^{\\circ} 54^{\\prime} \\mathrm{T} $$</p>','2024-01-11 23:02:02',0,1,4,420,'hard','subtopic'),(245,1,50,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A surveyor stands at a point \\(S\\), which is due South of the tower \\(OT\\) which has a height of \\(h\\) metres. The angle of elevation of the top of the tower \\(T\\) from \\(S\\) is \\(30^{\\circ}\\). The surveyor then walks 100 metres to point \\(B\\), which is on a bearing of \\(240^{\\circ}\\) from the foot of tower \\(O\\). The angle of elevation of the top of the tower \\(T\\) from \\(B\\) is \\(45^{\\circ}\\).</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:45.95%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:873/551;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a3ebc561553858edfdfba7675364b646.png\" width=\"873\" height=\"551\"></figure><p>i. Express the length of \\(OS\\) in terms of \\(h\\)<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the height of the tower, giving your answer correct to 1 decimal place<br>[3 marks]</p>','<p>i. Considering the \\(\\triangle TOS\\):</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:40.64%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:752/485;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/8de6b52b41e4596be47f6bc18e955417.png\" width=\"752\" height=\"485\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\tan 30^{\\circ} &amp; =\\frac{\\text { opposite }}{\\text { adjacent }} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{h}{O S} \\\\ \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} &amp; =\\frac{h}{O S} \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore O S &nbsp;=h \\sqrt{3} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Considering the \\(\\triangle T O B\\):</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:31.78%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:623/591;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/579165af11a7aef7f566544c3154a750.png\" width=\"623\" height=\"591\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\tan 45^{\\circ}=\\frac{h}{O B} \\\\ 1=\\frac{h}{O B} \\\\ \\therefore O B=h \\end{gathered} $$ Finally, considering the bottom \\(\\triangle B O S\\):</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:41.1%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:855/448;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/c8a0af3464655090ccc894b92be872e4.png\" width=\"855\" height=\"448\"></figure><p>Notice here that \\(\\angle B O S=240^{\\circ}-180^{\\circ}=60^{\\circ}\\) (Difference of bearings)&nbsp;<br><br>Considering the cosine rule for \\(\\triangle B O S\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} 100^2=h^2 &amp; +(h \\sqrt{3})^2-2(h)(h \\sqrt{3}) \\cos 60^{\\circ} \\\\ 100^2 &amp; =h^2+3 h^2-2 \\sqrt{3} h^2 \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\ &amp; =4 h^2-\\sqrt{3} h^2 \\\\ &amp; =h^2(4-\\sqrt{3}) \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore h^2=\\frac{100^2}{4-\\sqrt{3}} \\\\ \\therefore h &amp; =\\frac{100}{\\sqrt{4-\\sqrt{3}}} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 66 m \\text { (nearest metre) } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-12 09:32:30',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(246,1,50,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [6 marks total]</u></p><p>A road on horizontal ground has two parallel edges. CD is a vertical telegraph pole of height $h$ metres which stands on top of point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) on one edge of the road. \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) are two points on the opposite side such that \\(AB=9 m\\) and \\(\\angle A C B=60^{\\circ}\\). From \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{B}\\), the angles of elevation to the top of the telegraph pole \\(\\mathrm{D}\\) are \\(60^{\\circ}\\) and \\(30^{\\circ}\\) respectively.</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:47.16%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1406/829;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f424cae3a688f4d1696c29d692c76193.png\" width=\"1406\" height=\"829\"></figure><p>i. Find the exact height of the flagpole, h</p><p>[3 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. By considering the area of \\(\\triangle A B C\\), find the exact width of the footpath \\(w\\)</p><p>[3 marks]</p>','<p>i. Looking at \\(\\triangle \\mathrm{ABC}\\):</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:44.69%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:647/291;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/15748c2f0897bfeac6451be37cb03bf5.jpeg\" width=\"647\" height=\"291\"></figure><p>The idea to consider here is that if we are able to find expressions for \\(A C\\) and \\(A B\\), we are able to use the cosine rule.&nbsp;<br><br>Hence: Considering \\(\\triangle A C D\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:376/241;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/cd48be358353b419987f5c5e7f8e2843.jpeg\" width=\"376\" height=\"241\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{gathered} \\tan 60^{\\circ}=\\frac{h}{A C} \\\\ \\therefore A C=\\frac{h}{\\tan 60^{\\circ}}=\\frac{h}{\\sqrt{3}} \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>Considering \\(\\triangle B C D\\):</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:378/234;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/2e265252923cc3628e44aed1db07abfb.jpeg\" width=\"378\" height=\"234\"></figure><p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\tan 30^{\\circ} &amp; =\\frac{h}{B C} \\\\ \\therefore B C &amp; =\\frac{h}{\\tan 30^{\\circ}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{h}{\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{3} h \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, looking at \\(\\triangle A B C\\) again:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:42.49%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:645/290;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/7879da5928f0b396b4aefc66615f5987.jpeg\" width=\"645\" height=\"290\"></figure><p>Considering cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 9^2=(\\sqrt{3} h)^2+\\left(\\frac{h}{\\sqrt{3}}\\right)^2-2(\\sqrt{3} h)\\left(\\frac{h}{\\sqrt{3}}\\right) \\cos 60^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; 81=3 h^2+\\frac{h^2}{3}-2 h^2\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3}}\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right) \\\\ &amp; 81=\\frac{10 h^2}{3}-h^2 \\\\ &amp; 81=\\frac{7 h^2}{3} \\\\ &amp; h^2=\\frac{243}{7} \\\\ &amp; &nbsp;\\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore h=\\sqrt{\\frac{243}{7}}$$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. There are two ways to find the area of \\(\\triangle A B C\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} \\text { Area }=\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\text { base } \\times \\text { height } \\\\ O R \\\\ \\text { Area }=\\frac{1}{2} \\times B C \\times A C \\times \\sin 60^{\\circ} \\end{gathered} $$Since we now know the value of \\(h\\), we can find the area of \\(\\triangle A B C\\) using the sine rule formula:$$ \\text {} \\begin{aligned} Area \\ of \\ \\triangle A B C &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\sqrt{3} h \\times \\frac{h}{\\sqrt{3}} \\times \\sin 60^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\sqrt{3}\\left(\\sqrt{\\frac{241}{7}}\\right) \\times \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\left(\\sqrt{\\frac{241}{7}}\\right) \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{241}{7} \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{241 \\sqrt{3}}{28} \\mathrm{~m}^2 \\end{aligned} $$Therefore, now that we know the area value: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{241 \\sqrt{3}}{28}=\\frac{1}{2} \\times w \\times A B \\\\ &amp; \\frac{241 \\sqrt{3}}{14}=9 w \\\\ &amp; \\therefore w=\\frac{241 \\sqrt{3}}{126} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-12 09:57:59',0,1,6,600,'hard','subtopic'),(247,1,51,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The expression \\(3^{2 x+1} \\times\\left(3^{x+2}\\right)^2\\) can be simplified into which of the following?</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>Simplifying by first expanding the brackets: $$ \\begin{aligned} 3^{2 x+1} \\times\\left(3^{x+2}\\right)^2 &amp; =3^{2 x+1} \\times 3^{2 x+4} \\\\ &amp; =3^{2 x+1+2 x+4} \\\\ &amp; =3^{4 x+5} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-14 02:24:26',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(248,1,51,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following options are equivalent to the expression: $$\\frac{\\left(7^m \\times 7^{3 n}\\right)^2}{7}$$</p>','<p>Simplifying by first expressing the inside of the bracket as one power: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{\\left(7^m \\times 7^{3 n}\\right)^2}{7} &amp; =\\frac{\\left(7^{m+3 n}\\right)^2}{7} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{7^{2 m+6 n}}{7} \\\\ &amp; =7^{2 m+6 n-1} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-14 02:52:57',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(249,1,51,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The expression \\((-2)^{m+n} \\times(-2)^{-m-n} \\div(-2)^{m-n}\\) can be simplified into which of the following?</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} (-2)^{m+n} \\times(-2)^{-m-n} \\div(-2)^{m-n} &amp; =(-2)^{(m+n)+(-m-n)-(m-n)} \\\\ &amp; =(-2)^{m+n-m-n-m+n} \\\\ &amp; =(-2)^{n-m} \\end{aligned} $$ Note: be careful that for this question, the -2 must be in brackets!</p>','2024-01-14 02:54:24',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(250,1,51,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following options are equivalent to the expression: $$\\frac{9^{6 x} \\times 3^{2 m}}{3}$$</p>','<p>This question is tricky since the bases are not all the same.&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, we must first convert 9 into $3^2$ : $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{9^{6 x} \\times 3^{2 m}}{3} &amp; =\\frac{\\left(3^2\\right)^{6 x} \\times 3^{2 m}}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3^{12 x} \\times 3^{2 m}}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3^{12 x+2 m}}{3} \\\\ &amp; =3^{12 x+2 m-1} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-14 02:58:28',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(251,1,51,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Simplify $$\\frac{x^3 m^{-5} y^4}{x^5 m^{-2} y^{-1}}$$&nbsp;Leaving your answer in positive indices only</p>','<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{x^3 m^{-5} y^4}{x^5 m^{-2} y^{-1}} &amp; =x^{3-5} m^{-5--2} y^{4--1} \\\\ &amp; =x^{-2} m^{-3} y^5 \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{y^5}{x^2 m^3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-14 02:59:56',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(252,1,51,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Simplify the following expression into one fraction with only positive indices: $$ \\frac{x^{-1}+x^{-2}}{y^{-2}+y^{-1}} $$</p>','<p>First converting everything into in terms of positive indices:$$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{x^{-1}+x^{-2}}{y^{-2}+y^{-1}} &amp; =\\frac{\\frac{1}{x}+\\frac{1}{x^2}}{\\frac{1}{y^2}+\\frac{1}{y}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\frac{x+1}{x^2}}{\\frac{1+y}{y^2}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x+1}{x^2} \\div \\frac{1+y}{y^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x+1}{x^2} \\times \\frac{y^2}{1+y} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{y^2(x+1)}{x^2(1+y)} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-14 03:03:14',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(253,1,52,'freetext','1.609','<p><u>Short Answer [1 mark]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Evaluate } \\ln 5 \\text { correct to } 4 \\text { significant figures } $$</p>','<p>Inputting this directly into our calculator: $$ \\ln 5 \\approx 1.609 \\text { (4 sig figs) } $$</p>','2024-01-14 06:35:24',0,1,1,30,'easy','subtopic'),(254,1,52,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the correct solution to: $$\\log _3 x=3$$</p>','<p>Rearranging the logarithm: $$ \\begin{aligned} x &amp; =3^3 \\\\ &amp; =27 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-14 06:36:37',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(255,1,52,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the correct solution to: $$\\log _5 125=x$$</p>','<p>Rearranging the logarithm: $$ \\begin{gathered} 5^x=125 \\\\ \\therefore x=3 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-14 06:38:03',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(256,1,52,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the correct solution to \\(\\log _2(2 x+5)=2\\)?</p>','<p>Rearranging the logarithm: $$ \\begin{gathered} 2^2=2 x+5 \\\\ 4=2 x+5 \\\\ 2 x=-1 \\\\ \\therefore x=-\\frac{1}{2} \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-14 06:39:31',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(257,1,52,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Solve } 2^x=\\frac{1}{32} $$</p>','<p>Since \\(2^{-5}=\\frac{1}{32}\\): $$ \\therefore x=-5 $$</p>','2024-01-14 06:40:58',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(258,1,53,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ 2 \\ln x-\\ln 3 x \\text { is equal to: } $$</p>','<p>Applying our logarithmic laws:&nbsp;<br><br>Since \\(a \\ln b=\\ln b^a\\): $$ \\therefore 2 \\ln x-\\ln 3 x=\\ln x^2-\\ln 3 x $$ Then, since \\(\\ln a-\\ln b=\\ln \\frac{a}{b}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\ln x^2-\\ln 3 x &amp; =\\ln \\left(\\frac{x^2}{3 x}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =\\ln \\left(\\frac{x}{3}\\right) \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-15 07:45:38',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(259,1,53,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Let } a=e^x \\text {, which expression is equal to } \\ln \\left(a^3\\right) \\text {?} $$</p>','<p>Considering \\(a^3\\): $$ a^3=e^{3 x} $$ Therefore, considering the logarithm law that \\(\\log _a a^x=a\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\ln a^3 &amp; =\\ln e^{3 x} \\\\ &amp; =3 x \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-15 07:50:15',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(260,1,53,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { Which of the following is equal to } e^{-4\\left(\\log _e x\\right)} \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>First applying our logarithm law where \\(a \\ln b=\\ln b^a\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} -4 \\log _e x=\\log _e x^{-4} \\\\ \\therefore e^{-4\\left(\\log _e x\\right)}=e^{\\log _e x^{-4}} \\end{gathered} $$ Then applying our second logarithmic law where \\(a^{\\log _a b}=b\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore e^{\\log _e x^{-4}} &amp; =x^{-4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{x^4} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-15 07:55:44',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(261,1,53,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Let } m=e^{-\\frac{3}{2} y} \\text { , which expression is equal to } \\log _e\\left(m^4\\right) \\text {? } $$</p>','<p>Since \\(m=e^{-\\frac{3}{2} y}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\log _e\\left(m^4\\right) &amp; =\\log _e\\left(\\left(e^{-\\frac{3}{2} y}\\right)^4\\right) \\\\ &amp; =\\log _e\\left(e^{-6 y}\\right) \\end{aligned} $$ Recall the logarithmic law that: $$ \\log _e e^m=m $$ Therefore, applying that to this case: $$ \\therefore \\log _e\\left(e^{-6 y}\\right)=-6 y $$</p>','2024-01-15 07:59:13',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(262,1,53,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Let \\(\\log _a 2=x\\) and \\(\\log _a 3=y\\).&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find an expression for \\(\\log _a 12\\) in terms of \\(x\\) and \\(y\\)</p>','<p>Splitting up \\(\\log _a 12\\): $$ \\log _a 12=\\log _a(4 \\times 3) $$ Applying our logarithmic law of addition: $$ \\log _a(4 \\times 3)=\\log _a(4)+\\log _a(3) $$ Then applying our logarithmic law of powers: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\log _a(4)+\\log _a(3) &amp; =\\log _a\\left(2^2\\right)+\\log _a(3) \\\\ &amp; =2 \\log _a(2)+\\log _a(3) \\\\ &amp; =2 x+y \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-15 08:03:43',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(263,1,53,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>It is given that: \\(\\log _a\\left(1+\\frac{1}{8}\\right)=p,&nbsp;\\ \\log _a\\left(1+\\frac{1}{15}\\right)=q, \\ \\log _a\\left(1+\\frac{1}{24}\\right)=r\\).&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, prove that: $$p-q-r=\\log _a\\left[1+\\frac{1}{80}\\right]$$</p>','<p>Considering the LHS of the equation: $$ \\begin{gathered} p-q-r=\\log _a\\left(1+\\frac{1}{8}\\right)-\\log _a\\left(1+\\frac{1}{15}\\right) \\\\ -\\log _a\\left(1+\\frac{1}{24}\\right) \\end{gathered} $$ Recall the logarithmic law that: $$ \\log _a x-\\log _a y=\\log _a \\frac{x}{y} $$ Apply that to our equation:$$ \\begin{aligned} p-q-r &amp; =\\log _a\\left[\\frac{1+\\frac{1}{8}}{\\left(1+\\frac{1}{15}\\right) \\times\\left(1+\\frac{1}{24}\\right)}\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\log _a\\left[\\frac{\\frac{9}{8}}{\\left(\\frac{16}{15}\\right) \\times\\left(\\frac{25}{24}\\right)}\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\log _a\\left[\\frac{\\frac{9}{8}}{\\left(\\frac{2}{3}\\right) \\times\\left(\\frac{5}{3}\\right)}\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\log _a\\left[\\frac{\\frac{9}{8}}{\\frac{10}{9}}\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\log _a\\left[\\frac{9}{8} \\times \\frac{9}{10}\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\log _a\\left[\\frac{81}{80}\\right] \\\\ \\therefore p &amp; -q-r=\\log _a\\left[1+\\frac{1}{80}\\right] \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-15 08:08:09',0,1,2,180,'hard','subtopic'),(264,1,54,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {The solutions to } e^{4 x}-5 e^{2 x}+6=0 \\text { are } x= $$</p>','<p>Notice here that this is an equation that\'s reducible to a quadratic. In other words: $$ \\begin{gathered} u=e^{2 x} \\\\ \\therefore u^2-5 u+6=0 \\end{gathered} $$ Factorising this: $$ \\begin{gathered} (u-3)(u-2)=0 \\\\ \\therefore u=3 \\text { OR } 2 \\\\ \\therefore e^{2 x}=3 \\text { OR } 2 \\end{gathered} $$ Converting this to logarithms: $$ \\begin{gathered} 2 x=\\ln 3 \\text { OR } 2 x=\\ln 2 \\\\ \\therefore x=\\frac{1}{2} \\ln 3 \\text { OR } x=\\frac{1}{2} \\ln 2 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-15 08:33:28',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(265,1,54,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Solve } 2^x=\\frac{1}{32} $$</p>','<p>Converting the RHS into an exponential: $$ 2^x=2^{-5} $$ Hence, equating the indices: $$ \\therefore x=-5 $$</p>','2024-01-15 08:38:44',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(266,1,54,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Solve } 3^{3 x-2}=27 $$</p>','<p>Converting the RHS into an exponential: $$ 3^{3 x-2}=3^3 $$ Hence, equating the indices: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 3 x-2=3 \\\\ &amp; 3 x=5 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x=\\frac{5}{3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-15 08:45:35',0,1,2,180,'easy','subtopic'),(267,1,54,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>$$ \\text {Evaluate } 10^x \\text {, given that } \\frac{4^x}{2^{x+1}}=\\frac{3}{5^x} $$You are not required to find the value of \\(x\\) for this question</p>','<p>First converting \\(4^x=2^{2 x}\\): $$ \\therefore \\frac{2^{2 x}}{2^{x+1}}=\\frac{3}{5^x} $$ Then subtracting indices for the LHS: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 2^{2 x-(x+1)}=\\frac{3}{5^x} \\\\ &amp; 2^{x-1}=\\frac{3}{5^x} \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(2^{x-1}=\\frac{2^x}{2}\\): $$ \\therefore \\frac{2^x}{2}=\\frac{3}{5^x} $$Now cross multiplying: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 2^x \\times 5^x=6 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore 10^x=6 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-15 08:47:55',0,1,2,240,'hard','subtopic'),(268,1,54,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Solve the following equation for \\(x\\): $$ 4^x-\\frac{8}{4^x}=2 $$</p>','<p>This equation is reducible to a quadratic, so let $u=4^x$ : $$ u-\\frac{8}{u}=2 $$ Multiplying both sides by $u$ : $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; u^2-8=2 u \\\\ &amp; \\therefore u^2-2 u-8=0 \\end{aligned} $$ Now factorising the quadratic equation: $$ \\begin{gathered} (u-4)(u+2)=0 \\\\ \\therefore u=4 \\text { ONLY }\\left(\\because 4^x&gt;0\\right) \\end{gathered} $$ The reason why $4^x&gt;0$ is because an exponential can never equal to 0 or a negative number. Hence, $u$ can only equal to 4 ! $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore 4^x=4 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x=1 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-15 08:51:21',0,1,3,300,'hard','subtopic'),(269,0,56,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>On the Richter scale, the magnitude \\(R\\) of an earthquake of intensity, \\(I\\) is given by the formula \\(R=\\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{I}{I_0}\\right)\\), where \\(I_0\\) is a reference intensity used for comparisons. The 2023 Syrian earthquake measured a magnitude of 7.8 on the Richter scale.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of these options is closest to \\(\\left(\\frac{I}{I_0}\\right)\\), which is the number of times this earthquake is more intense than the reference intensity?</p>','<p>Letting \\(R=7.8\\): $$ \\therefore 7.8=\\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{I}{I_0}\\right) $$ Then considering exponential: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(\\frac{I}{I_0}\\right) &amp; =10^{7.8} \\\\ &amp; =63095734.45 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, this is closest to 60000000</p>','2024-01-16 08:25:57',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(270,0,56,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>A rumour is spreading around school that Ed is a secret math genius and Nobel Prize winner. This rumour can be modelled by the equation: $$ N=2 \\times 1.13^{0.7 t} $$Where \\(N\\) is the number of students who have heard the rumour, and \\(t\\) is the number of hours after the rumour first started.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. How many students would have heard the rumour, exactly 1 day after it started?&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. How long would it take all 400 students in the school to hear the rumour? Give your answer to the nearest hour&nbsp;<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Be careful here, \\(t\\) is defined as the number of hours, so if 1 day has passed, then we should let \\(t=24\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore N &amp; =2 \\times 1.13^{0.7 \\times 24} \\\\ &amp; =15.59(2 \\text { d.p. }) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, 15 students would have heard the rumour. We round down because we can\'t have half a student hearing a rumour!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Now letting \\(N=400\\) and calculating the value of \\(t\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 400=2 \\times 1.13^{0.7 t} \\\\ &amp; 200=1.13^{0.7 t} \\end{aligned} $$ Using logarithms: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore 0.7 t=\\log _{1.13} 200 \\\\ &amp; t=\\frac{1}{0.7} \\log _{1.13} 200 \\end{aligned} $$ Now using change of base laws: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore t &amp; =\\frac{1}{0.7} \\times \\frac{\\ln 200}{\\ln 1.13} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 62 \\text { hours (nearest hour) } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-16 08:40:02',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(271,0,56,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>The Richter scale is used to measure the magnitude of earthquakes. The magnitude, \\(R\\) of an earthquake is proportional to the logarithm of the ground displacement, \\(d\\) caused by the earthquake in centimetres. This relationship is modelled by the equation: $$ R=\\log _{10}(100 d) $$</p><p>i. In January 2023, an earthquake in Sydney, Australia caused a ground displacement of \\(72 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). What was its magnitude on the Richter scale? Give your answer correct to 2 decimal places&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]</p><p>ii. How many times larger is the ground displacement of an earthquake with a magnitude of 7.8 compared to an earthquake with a magnitude of 6.5? Give your answer correct to the nearest whole number<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Since the displacement is \\(d=72\\), substituting this value into the Richter scale equation: $$ \\begin{aligned} R &amp; =\\log _{10}(100 \\times 72) \\\\ &amp; =\\log _{10} 7200 \\\\ &amp; \\approx 3.86(\\text { nearest } 2 d . p .) \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. First letting \\(R=7.8\\) and calculating the value of \\(d_1\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 7.8=\\log _{10} 100 d_1 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore 100 d_1=10^{7.8} \\\\ &amp; d_1=\\frac{1}{100} 10^{7.8} \\end{aligned} $$ We can leave our \\(d\\) here in exact form to get a more accurate answer later Then, letting \\(R=6.5\\) and calculating the value of \\(d_2\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 6.5=\\log _{10} 100 d_2 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore 100 d_2=10^{6.5} \\\\ &amp; d_2=\\frac{1}{100} 10^{6.5} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, finding how many times \\(d_1\\) is compared to \\(d_2\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d_1}{d_2} &amp; =\\frac{\\frac{1}{100} 10^{7.8}}{\\frac{1}{100} 10^{6.5}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{10^{7.8}}{10^{6.5}} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 20(\\text { nearest whole number }) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the ground displacement is 20 times greater!</p>','2024-01-16 09:03:40',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(272,0,56,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>Astronomers study stars and classify their brightness according to a scale of magnitude. The difference in magnitude between two stars is defined by the formula: $$ m_1-m_2=2.5 \\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{b_2}{b_1}\\right) $$Where \\(m_1\\) and \\(m_2\\) are the magnitudes of the two stars, and \\(b_1\\) and \\(b_2\\) are the corresponding apparent brightness measured in watts per metre squared. The magnitude of a star is a unitless measure, and its value can be positive or negative. The star called \"Harry\" has a magnitude of -1.4 and an apparent brightness of \\(1.04 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~W} / \\mathrm{m}^2\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. The star \"John\" has an apparent brightness of \\(1.53 \\times 10^{-8} \\mathrm{~W} / \\mathrm{m}^2\\).&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Calculate the magnitude of John, correct to two decimal place&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. The sun has a magnitude of \\(-27\\).&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Calculate the apparent brightness of the sun, correct to the nearest whole number&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Using the given formula, let \\(m_1\\) be the magnitude of John, and \\(b_1\\) be the brightness of John. $$ b_1=1.53 \\times 10^{-8} $$ This also means that \\(m_2\\) is the magnitude of Harry and \\(b_2\\) is the brightness of Harry $$ \\begin{gathered} m_2=-1.4 \\\\ b_2=1.04 \\times 10^{-7} \\\\ \\therefore m_1=2.5 \\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{b_2}{b_1}\\right)+m_2 \\\\ =2.5 \\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{1.04 \\times 10^{-7}}{1.53 \\times 10^{-8}}\\right)-1.4 \\\\ \\approx 0.681[3 \\text { significant figures}] \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. This time, we\'re going to let the sun\'s magnitude be \\(m_2\\) and its brightness \\(b_2\\). This is so that when we rearrange it later on, it\'ll be a little easier! $$ m_2=-27 $$ This also means that \\(m_1\\) is the magnitude of Harry and \\(b_1\\) is the brightness of Harry $$ \\begin{gathered} m_1=-1.4 \\\\ b_1=1.04 \\times 10^{-7} \\end{gathered} $$ Rearranging the equation to make \\(b_2\\) the subject now:</p><p>$$ \\begin{gathered} m_1-m_2=2.5 \\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{b_2}{b_1}\\right) \\\\ \\frac{1}{2.5}\\left(m_1-m_2\\right)=\\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{b_2}{b_1}\\right) \\\\ \\frac{b_2}{b_1}=10^{\\frac{1}{2.5}\\left(m_1-m_2\\right)} \\end{gathered} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore b_2 &amp; =b_1 \\times 10^{\\frac{1}{2.5}\\left(m_1-m_2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\left(1.04 \\times 10^{-7}\\right) \\times 10^{\\frac{1}{2.5}(-1.4--27)} \\\\ &amp; =\\left(1.04 \\times 10^{-7}\\right) \\times 10^{\\frac{1}{2.5}(-1.4+27)} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 1807 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-16 09:08:40',0,1,3,300,'hard','subtopic'),(273,0,56,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>The Richter scale defines the magnitude of an earthquake as \\(M=\\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{I}{I_0}\\right)\\), where \\(I\\) is the intensity of the earthquake wave, and \\(I_0\\) is the intensity of the smallest detectable wave.<br><br>An earthquake that registered 6.6 in magnitude was followed by another which was 4 times more intense.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><br><br>Determine the magnitude of the second earthquake, accurate to 1 decimal place</p>','<p>Letting \\(M=6.6\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} 6.6=\\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{I}{I_0}\\right) \\\\ \\therefore \\frac{I}{I_0}=10^{6.6} \\\\ I=I_0 \\times 10^{6.6} \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, this means that the intensity of the 6.6 magnitude earthquake was \\(I_0 \\times 10^{6.6}\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Therefore, if the second earthquake has quadruple the intensity, this means that:$$ I=4 I_0 \\times 10^{6.6} $$ Substituting this into the Richter equation to find \\(M\\) now: $$ \\begin{aligned} M &amp; =\\log _{10}\\left(\\frac{4 I_0 \\times 10^{6.6}}{I_0}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =\\log _{10}\\left(4 \\times 10^{6.6}\\right) \\\\ &amp; \\approx 7.2 \\text { (nearest } 1 \\text { d.p.) } \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the magnitude of the second earthquake is 7.2</p>','2024-01-16 09:15:39',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(274,1,69,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Consider the experiment of recording the number on the face that touches the table when an unbiased tetrahedral die with its faces numbered 1, 2, 3 and 4 is rolled.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability of getting a number greater than \\(1\\)?</p>','<p>Since there are 4 possible numbers the die can land on, the sample space for this question is: $$ \\text { Sample space }=4 $$ If we want a number greater than 1 , then the die can either land on 2,3 or 4 . Hence, the event space for this question is: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Event space } &amp; =3 \\\\ \\therefore P(\\text { greater than } 1) &amp; =\\frac{\\text { Event space }}{\\text { Sample space }} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3}{4} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-18 07:36:34',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(275,1,69,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>With reference to an experiment in which a card is drawn randomly from a bag containing 5 identical cards numbered from \\(1\\) to \\(5\\).&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability \\(P(A)\\) that an even number is drawn?</p>','<p>Since there are 5 possible cards that can be drawn, the sample space for this question is: $$ \\text { Sample space }=5 $$ If we want a card with an even number, then the card can either have a 2 or a 4 . Hence, the event space for this question is: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Event space } &amp; =2 \\\\ \\therefore P(\\text { even number }) &amp; =\\frac{\\text { Event space }}{\\text { Sample space }} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{5} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-18 07:45:41',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(276,1,69,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>There are \\(10\\) red marbles and \\(B\\) blue marbles in a bag. The probability of selecting a blue marble is \\(\\frac{4}{9}\\).&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">How many more blue marbles need to be added to the bag so that the probability of selecting a blue marble from the bag is \\(\\frac{3}{5}\\)?</p>','<p>Let the total number of marbles in the bag be \\(x\\), of which 10 are red. Since \\(P\\)(blue)\\(=\\frac{4}{9}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text { red }) &amp; =1-P(\\text { blue }) \\\\ &amp; =1-\\frac{4}{9} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5}{9} \\\\ P(\\text { red }) &amp; =\\frac{10}{x}=\\frac{5}{9} \\\\ \\therefore 5 x &amp; =90 \\\\ x &amp; =18 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, there are currently \\(18\\) marbles in the bag, \\(10\\) of which are red and \\(8\\) of which are blue.</p><p><br>Now letting \\(n\\) be the number of blue marbles added. We want P(blue)\\(=\\frac{3}{5}\\), where: $$ \\therefore P(\\text { blue })=\\frac{8+n}{18+n}=\\frac{3}{5} $$ Cross multiplying this expression: $$ \\begin{gathered} 5(8+n)=3(18+n) \\\\ 40+5 n=54+3 n \\\\ 2 n=14 \\\\ \\therefore n=7 \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, 7 blue marbles must be added to the bag</p>','2024-01-18 07:49:37',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(277,1,69,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks total]</u></p><p>David asks some people in his town about their dietary habits and records the results in the table below.$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|} \\hline \\text { Dietary habits } &amp; \\text { Frequency } \\\\ \\hline \\text { Vegetarian } &amp; 44 \\\\ \\hline \\text { Vegan } &amp; 23 \\\\ \\hline \\text { Other } &amp; 43 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Find the relative frequency of someone in David\'s town being vegetarian<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. There are 20,000 people in David\'s town. Using your answer to part (i), find an estimate for the number of people in this town who are vegetarian<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. Firstly, we need the total number of all outcomes: $$ \\text { Total }=44+23+43=\\mathbf{1 1 0} $$ Then, since 44 of these people are vegetarian: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\text { Relative Frequency } &amp; =\\frac{44}{110} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{5} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Since we know that the relative frequency of vegetarians is \\(\\frac{2}{5}\\), then this means \\(\\frac{2}{5}\\) of the town population will be vegetarian.&nbsp;</p><p>Hence: $$ \\text { Estimated no. of vegetarian }=\\frac{2}{5} \\times 20000=8000 $$</p>','2024-01-18 07:59:07',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(278,1,69,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A spinning wheel displays numbers \\(1-20\\), with an equal chance of the wheel landing on each number.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><br>If the wheel is spun \\(240\\) times, how many times would you expect a number greater than \\(15\\) to be obtained?</p>','<p>There are 5 numbers which are greater than \\(15\\):(16,17,18,19 and 20).&nbsp;</p><p>Therefore, the probability of getting a number greater than 15 in one spin is: $$ P(X&gt;15)=\\frac{5}{20}=\\frac{1}{4} $$ Hence, calculating the expected number of times this will occur in \\(240\\) spins: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Expected Frequency } &amp; =n \\times P(X&gt;15) \\\\ &amp; =240 \\times \\frac{1}{4} \\\\ &amp; =60 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-18 08:16:47',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(279,1,70,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>You have a cowboy hat, a top hat, and an Indonesian hat called a songkok. You also have four shirts: white, black, green, and pink.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">If you choose one hat and one shirt at random, what is the probability that you choose the songkok and the black shirt?</p>','<p>There are three different hats, so the probability of choosing the songkok is: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { songkok }) &amp; =\\frac{n(\\text { songkok })}{n(\\text { total hats })} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3} \\end{aligned} $$ There are four different shirts, so the probability of choosing the black shirt is $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { black shirt }) &amp; =\\frac{n(\\text { black shirt })}{n(\\text { total shirt })} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{4} \\end{aligned} $$ So, by the Multiplication Rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { songkok and black shirt }) &amp; =P(\\text { songkok }) \\times P(\\text { black shirt }) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{4} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{12} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-18 08:22:53',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(280,1,70,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A jar contains 50 seashells. 28 of these are white and 22 of them are brown. Alex is to select two shells from the jar at random.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that Alex selects two white shells?</p>','<p>The first time Alex selects a shell, the probability of getting a white shell is: $$ P(\\text {White})=\\frac{28}{50} $$ The second time Alex selects a shell, there is now one less white shell, meaning there are 27 white shells out of 49 total shells now. Therefore, the probability of getting a white shell is: $$ P(\\text {White})=\\frac{27}{49} $$ Hence, using the multiplication rule, we can find the probability of getting 2 white seashells: $$ \\therefore P(W W)=\\frac{28}{50} \\times \\frac{27}{49} $$</p>','2024-01-18 08:26:05',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(281,1,70,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A fair die numbered from 1 to 6 is rolled and an unbiased coin is tossed at the same time. The side on top is recorded in each case.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability of getting an even number on the die and heads on the coin?</p>','<p>First considering the probability of getting an even number from the die: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { even }) &amp; =\\frac{3}{6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\end{aligned} $$ Then considering the probability of getting heads: $$ P(\\text { heads })=\\frac{1}{2} $$ Therefore, considering the multiplication rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { even AND heads }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{4} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-18 08:30:42',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(283,1,70,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Suppose you take out two cards from a standard pack of 52 cards one after another, without replacing the first card.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that the first card is the ace of spades, and the second card is a heart?&nbsp;</p>','<p>For the first card: $$ P(\\text { ace of spades })=\\frac{1}{52} $$ After this card is taken out though, since it is not replaced, the sample space is now reduced to \\(51\\).&nbsp;</p><p>Since there are still \\(13\\) heart cards left, this means that for the second card: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\text { Event space }=13 \\\\ \\therefore P(2 \\text {nd card is heart })=\\frac{13}{51} \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, considering the multiplication rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { ace of spades and then heart }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{52} \\times \\frac{13}{51} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{204} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-18 08:32:04',0,1,2,180,'hard','subtopic'),(284,1,71,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A bag contains 6 blue marbles and 9 white marbles. Three marbles are selected at random without replacement.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that at least one of the marbles selected is blue?</p>','<p>Considering complementary events: $$ P(\\text { at least one blue })=1-P(\\text { no blues }) $$ Hence, calculating P(no blues): $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { no blues })=P(3 \\text { whites }) &amp; =\\frac{9}{15} \\times \\frac{8}{14} \\times \\frac{7}{13} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{12}{65} \\\\ \\therefore P(\\text { at least one blue }) &amp; =1-\\frac{12}{65} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{53}{65} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 02:54:11',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(285,1,71,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Two standard fair dice (with faces numbered 1 to 6 ) are rolled.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability of rolling at least one five?</p>','<p>We are asked to find P(at least one five). Considering the complement: $$P(\\text{at least one five})=1-P(\\text{no fives})$$</p><p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &nbsp;P(\\text { no fives }) &amp; =\\frac{5}{6} \\times \\frac{5}{6} \\\\ = &amp; \\frac{25}{36} \\\\ \\therefore P(\\text { at least one five }) &amp; =1-\\frac{25}{36} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{11}{36} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 02:55:43',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(286,1,71,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Jack randomly selects two socks from his closet which contains \\(15\\) white socks and \\(7\\) black socks without replacement</p><p>i. Find the probability of selecting a matching pair of colours<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the probability of not selecting a pair of white socks<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. There are two ways to get a matching pair of colours:&nbsp;<br><br><strong>Case 1:</strong> <strong>Two black socks</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} P(B B) &amp; =\\frac{7}{22} \\times \\frac{6}{21} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{11} \\end{aligned} $$<strong> Case 2:</strong> <strong>Two white socks</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} P(W W) &amp; =\\frac{15}{22} \\times \\frac{14}{21} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5}{11} \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the total probability of getting a matching pair of colours is:&nbsp;$$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { matching }) &amp; =P(B B)+P(W W) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{11}+\\frac{5}{11} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{6}{11} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. As was shown in part i), the probability of selecting a pair of white socks was: $$ P(W W)=\\frac{5}{11} $$ Therefore, the probability of NOT getting a pair of white socks is its complement: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text{NOT WW}) &amp; =1-P(W W) \\\\ &amp; =1-\\frac{5}{11} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{6}{11} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 03:00:19',0,1,3,300,'hard','subtopic'),(287,1,71,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The ratio of boys to girls at Mathify High School is \\(4:5\\). The ratio of boys to girls at Lebron High School is \\(3:2\\). A student is chosen at random from Mathify High School and then another student is chosen from Lebron High School.&nbsp;<br><br>Find the probability that:</p><p>i. Two girls are chosen<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. At least one boy is chosen<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. A girl must be chosen from each school, where: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; P(\\text { girl from Mathify High })=\\frac{5}{9} \\\\ &amp; P(\\text { girl from Lebron High })=\\frac{2}{5} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text { Both girls }) &amp; =\\frac{5}{9} \\times \\frac{2}{5} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{9} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. To find the probability of at least one boy being chosen, consider the complement: $$ P(\\text { At least one boy })=1-P(\\text { No boys }) $$ Moreover, consider that having no boys selected is the same thing as having both selections be girls. $$ \\therefore P(\\text { no boys })=P(\\text { Both girls }) $$ Therefore: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { At least one boy }) &amp; =1-P(\\text { Both girls }) \\\\ &amp; =1-\\frac{2}{9} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{7}{9} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 03:08:27',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(288,1,71,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Kylie begins work at a caf in Sydney CBD and needs to catch a bus to get to work. She will be late if the buses do not run on schedule, and the probability that, on any given day, her bus will run to schedule is \\(0.92\\) (a record high for NSW transport).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">&nbsp;</p><p>i. What is the probability that Kylie\'s bus is late on the first day?</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. What is the probability that Kylie arrives late on exactly one of the first three days she is working at her caf?&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Since P(on schedule)\\(=0.92\\), considering the complement: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text { not on schedule }) &amp; =1-P(\\text { on schedule }) \\\\ &amp; =1-0.92 \\\\ &amp; =0.08 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the probability that Kylie\'s bus is late will be \\(0.08\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. There are three possibilities for Kylie to arrive late on exactly one of her first three days working:&nbsp;<br><br><strong>Case 1: Arrive late the first day only&nbsp;</strong><br><br>This means that Kylie\'s bus will not be on schedule (N) the first day but on schedule (Y) the next two days:<br>$$ \\begin{aligned} P(N Y Y) &amp; =0.08 \\times 0.92 \\times 0.92 \\\\ &amp; =0.067712 \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Case 2: Arrive late the second day only</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} P(Y N Y) &amp; =0.92 \\times 0.08 \\times 0.92 \\\\ &amp; =0.067712 \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Case 3: Arrive late the third day only</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} P(Y Y N) &amp; =0.92 \\times 0.92 \\times 0.08 \\\\ &amp; =0.067712 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { Late on one of the first } 3 \\text { days }) &amp; =P(N Y Y)+P(Y N Y)+P(Y Y N) \\\\ &amp; =0.067712+0.067712+0.067712 \\\\ &amp; =0.203136 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 03:27:33',0,1,3,300,'hard','subtopic'),(289,1,72,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>A box contains \\(n\\) marbles. Let \\(k\\) represent the number of green marbles, with the remaining marbles being blue. Two marbles are chosen at random from the box without replacement.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that both marbles are the same colour?</p>','<p>There are two possible scenarios for this question:&nbsp;</p><p><br><strong>Case 1: Two green marbles&nbsp;</strong><br><br>Since there are \\(k\\) green marbles: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(G G) &amp; =\\frac{k}{n} \\times \\frac{k-1}{n-1} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{k(k-1)}{n(n-1)} \\end{aligned} $$<strong>Case 2: Two blue marbles&nbsp;</strong><br><br>There are \\(n-k\\) blue marbles in the box: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(B B) &amp; =\\frac{n-k}{n} \\times \\frac{n-k-1}{n-1} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{(n-k)(n-k-1)}{n(n-1)} \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the total probability will be: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { Same colour }) &amp; =P(G G)+P(B B) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{k(k-1)}{n(n-1)}+\\frac{(n-k)(n-k-1)}{n(n-1)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{k(k-1)+(n-k)(n-k-1)}{n(n-1)} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 05:07:00',0,1,1,120,'hard','subtopic'),(290,1,72,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>In a raffle where \\(100\\) tickets are sold, there is one first prize and one second prize. Frank decides to buy \\(15\\) tickets in this raffle. The first prize is drawn before the second prize, and the ticket is not replaced.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Complete the probability tree diagram below, showing all outcomes:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:31.58%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:544/750;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/19ee3f9abdae6e1899260b2f54de3b6b.png\" width=\"544\" height=\"750\"></figure><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. What is the probability that Frank wins the second prize, but not the first prize?&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. Completing the probability tree diagram:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:32.09%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:632/836;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/0b9d8b9d9537cda065e5b0e3f17d084b.png\" width=\"632\" height=\"836\"></figure><p>ii. From the probability tree diagram, we need to look at the branch which has lose then win [since we lose first but win second prize] $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(L W) &amp; =\\frac{85}{100} \\times \\frac{15}{99} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{17}{132} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 05:09:21',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(291,1,72,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The probability of Morant\'s basketball team winning their next game is dependent on whether or not they won the previous game</p><p><br>If they won the previous game, the probability of winning their next game is \\(0.9\\)&nbsp;<br><br>If they lost the previous game, then the probability of winning their next game is reduced to \\(0.4\\)&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Morant\'s team won on Monday and then they also played on Tuesday and Wednesday</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">&nbsp;</p><p>i. Represent the above information using a tree diagram&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the probability that Morant\'s soccer team do not win on Wednesday&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Drawing a tree diagram with 2 steps, Tuesday and Wednesday:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:41.43%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:719/895;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e5f60eb441c5d894ab48a8be33046517.png\" width=\"719\" height=\"895\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. There are two possible scenarios for which Morant\'s team lose on Wednesday:&nbsp;<br><br><strong>Case 1: Won on Tuesday, lost on Wednesday</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} P(W L) &amp; =0.9 \\times 0.1 \\\\ &amp; =0.09 \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Case 2: Lost on Tuesday, lost on Wednesday</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} P(L L) &amp; =0.1 \\times 0.6 \\\\ &amp; =0.06 \\\\ \\therefore P(\\text { Loss on Wednesday }) &amp; =P(W L)+P(L L) \\\\ &amp; =0.09+0.06 \\\\ &amp; =0.15 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 05:22:42',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(292,1,72,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>At the start of the week, Herbert has 5 pairs of white socks and 3 pairs of black socks. On Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday of this week, she randomly selects one pair each day to wear.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">In this three day period, what is the probability that Herbert does not wear a pair of socks of the same colour on any two successive days?&nbsp;</p>','<p>There are two cases in which Herbert does not wear a pair of socks of the same colour:&nbsp;<br><br><strong>Case 1: White, Black, White</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} P(W B W) &amp; =\\frac{5}{8} \\times \\frac{3}{7} \\times \\frac{4}{6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5}{28} \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Case 2: Black, White, Black</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} P(B W B) &amp; =\\frac{3}{8} \\times \\frac{5}{7} \\times \\frac{2}{6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5}{56} \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, our answer will be:$$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { Not same colour on } 2 \\text { successive days }) &amp; =P(W B W)+P(B W B) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5}{28}+\\frac{5}{56} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{15}{56} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 05:33:41',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(293,1,72,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks]</u></p><p>There are some red cards and some blue cards in a bag. At the start, 9 of the cards are red and the rest of the cards are blue. Aiden takes two cards from the bag.&nbsp;<br><br>First, he takes at random a card from the bag. Without replacing it, he then takes at random another card from the bag</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Let the number of blue counters in the bag be \\(B\\)&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Draw a tree diagram that represents the above scenario, showing all relevant information</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">&nbsp;</p><p>ii. It is given that the probability that the first card Woody takes is Blue, and the second card Woody takes is red is \\(\\frac{9}{35}\\)&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find the possible value(s) of \\(B\\)</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. If there are \\(B\\) blue cards, then that means the total number of cards will be: $$ \\text { Total }=B+9 $$ Therefore, drawing the tree diagram:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:41.46%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:688/918;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/b46ac3dda06fa322ddcc56c7e51bcf60.png\" width=\"688\" height=\"918\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Since the first card is blue and the second card is red, the probability is:$$ \\begin{aligned} P(B R) &amp; =\\frac{B}{B+9} \\times \\frac{9}{B+8} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{9 B}{(B+9)(B+8)} \\end{aligned} $$Since it is given that $P(B R)=\\frac{9}{35}$ : $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\frac{9}{35} &amp; =\\frac{9 B}{(B+9)(B+8)} \\\\ \\frac{1}{35} &amp; =\\frac{B}{(B+9)(B+8)} \\end{aligned} $$ Cross multiplying: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 35 B=(B+9)(B+8) \\\\ &amp; 35 B=B^2+8 B+9 B+72 \\\\ &amp; B^2+17 B-35 B+72=0 \\\\ &amp; B^2-18 B+72=0 \\\\ &amp; (B-12)(B-6)=0 \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore B=6 \\text { OR } 12$$ Hence, at the start there could\'ve been either 6 or 12 blue counters in the bag</p>','2024-01-19 05:39:04',0,1,4,480,'hard','subtopic'),(294,1,72,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>Kobe and Shaq complete a series of games. The series finishes when one player has won two games. In any game, the probability that Kobe wins is \\(\\frac{4}{7}\\) and the probability that Shaq wins is \\(\\frac{3}{7}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Draw a probability tree showing the possible outcomes, in a series of three games&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. What is the probability that Kobe wins the series?&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. What is the probability that Kobe wins at least one game?&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. Drawing the probability tree diagram:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:50.03%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:883/1008;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/80af13c587af13d5fa46d5812281f6df.png\" width=\"883\" height=\"1008\"></figure><p>Notice that some third games are missing since when a player wins the first 2 , there is no need for a \\(3^{\\text {rd }}\\) game.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. To calculate the probability of Kobe winning, we must add up all possibilities where Kobe wins 2 out of the three games: $$ \\begin{gathered} P(\\text {Kobe win })=P(K K)+P(K S K)+P(S K K) \\\\ P(K K)=\\frac{4}{7} \\times \\frac{4}{7}=\\frac{16}{49} \\\\ P(K S K)=\\frac{4}{7} \\times \\frac{3}{7} \\times \\frac{4}{7}=\\frac{48}{343} \\\\ P(S K K)=\\frac{3}{7} \\times \\frac{4}{7} \\times \\frac{4}{7}=\\frac{48}{343} \\\\ \\therefore P(\\text { Kobe win })=\\frac{16}{49}+\\frac{48}{343}+\\frac{48}{343} \\\\ =\\frac{208}{343} \\end{gathered} $$`</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. We are asked to find P(Kobe wins at least one). Considering the complement: $$ P(\\text { Kobe wins at least one })=1-P(\\text { Kobe wins none }) $$ The situation where Kobe wins none is when Shaq wins the first 2 games. Therefore:$$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { Kobe wins none })=P(S S) &amp; =\\frac{3}{7} \\times \\frac{3}{7} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{9}{49} \\\\ \\therefore P(\\text {Kobe wins at least one}) &amp; =1-\\frac{9}{49} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{40}{49} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-19 05:48:38',0,1,4,480,'hard','subtopic'),(295,1,73,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Consider the two sets \\(A=\\{8,9,10\\}\\) and \\(B=\\{10,11,12\\}\\). A number is randomly selected from each set.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability of selecting a number from each set that has a sum equal to or greater than 20?</p>','<p>For this question, we must first consider how many total possibilities there are, i.e. find our sample space&nbsp;</p><p>Since there are 3 options in each set, the total number of possibilities is: $$ \\text { Sample space }=3 \\times 3=9 $$ Now we must consider how many possibilities there are where the sum of one number from each set is equal to or greater than 20 : $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 8+12 \\\\ &amp; 9+11 \\\\ &amp; 9+12 \\\\ &amp; 10+10 \\\\ &amp; 10+11 \\\\ &amp; 10+12 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, there are 6 total possibilities that make up our event space. $$ \\therefore P(\\text { Sum } \\geq 20)=\\frac{6}{9}=\\frac{2}{3} $$</p>','2024-01-19 06:41:39',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(296,6,73,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks total]</u></p><p>A survey of which social media students prefer to use revealed that, on a regular basis, \\(33 \\%\\) use BeFake, \\(45 \\%\\) use Bookface and \\(44 \\%\\) do not use any social media</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. By constructing a venn diagram, or otherwise, find the percentage of students who use both BeFake and Bookface&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. A student is selected at random. Find the probability that this student uses either BeFake or Bookface but not both&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. Before constructing the venn diagram, we must first determine what percentage of students use both social media sites&nbsp;<br><br>Since \\(44 \\%\\) do not use any social media, then \\(56 \\%\\) do use social media&nbsp;<br><br>However, \\(33\\% +45 \\%=78 \\%\\), which is not equal to \\(56 \\%\\). Hence, this means that there exist a number of students that use both sites $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Percentage who use both sites } &amp; =78 \\%-56 \\% \\\\ &amp; =22 \\% \\end{aligned} $$Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 33 \\%-22 \\%=11 \\% \\text { use BeFake ONLY } \\\\ &amp; 45 \\%-22 \\%=23 \\% \\text { use Bookface ONLY } \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the Venn diagram will resemble:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:53.41%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1105/505;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/2d57435ff018ff2bca3391474e665d31.png\" width=\"1105\" height=\"505\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Consider that: $$ P(\\text { students uses either but not both })=P(\\text { BeFake ONLY })+P(\\text { Bookface ONLY }) $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text { students uses either but not both }) &amp; =0.11+0.23 \\\\ &amp; =0.34 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-21 10:15:18',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(297,6,73,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>\\(271\\) students voted for the types of music they wanted at the school dance. The results are shown in the Venn diagram.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that a randomly selected student voted for rock and not jazz?</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:237/247;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/12a1fb2206438c422efc2f4621827488.png\" width=\"237\" height=\"247\"></figure>','<p>First, we must calculate the total number of students: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Total no. of students } &amp; =77+7+9+11+70+6+91 \\\\ &amp; =271 \\end{aligned} $$ This will act as the \"Sample Size\" of our probability.&nbsp;<br><br>Next, we need to find the number of students who voted for rock but not jazz:&nbsp;<br>Using the Venn diagram, we can see that the number of students for this event is: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Rock but not Jazz } &amp; =70+7 \\\\ &amp; =77 \\end{aligned} $$ This will be the \"Event Space\" of our probability&nbsp;<br><br>Finally calculating our probability: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text {Student likes Rock but not Jazz}) &amp; =\\frac{\\text { Event space }}{\\text { Sample size }} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{77}{271} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-21 10:21:41',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(298,6,73,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>Eighty people were asked in a survey if they had holidayed internationally (I) or within the country domestically (D) in the past 5 years.</p><p>The results showed that:</p><ul><li>12 people had not holidayed at all</li><li>42 people had holidayed internationally</li><li>36 people had holidayed domestically</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\\(\\text{i. Draw a complete Venn diagram of the survey results}\\)<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\\(\\text{ii. One of the surveyed people is selected at random. Find the probability that the person selected has holidayed both domestically and internationally in the last five years.}\\)&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\\(\\text{iii. A randomly selected person is known to have travelled somewhere. Find the probability that this person holidayed internationally}\\)<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\\(\\text{iv. Two people are chosen, in turn and at random. Find the probability that exactly one of the two chosen holidayed domestically.}\\)<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Before drawing the Venn diagram, we first determine how many people holidayed internationally and domestically: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { no. of people who holidayed } &amp; =80-12 \\\\ &amp; =68 \\\\ \\text { no. of people who holidayed both } &amp; =42+36-68 \\\\ &amp; =10 \\end{aligned} $$ \\(\\therefore\\) no. who holidayed internationally ONLY \\( =42-10=32\\) \\(\\therefore\\) no. who holidayed domestically \\(\\text{ONLY}=36-10=26\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Now sketching the Venn diagram using these values:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:46.6%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1004/548;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/39a846807834ef083f175c1a575de39e.png\" width=\"1004\" height=\"548\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. There are \\(10\\) people out of \\(80\\) who have holidayed both internationally and domestically: $$ \\therefore P(I \\cap D)=\\frac{10}{80}=\\frac{1}{8} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Notice that this is a conditional probability question, where we are asked to find: $$ P(\\text {International given that they holidayed})=P(I \\mid \\text {they holidayed}) $$ Thus, applying our conditional probability formula: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(A\\mid B) &amp; =\\frac{P(A\\cap B)}{P(B)} \\\\ \\therefore P(I \\mid \\text {they holidayed}) &amp; =\\frac{P(\\text {international holiday})}{P(\\text {they holidayed})} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{42}{68} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{21}{34} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. If we only want one person out of the two selected to have holidayed domestically, there are two cases we must consider:&nbsp;<br><br><strong><u>Case 1: Choose domestic traveller, then choose non-domestic traveller</u></strong>&nbsp;<br>In other words, we are finding \\(P(D, \\bar{D})\\), where \\(\\bar{D}\\) is the complement of \\(D\\). $$ \\text { : } \\begin{aligned} P(D, \\bar{D}) &amp; =P(D) \\times P(\\bar{D}) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{36}{80} \\times \\frac{80-36}{79} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{36}{80} \\times \\frac{44}{79} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{99}{395} \\end{aligned} $$ <strong><u>Case 2: Choose non - domestic traveller, then choose domestic traveller</u></strong></p><p><br>In other words, we are finding \\(P(\\bar{D}, D)\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\bar{D}, D) &amp; =P(\\bar{D}) \\times P(D) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{44}{80} \\times \\frac{36}{79} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{99}{395} \\\\ \\therefore P(D, \\bar{D})+P(\\bar{D}, D) &amp; =\\frac{99}{395}+\\frac{99}{395} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{198}{395} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-21 10:24:40',0,1,5,540,'hard','subtopic'),(299,1,73,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [6 marks total]</u></p><p>In a music class with \\(32\\) students, \\(18\\) students play the piano \\((\\mathrm{P})\\) and \\(15\\) students play the bagpipes \\((\\mathrm{B})\\). \\(6\\) students don\'t play any instrument at all.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Draw a Venn diagram to represent these events using the labels \\(P\\) and \\(B\\)<br>\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. A student is chosen at random from the class. Find \\(P(P \\cap B)\\)&nbsp;<br>\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. A student is chosen at random again from the class. Find \\(P(P \\cup B)\\)&nbsp;<br>\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. The school principal wants only one piano player and one bagpipe player to play for the upcoming school assembly. If two students are chosen at random from the class, what is the probability that they can play in the upcoming school assembly?&nbsp;<br>\\(\\text{[3 marks]}\\)</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>i. Before drawing the venn diagram, we first determine how many students play both the bagpipes and the piano:&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>no. who play instrument \\(=32-6=26\\)</li><li>no. who play both \\(=18+15-26=7\\)&nbsp;</li></ul><p>$$\\therefore \\text{number who play piano only} =18-7=11$$</p><p>$$\\therefore \\text{number who play bagpipes only} =15-7=8$$</p><p><br>Therefore, drawing the venn diagram:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:40.04%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1072/584;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ee4d4165098ebed6b3117feee7802c11.png\" width=\"1072\" height=\"584\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. There are \\(7\\) people out of the class who play both the piano and bagpipes $$ \\therefore P(P \\cap B)=\\frac{7}{32} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. There are \\(26\\) people who play either instrument $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(P \\cup B) &amp; =\\frac{26}{32} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{13}{16} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. This is quite a complex question, so drawing a tree diagram to represent our possibilities:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:34.59%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:634/1204;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/2607f0cf615e8fb63f2c4417f2da3292.png\" width=\"634\" height=\"1204\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore P(\\text {play in assembly}) \\\\ &amp; =P(p, b)+P(p, \\text {both})+P(\\text {both}, p)+P(\\text {both}, \\text {both})+P(\\text {both, } b) \\\\ &amp; +P(b, p)+P(b, \\text {both}) \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$ Where \\(p\\) refers to students who only play piano, both refers to students who play both piano and bagpipes and \\(b\\) refers to students who only play bagpipes $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; P(\\text {play in assembly) } \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{11}{32} \\times \\frac{8}{31}+\\frac{11}{32} \\times \\frac{7}{31}+\\frac{7}{32} \\times \\frac{11}{31}+\\frac{7}{32} \\times \\frac{6}{31}+\\frac{7}{32} \\times \\frac{8}{31}+\\frac{8}{32} \\times \\frac{11}{31} \\\\ &amp; +\\frac{8}{32} \\times \\frac{7}{31} \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore P(\\text {play in assembly})=\\frac{121}{248} $$</p>','2024-01-22 00:52:54',0,1,6,600,'hard','subtopic'),(300,6,74,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>One ticket is selected at random from a pile of tickets labeled \\(1\\) to \\(50\\).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find the probability that the ticket is an even number or a number greater than \\(40\\).</p>','<p>Recalling the addition rule: $$ P(A \\text { or } B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A \\cap B) $$ For this scenario: $$ P(\\text {even or }&gt;40)=P(\\text {even})+P(&gt;40)-P(\\text {even and }&gt;40) $$ In total, there are 10 numbers greater than \\(40(41,42,43, \\ldots 50)\\) and 5 of these are even. $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore P(&gt;40)=\\frac{10}{50}=\\frac{1}{5} \\\\ \\therefore P(\\text {even and }&gt;40)=\\frac{5}{50}=\\frac{1}{10} \\end{gathered} $$ Substituting this into the previous equation: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text {even or}&gt;40) &amp; =\\frac{1}{2}+\\frac{1}{5}-\\frac{1}{10} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3}{5} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 01:27:45',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(301,6,74,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>In a group of \\(80\\) students, \\(64\\) have subscribed to Mathify and \\(28\\) have subscribed to Mathrolo.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">If \\(18\\) students have subscribed to both Mathify and Mathrolo, what is the probability that a student chosen at random has subscribed to neither Mathify nor Mathrolo?</p>','<p>If 8 people have subscribed to both Mathify and Mathrolo, then that means: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 64-18=46 \\text { subscribed to Mathify ONLY } \\\\ &amp; 28-18=10 \\text { subscribed to Mathrolo ONLY } \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the number of people subscribed to neither will be: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { no. of people subscribed to neither } &amp; =80-46-10-18 \\\\ &amp; =6 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the probability of someone being subscribed to neither is: $$ P(\\text {neither})=\\frac{6}{80}=\\frac{3}{40} $$</p>','2024-01-22 01:36:10',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(302,6,74,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>In a group of \\(101\\) students \\(40\\) are juniors, \\(50\\) are female, and \\(22\\) are female juniors.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find the probability that a student picked from this group at random is either a junior or female?</p>','<p>Recalling the addition rule: $$ P(A \\text { or } B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A \\text { and } B) $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text {Junior or Female}) &amp; =P(\\text {Junior})+P(\\text {Female})-P(\\text {Junior and Female}) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{40}{101}+\\frac{50}{101}-\\frac{22}{101} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{68}{101} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:09:26',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(303,6,74,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [1 mark]</u></p><p>On New Year\'s Eve, the probability of a person getting in a car accident is \\(0.09\\) The probability of a person driving while intoxicated is \\(0.32\\) and the probability of a person getting in a car accident while intoxicated is \\(0.15\\).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability of a person driving while intoxicated or getting in a car accident?&nbsp;</p>','<p>Recalling the addition rule: $$ P(A \\text { or } B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A \\text { and } B) $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text {intoxicated or accident}) &amp; =P(\\text {intoxicated})+P(\\text {accident})-P(\\text {both}) \\\\ &amp; =0.32+0.09-0.15 \\\\ &amp; =0.26 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:13:48',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(304,6,74,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [1 mark]</u></p><p>The probability of a New York teenager owning a skateboard is \\(0.37\\) of owning a bicycle is \\(0.81\\) and of owning both is \\(0.36\\).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">If a New York teenager is chosen at random, what is the probability that the teenager owns a skateboard or a bicycle?</p>','<p>Recalling the addition rule: $$ P(A \\text { or } B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A \\text { and } B) $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text {skateboard and bicycle}) &amp; =P(\\text {skateboard})+P(\\text {bicycle})-P(\\text {both}) \\\\ &amp; =0.37+0.81-0.36 \\\\ &amp; =0.82 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:18:18',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(305,6,75,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>In a group of \\(80\\) Year 12 students, \\(32\\) study Maths Advanced only, \\(36\\) study Chemistry only, and \\(12\\) study both.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Find the probability that a student studies Chemistry given that they study Maths Advanced.</p>','<p>This is a conditional probability question, and we should thus consider the conditional probability formula:$$ P(A \\mid B)=\\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)} $$ In this case: $$ P(\\text {Chemistry given Maths})=\\frac{P(\\text {Chemistry and Maths})}{P(\\text {Maths})} $$ Note here that $32+12=44$ students study Maths, so: $$ \\begin{gathered} P(\\text {Maths})=\\frac{44}{80}=\\frac{11}{20} \\\\ P(\\text {Chemistry and Maths})=\\frac{12}{80}=\\frac{3}{20} \\end{gathered} $$ Thus: $$ P(\\text {Chemistry given Maths})=\\frac{\\frac{3}{20}}{\\frac{11}{20}}=\\frac{3}{11} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:23:42',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(306,6,75,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>In a class, students were asked which sports they liked, and the results are shown in the Venn diagram below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:37.74%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:744/682;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/8acee953bbe97cd04bdbf1abed422ef9.png\" width=\"744\" height=\"682\"></figure><p>A student who liked soccer was chosen at random.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that they also like basketball?</p>','<p>Since we are only choosing students who liked soccer, in total there are: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Total no. liking soccer } &amp; =6+6+3+3 \\\\ &amp; =18 \\end{aligned} $$ Of these 18 people, there are also \\(6+3=9\\) students who like basketball too. Therefore, the probability is: $$ \\frac{9}{18}=\\frac{1}{2} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:29:42',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(307,6,75,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Five hundred people were tested for COVID with the following results:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:51.2%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:866/112;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/d7f151515930f9f0802056f549fa390f.png\" width=\"866\" height=\"112\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the probability that the person tests positive to COVID, given that they didn\'t show symptoms?</p>','<p>Since this is a conditional probability question: $$ P(A \\mid B)=\\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)} $$$$ \\therefore P(\\text {Covid positive } \\mid \\text { no symptoms})=\\frac{P(\\text {positive and no symptoms})}{P(\\text {no symptoms})} $$ In total, there were \\(24+44=68\\) people without symptoms&nbsp;<br><br>There were also \\(24\\) people who had no symptoms and tested positive&nbsp;<br><br>Therefore, subbing this information in: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text {Covid positive } \\mid \\text { no symptoms}) &amp; =\\frac{24}{68} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{6}{17} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:34:51',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(308,6,75,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>$$ \\text { If } P(A)=0.8, P(B)=0.6 \\text { and } P(B \\mid A)=0.4 \\text {, what is the value of } P(A \\cap B) \\text { ? } $$</p>','<p>Using the conditional probability formula, we know that: $$ P(B \\mid A)=\\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(A)} $$ Therefore, substituting in our given values: $$ 0.4=\\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{0.8} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(A \\cap B) &amp; =0.4 \\times 0.8 \\\\ &amp; =0.32 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:40:13',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(309,1,75,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>A sports magazine surveyed \\(180\\) basketball fans and asked them whether they supported Michael Jordan or Lebron James. \\(102\\) fans supported Michael Jordan, \\(88\\) supported Lebron James and \\(18\\) supported neither.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Represent this data in a Venn diagram<br>\\(\\text{[2 marks]}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. A fan is selected at random. If the fan selected is a Michael Jordan fan, what is the probability that they are also a Lebron fan?<br>\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)</p>','<p>i. Before drawing the venn diagram, we must first make a few calculations: $$ \\begin{gathered} 180-18=162 \\text { fans for either Michael or Lebron } \\\\ \\qquad 102+88-180=10 \\text { support both } \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore:&nbsp;<br><br>\\(92\\) fans support Jordan ONLY&nbsp;<br>\\(78\\) fans support Lebron ONLY&nbsp;<br><br>Now drawing the venn diagram:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:44.07%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1079/473;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f2e5d6b6522b57932e97a2d85cde3d13.png\" width=\"1079\" height=\"473\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Since this is a conditional probability question: $$ P(A \\mid B)=\\frac{P(A\\cap B)}{P(B)} $$$$ \\therefore P(\\text {fan of Lebron} \\mid \\text {fan of Jordan})=\\frac{P(\\text {fan of Lebron AND Jordan})}{P(\\text {fan of Jordan})} $$ There are \\(102\\) people who are a fan of Jordan, and \\(10\\) who are a fan of Lebron and Jordan. Therefore: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text {fan of Lebron} \\mid \\text {fan of Jordan}) &amp; =\\frac{10}{102} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5}{51} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:44:39',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(310,1,75,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A year 12 class is made up of \\(22\\) boys and \\(18\\) girls, while a year 11 class is made up of \\(16\\) boys and \\(20\\) girls. If you pick one of their classes and a pupil from it at random:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. What is the probability that you select a boy?<br>\\(\\text{[2 marks]}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. What is the probability that the student is from year 12 given that a boy is selected?<br>\\(\\text{[2 marks]}\\)</p>','<p>i. Since there are 2 classes, this means that there are 2 possible scenarios:&nbsp;<br><br><strong>Case 1: Pick Year 11 class and then pick a boy&nbsp;</strong><br><br>There is a \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\) chance of picking the year 11 class and there are \\(16\\) boys out of \\(36\\) students in the class $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text { Year } 11 \\text { boy }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{16}{36} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{9} \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Case 2: Pick Year 12 class and then pick a boy</strong><br><br>There is a \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\) chance of picking the year 12 class and there are \\(22\\) boys out of \\(40\\) students in the class $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text { Year } 12 \\text { boy }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{22}{40} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{11}{40} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the total probability of selecting a boy will be: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { boy }) &amp; =P(\\text { Year } 11 \\text { boy })+P(\\text { Year } 12 \\text { boy }) \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{9}+\\frac{11}{40} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{179}{360} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. This is a conditional probability question, where we are asked for the probability of a student being in year 12 , given that they are a boy.<br>&nbsp;</p><p>Remembering the conditional probability formula: $$ P(A \\mid B)=\\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)} $$ Therefore: $$ P(\\text { year } 12 \\text { given that they are a boy })=\\frac{P(\\text { boy and in year } 12)}{P(\\text { boy })} $$ Using \\(P\\) (Year 12 boy) from part i: $$ P(\\text { boy and in year } 12)=\\frac{11}{40} $$Using \\(P\\) (boy) from part i:&nbsp;$$ P(\\text { boy })=\\frac{179}{360} $$<strong>Substituting these two values into our previous equation:</strong>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(\\text { year } 12 \\text { given that they are a boy }) &amp; =\\frac{\\frac{11}{40}}{\\frac{179}{360}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{99}{179} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 03:51:49',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(311,6,75,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Maximus&nbsp;has \\(3\\) pennies in his pocket. One of his pennies has heads on both sides, another is biased such that it has a \\(60 \\%\\) chance of landing on heads and the third coin is a fair coin where there is a \\(50 \\%\\) chance of heads.<br><br>A coin is selected at random and tossed. Given that the coin that was tossed comes up heads, what is the probability that it was the fair coin?</p>','<p>We are asked to find \\(P\\) (fair coin given that result was heads). In other words: $$ P(\\text { fair coin given that result was heads })=P(\\text { fair coin } \\mid \\text { result was heads }) $$ Recalling the conditional probability formula: $$ P(A \\mid B)=\\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)} $$ In this question: $$ P(\\text { fair coin } \\mid \\text { result was heads })=\\frac{P(\\text { fair coin and heads })}{P(\\text { heads })} $$To find \\(P\\) (heads), we must consider the three possible cases:&nbsp;<br><br>Case 1: Maximus selects the penny with two heads $$ P(\\text { two heads })=\\frac{1}{3} $$ Case 2: Maximus selects the biased coin and gets heads $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { biased and heads }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{3} \\times 60 \\% \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{3}{5} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{5} \\end{aligned} $$Case 3: Maximus selects the fair coin and gets heads $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { fair and heads }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the total probability of getting heads is: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(\\text { heads }) &amp; =\\frac{1}{3}+\\frac{1}{5}+\\frac{1}{6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{7}{10} \\end{aligned} $$ Since we also know that \\(P\\) ( fair and heads = \\(\\frac{1}{6}\\) ), therefore subbing this into our previous formula: $$ P(\\text { fair coin } \\mid \\text { result was heads })=\\frac{\\frac{1}{6}}{\\frac{7}{10}}=\\frac{5}{21} $$</p>','2024-01-22 04:13:11',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(312,6,76,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>If \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) are two independent events, then the probability of occurrence of at least one of \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) is given by:</p>','<p>When the question asks us for the probability of \"at least one of \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{B}\\)\", they are essentially asking us to find: $$ P(A \\cup B) $$ From the addition rule, we formulate the expression: $$ P(A \\cup B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A \\cap B) $$ Since we know that \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) are independent events, we know \\(P(A \\cap B)=P(A) \\times P(B)\\) $$ \\therefore P(A \\cup B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A) \\times P(B) $$ Factorising: $$ P(A \\cup B)=P(A)+P(B)[1-P(A)] $$ Notice that \\(1-P(A)=P(\\bar{A})\\) (complementary events) $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(A \\cup B) &amp; =P(A)+P(B)[P(\\bar{A})] \\\\ &amp; =1-P(\\bar{A})+P(B)[P(\\bar{A})] \\end{aligned} $$ Factorising again: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(A \\cup B) &amp; =1-P(\\bar{A})[1-P(B)] \\\\ &amp; =1-P(\\bar{A}) P(\\bar{B}) \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 04:24:29',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(313,1,76,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Let \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) be two events, where it is known that \\(P(A)=0.55\\) and \\(P(B)=0.65\\) and \\(P(B|A)=0.75\\).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of the following statements is false?</p>','<p>When 2 events \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) are defined as independent, this means that: $$ P(A) \\times P(B)=P(A \\cap B) $$ In this case: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(A) \\times P(B) &amp; =0.55 \\times 0.65 \\\\ &amp; =0.3575 \\end{aligned} $$ Now we need to find a value for \\(P(A \\cap B)\\) to verify if they are equal or not. <strong>We will do this using the conditional probability formula:</strong> $$ P(B \\mid A)=\\frac{P(B \\cap A)}{P(A)} $$ Substituting in our known values:$$ \\begin{aligned} 0.75= \\&nbsp; &amp; \\frac{P(B\\cap A)}{0.55} \\\\ \\therefore P(B \\cap A) &amp; =0.55 \\times 0.75 \\\\ &amp; =0.4125 \\\\ &amp; \\neq 0.3575 \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(0.3575 \\neq 0.4125\\), it can therefore be said that events A and B are NOT independent. Hence, this statement is false.</p>','2024-01-22 04:30:42',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(314,1,76,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>Two events \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) are such that \\(P(A)=p, P(B)=2 p, P(A \\cup B)=0.42\\) and \\(P(A \\cap B)=0.03\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Show that \\(p=0.15\\)<br>\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. By use of a Venn diagram, or otherwise, show that \\(P(A \\cup \\bar{B})=0.73\\), where \\(\\bar{B}\\) is the complement of B<br>\\(\\text{[2 marks]}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Show that \\(P(A \\cap \\bar{B})=0.12\\) and hence determine whether the events \\(A\\) and \\(\\bar{B}\\) are independent<br>\\(\\text{[2 marks]}\\)</p>','<p>i. <strong>Using the addition rule:</strong> $$ P(A \\cup B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A \\cap B) $$ Substituting in our given values: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 0.42=p+2 p-0.03 \\\\ &amp; 0.45=3 p \\\\ &amp; \\therefore p=0.15 \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. <strong>Since</strong> \\(p=0.15\\) <strong>from part i:</strong> $$ \\begin{gathered} P(A)=0.15 \\\\ P(B)=0.3 \\end{gathered} $$ Then filling in the venn diagram:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:39.69%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1026/458;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f5154cf7c3cb39365c2e97803e5d4605.png\" width=\"1026\" height=\"458\"></figure><p>Hence, looking at the venn diagram: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(A \\cup \\bar{B}) &amp; =0.12+0.03+0.58 \\\\ &amp; =0.73 \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. <strong>From the venn diagram, we can see that: </strong>$$ \\begin{gathered} P(A \\cap \\bar{B})=P(A \\text { only }) \\\\ \\therefore P(A \\cap \\bar{B})=0.12 \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, to prove if \\(A\\) and \\(\\bar{B}\\) are independent, we need to prove that: $$ \\begin{aligned} P(A) \\times P(\\bar{B}) &amp; =P(A \\cap \\bar{B}) \\\\ &amp; =0.12 \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(P(A)=0.15\\) and \\(P(\\bar{B})=0.7\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} P(A) \\times P(\\bar{B}) &amp; =0.15 \\times 0.7 \\\\ &amp; =0.105 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, since \\(P(A) \\times P(\\bar{B}) \\neq 0.12\\), then that means events \\(A\\) and \\(\\bar{B}\\) are NOT independent.</p>','2024-01-22 04:36:54',0,1,5,540,'medium','subtopic'),(315,6,76,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Let \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) be two independent events, where \\(P(A \\cap B)=\\sqrt{x^2-x-2}\\) and \\(P(A \\mid B)=\\sqrt{x+1}\\). What are the expressions for \\(P(B)\\) and \\(P(A)\\)?</p>','<p>Since events \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) are independent: $$ \\therefore P(A \\mid B)=P(A) $$ [This property is outlined in the theory booklet] Hence, since \\(P(A \\mid B)=\\sqrt{x+1}\\) $$ \\therefore P(A)=P(A \\mid B)=\\sqrt{x+1} $$ Moreover, since events \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) are independent, another property is that: $$ P(A \\cap B)=P(A) \\times P(B) $$ Hence, since \\(P(A \\cap B)=\\sqrt{x^2-x-2}\\) : $$ \\sqrt{x^2-x-2}=\\sqrt{x+1} \\times P(B) $$ Rearranging the equation:$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(B) &amp; =\\frac{\\sqrt{x^2-x-2}}{\\sqrt{x+1}} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{\\frac{x^2-x-2}{x+1}} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{\\frac{(x-2)(x+1)}{x+1}} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{x-2} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, \\(P(B)=\\sqrt{x-2}\\)</p>','2024-01-22 04:44:05',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(316,6,76,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>If it is known that:$$ P(A)=0.5, P(B)=0.3 \\text { and } P(A \\cap B)=0.15 $$</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of the following statements will be true?</p>','<p>Considering \\(P(A) \\times P(B)\\) : $$ \\begin{aligned} P(A) \\times P(B) &amp; =0.5 \\times 0.3 \\\\ &amp; =0.15 \\\\ &amp; =P(A \\cap B) \\end{aligned} $$ \\(\\therefore\\) Since \\(P(A \\cap B)=P(A) \\times P(B), A\\) and \\(B\\) are independent</p>','2024-01-22 04:47:55',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(317,6,77,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is an example of a discrete random variable?</p>','<p>A discrete random variable is finite and countable.&nbsp;<br><br>Hence, the only countable quantity out of the options is \"The number of students sitting the HSC in a year\", since it is impossible to have decimal points of students taking an exam.&nbsp;<br><br>For all the other options, decimal points are possible and thus they are considered continuous.</p>','2024-01-22 06:13:30',0,1,1,60,'easy','subtopic'),(318,6,77,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>In an experiment, \\(2\\) marbles are drawn at random and without replacement from a bag which is known to contain \\(4\\) red balls and \\(6\\) black balls. Let \\(X\\) be the number of red balls selected.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Complete the table below:$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline \\text { Outcome } &amp; R R &amp; R B &amp; B R &amp; B B \\\\ \\hline x &amp; 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; \\frac{2}{15} &amp; &amp; &amp; \\\\ \\hline x^2 &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; \\\\ \\hline x^2 P(X=x) &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$</p>','<p>We must first calculate \\(P(R B), P(B R)\\) and \\(P(B B)\\) to put these values into the table $$ \\begin{aligned} P(R B) &amp; =\\frac{4}{10} \\times \\frac{6}{9} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{24}{90} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{4}{15} \\\\ P(B R) &amp; =\\frac{6}{10} \\times \\frac{4}{9} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{24}{90} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{4}{15} \\\\&nbsp; \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} P(B B) &amp; =\\frac{6}{10} \\times \\frac{5}{9} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{30}{90} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3} \\end{aligned} $$\\(&nbsp;\\text { Hence, now completing the table, it should look like: } \\)$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline \\text { Outcome } &amp; R R &amp; R B &amp; B R &amp; B B \\\\ \\hline x &amp; 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; \\frac{2}{15} &amp; \\frac{4}{15} &amp; \\frac{4}{15} &amp; \\frac{1}{3} \\\\ \\hline x^2 &amp; 4 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\\\ \\hline x^2 P(X=x) &amp; \\frac{8}{15} &amp; \\frac{4}{15} &amp; \\frac{4}{15} &amp; 0 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$</p>','2024-01-22 06:18:46',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(319,6,77,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>If \\(X\\) is a random variable such that \\(P(X \\geq 3)=m\\) and \\(P(X \\geq 10)=n\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Show that \\(P(X&lt;3 \\mid X&lt;10)\\) is \\(\\frac{m-1}{n-1}\\)</p>','<p>Recalling the conditional probability formula: $$ P(A \\mid B)=\\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)} $$ Therefore, for this question: $$ P(X&lt;3 \\mid X&lt;10)=\\frac{P(X&lt;3 \\cap X&lt;10)}{P(X&lt;10)} $$ For \\(P(X \\leq 3 \\cap X \\leq 10)\\), this essentially represents the overlap between \\(P(X \\leq 3)\\) and \\(P(X \\leq 10)\\). The overlap for which this occurs is \\(P(X \\leq 3)\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore P(X&lt;3 \\cap X&lt;10)=P(X&lt;3) \\\\ &amp; \\therefore P(X&lt;3 \\mid X&lt;10)=\\frac{P(X&lt;3)}{P(X&lt;10)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1-P(X \\geq 3)}{1-P(X \\geq 10)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1-m}{1-n} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{m-1}{n-1} \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 06:22:44',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(320,6,77,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>The random variable \\(X\\) has the probability distribution given in the following table: $$$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 4 &amp; 5 &amp; 6 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; 0.15 &amp; 0.25 &amp; 0.3 &amp; 0.05 &amp; 0.15 &amp; 0.1 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} \\( \\text { Find } P(X&gt;2 \\mid X \\leq 5) \\)</p>','<p>Recalling the conditional probability formula: $$ P(A \\mid B)=\\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)} $$ Therefore for this question: $$ P(X&gt;2 \\mid X \\leq 5)=\\frac{P(X&gt;2 A N D X \\leq 5)}{P(X \\leq 5)} $$ Note that \\(P(X&gt;2 A N D X \\leq 5)\\) refers to the intersection or overlap between \\(P(X&gt;2)\\) and \\(P(X \\leq 5)\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(X&gt;2 A N D X \\leq 5) &amp; =P(X=3)+P(X=4)+P(X=5) \\\\ &amp; =0.3+0.05+0.15 \\\\ &amp; =0.5 \\end{aligned} $$Moreover, for \\(P(X \\leq 5)\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(X \\leq 5) &amp; =P(X=1)+P(X=2)+P(X=3)+P(X=4)+P(X=5) \\\\ &amp; =0.15+0.25+0.3+0.05+0.15 \\\\ &amp; =0.9 \\end{aligned} $$ Substituting this back into the original equation: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(X&gt;2 \\mid X \\leq 5) &amp; =\\frac{0.5}{0.9} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5}{9} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 06:27:35',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(321,1,77,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks total]</u></p><p>Donald is playing a game involving a spinner. The spinner is divided into three sectors of equal area, being coloured red, yellow and green as shown below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:28.22%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:597/606;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/3b9c10d46bb8e11310e6171bbca025f3.png\" width=\"597\" height=\"606\"></figure><p>Donald spins the spinner \\(5\\) times and lets the random variable, \\(X\\), be the number of times the spinner lands on green. This discrete random variable has the following probability distribution:$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 4 &amp; 5 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; \\frac{32}{243} &amp; a &amp; a &amp; \\frac{40}{243} &amp; \\frac{10}{243} &amp; \\frac{1}{243} \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Find the value of \\(a\\)</p><p>\\([1 \\text{ mark}]\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find \\(P(1&lt;x \\leq 4)\\)</p><p>\\([1 \\text{ mark}]\\)</p>','<p>i. The total sum of all probabilities is equal to \\(1\\) $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\frac{32}{243}+a+a+\\frac{40}{243}+\\frac{10}{243}+\\frac{1}{243}=1 \\\\ 2 a+\\frac{83}{243}=1 \\\\ 2 a=1-\\frac{83}{243} \\\\ 2 a=\\frac{160}{243} \\quad \\therefore a=\\frac{80}{243} \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Now that we know \\(a=\\frac{80}{243}\\), for a discrete probability distribution:<br>$$<br>\\begin{aligned}<br>P(1&lt;x \\leq 4) &amp; =P(x=2)+P(x=3)+P(x=4) \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{80}{243}+\\frac{40}{243}+\\frac{10}{243} \\\\<br>&amp; =\\frac{130}{243}<br>\\end{aligned}<br>$$</p>','2024-01-22 06:33:47',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(322,6,78,'mcq',NULL,'<p>The discrete random variable \\(X\\) text has the following probability distribution: $$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; 2 k &amp; 6 k &amp; 3 k &amp; 4 k \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$ The expected value of \\(X\\) is which of the following?</p>','<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The sum of all probabilities is equal to \\(1\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Hence: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 2 k+6 k+3 k+4 k=1 \\\\ 15 k=1 \\\\ \\therefore k=\\frac{1}{15} \\end{gathered} $$ Recalling the expected value formula:$$ \\begin{aligned} E(x) &amp; =\\sum x p(x) \\\\ &amp; =0 \\times \\frac{2}{15}+1 \\times \\frac{6}{15}+2 \\times \\frac{3}{15}+3 \\times \\frac{4}{15} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{6}{15}+\\frac{6}{15}+\\frac{12}{15} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{24}{15} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{8}{5} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the expected value of \\(X\\) is \\(\\frac{8}{5}\\)</p>','2024-01-22 06:41:49',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(323,1,78,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>Alex records the results of an experiment where the random variable \\(X\\) has the probability distribution shown below: $$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 0 &amp; 2 &amp; 4 &amp; 6 &amp; 8 &amp; 10 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; 0.11 &amp; 0.23 &amp; 0.2 &amp; 0.22 &amp; 0.15 &amp; 0.09 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i.&nbsp; Find the expected value<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the variance&nbsp;<br>[2 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Calculate the standard deviation<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. Recall the expected value equation: $$ E(x)=\\sum x p(x) $$ Therefore, for this question: $$ \\begin{aligned} E(x) &amp; =0 \\times 0.11+2 \\times 0.23+4 \\times 0.2+6 \\times 0.22+8 \\times 0.15+10 \\times 0.09 \\\\ &amp; =0.46+0.8+1.32+1.2+0.9 \\\\ &amp; =4.68 \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Recall the variance equation: $$ \\text { Variance }=\\sum x^2 p(x)-(E(x))^2 $$ Adding an extra row \\(\\left(X^2\\right)\\) for the discrete random variable:$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 0 &amp; 2 &amp; 4 &amp; 6 &amp; 8 &amp; 10 \\\\ \\hline x^2 &amp; 0 &amp; 4 &amp; 16 &amp; 36 &amp; 64 &amp; 100 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; 0.11 &amp; 0.23 &amp; 0.2 &amp; 0.22 &amp; 0.15 &amp; 0.09 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\sum x^2 p(x) &amp; =0 \\times 0.11+4 \\times 0.23+16 \\times 0.2+36 \\times 0.22+64 \\times 0.15+100 \\times 0.09 \\\\ &amp; =0.92+3.2+7.92+9.6+9 \\\\ &amp; =30.64 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, calculating variance: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\operatorname{Var}(x) &amp; =\\sum x^2 p(x)-(E(x))^2 \\\\ &amp; =30.64-(4.68)^2 \\\\ &amp; =8.7376 \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Recall the standard deviation equation: $$\\sigma=\\sqrt{\\operatorname{Var}(x)}$$ $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\sigma&amp;=\\sqrt{8.7376} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 2.96 \\text { (nearest } 2 \\text { d.p.) } \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 06:48:28',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(324,6,78,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>The discrete random variable \\(X\\) has a mean of \\(2\\) and probability distribution: $$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 4 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; 0.3 &amp; 0.45 &amp; m &amp; n \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Show that the two equations in terms of \\(m\\) and \\(n\\) are: $$ \\begin{gathered} m+n=0.25 \\\\ 3 m+4 n=0.8 \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Hence, find the values of \\(m\\) and \\(n\\)<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Since the sum of all probabilities is equal to \\(1\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 0.3+0.45+m+n=1 \\\\ 0.75+m+n=1 \\\\ \\therefore m+n=0.25(1) \\end{gathered} $$ This is one of the equations.&nbsp;<br><br>For the other equation: Recall the expected value/mean formula: $$ \\text { Mean }=E(x)=\\sum x p(x) $$Since we know for this question that the mean is equal to \\(2\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 2=1 \\times 0.3+2 \\times 0.45+3 \\times m+4 \\times n \\\\ 2=0.3+0.9+3 m+4 n \\\\ 2=1.2+3 m+4 n \\\\ \\quad \\therefore 3 m+4 n=0.8(2) \\end{gathered} $$ This is the second equation</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Solving the two equations from part i) simultaneously: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; m+n=0.25(\\text { from equation }(1)) \\\\ &amp; \\therefore m=0.25-n(3) \\end{aligned} $$ Substituting equation (3) into (2): $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 3(0.25-n)+4 n=0.8 \\\\ 0.75-3 n+4 n=0.8 \\\\ 0.75+n=0.8 \\\\ \\therefore n=0.05 \\\\ \\therefore m=0.25-0.05 \\\\ =0.2 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-22 06:54:49',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(325,6,78,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>The discrete random variable \\(X\\) denotes the largest number shown after \\(4\\) dice are thrown. It is known that \\(P(X \\leq x)=\\left(\\frac{x}{6}\\right)^4\\), for \\(x=1,2, \\ldots, 6\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Complete the following probability distribution table:$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 4 &amp; 5 &amp; 6 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; \\frac{1}{1296} &amp; \\frac{15}{1296} &amp; &amp; \\frac{175}{1296} &amp; \\frac{369}{1296} &amp; \\frac{671}{1296} \\\\ \\hline x^2 &amp; &amp; &amp; 9 &amp; &amp; &amp; \\\\ \\hline x^2 P(X=x) &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; \\frac{9225}{1296} &amp; \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Calculate \\(E(x)\\), correct to \\(2\\) decimal places<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Find \\(\\operatorname{Var}(X)\\), correct to \\(2\\) decimal places<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. First, finding the probability of \\(X=3\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Since the total sum of all probabilities is equal to \\(1\\) : $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore P(X=3) &amp; =1-\\frac{1}{1296}-\\frac{15}{1296}-\\frac{175}{1296}-\\frac{369}{1296}-\\frac{671}{1296} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{65}{1296} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, completing the table now:$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 4 &amp; 5 &amp; 6 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; \\frac{1}{1296} &amp; \\frac{15}{1296} &amp; \\frac{65}{1296} &amp; \\frac{175}{1296} &amp; \\frac{369}{1296} &amp; \\frac{671}{1296} \\\\ \\hline x^2 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 &amp; 9 &amp; 16 &amp; 25 &amp; 36 \\\\ \\hline x^2 P(X=x) &amp; \\frac{1}{1296} &amp; \\frac{60}{1296} &amp; \\frac{585}{1296} &amp; \\frac{2800}{1296} &amp; \\frac{9225}{1296} &amp; \\frac{24156}{1296} \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Recalling the expected value formula: $$ E(x)=\\sum x p(x) $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{aligned} E(x) &amp; =1 \\times \\frac{1}{1296}+2 \\times \\frac{15}{1296}+3 \\times \\frac{65}{1296}+4 \\times \\frac{175}{1296}+5 \\times \\frac{369}{1296}+6 \\times \\frac{671}{1296} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{1296}+\\frac{30}{1296}+\\frac{195}{1296}+\\frac{700}{1296}+\\frac{1845}{1296}+\\frac{4026}{1296} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{6797}{1296} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 5.24(\\text { nearest } 2 \\text { d.p.) } \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Recall the variance equation: $$ \\text { Variance }=\\sum x^2 p(x)-(E(x))^2 $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\sum x^2 p(x)=\\frac{1}{1296}+\\frac{60}{1296}+\\frac{585}{1296}+\\frac{2800}{1296}+\\frac{9225}{1296}+\\frac{24156}{1296} \\\\ =\\frac{36827}{1296} \\\\ \\therefore \\operatorname{Var}(x)=\\frac{36827}{1296}-5.24^2 \\\\ \\approx 0.96(\\text { nearest } 2 \\text { d.p. }) \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-22 07:01:56',0,1,5,540,'medium','subtopic'),(326,1,78,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>The discrete random variable \\(X\\) has the following probability distribution: $$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|} \\hline X &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; a &amp; b &amp; 0.35 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$ Given that \\(E(x)\\)=0.9, then:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Find the values of \\(a\\) and \\(b\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Calculate the \\(\\operatorname{Var}(x)\\) correct to 2 decimal places, showing all working<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. Firstly, since the sum of all probabilities must equal to 1 : $$\\therefore a+b+0.35=1$$$$a+b=0.65$$<strong>Moreover, </strong>since \\(E(x)=\\sum x p(x)\\) $$\\therefore E(x)=0.9=0 \\times a+1 \\times b+2 \\times 0.35$$ $$0.9=b+0.7$$ $$\\therefore b=0.2$$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Recall the variance equation: $$ \\operatorname{Var}(x)=\\sum x^2 p(x)-(E(x))^2 $$ Adding an extra row \\(\\left(X^2\\right)\\) for the discrete random variable:$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|} \\hline X &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\\\ \\hline X^2 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \\\\ \\hline P(X=x) &amp; 0.45 &amp; 0.2 &amp; 0.35 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\sum x^2 p(x) &amp; =0 \\times 0.45+1 \\times 0.2+4 \\times 0.35 \\\\ &amp; =0.2+1.4 \\\\ &amp; =1.6 \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Hence, calculating variance:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} \\operatorname{Var}(x) &amp; =\\sum x^2 p(x)-(E(x))^2 \\\\ &amp; =1.6-0.9^2 \\\\ &amp; =0.79 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 07:06:53',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(327,6,79,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of the function \\(y=\\frac{x^2+2 x}{x^2+2}\\) has a horizontal asymptote. The equation of this asymptote is:</p>','<p>To find horizontal asymptotes, we first divide the top and bottom by the denominator\'s highest degree. In this case, we divide by \\(x^2\\): $$ \\therefore \\frac{x^2+2 x}{x^2+2}=\\frac{1+\\frac{2}{x}}{1+\\frac{2}{x^2}} $$ consider the limit as \\(x \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty\\): $$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty} \\frac{1+\\frac{2}{x}}{1+\\frac{2}{x^2}}=\\frac{1+0}{1+0}=1 $$ Therefore, the horizontal asymptote has equation \\(y=1\\)</p>','2024-01-22 20:06:43',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(328,6,79,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following options are the asymptote(s) for \\(y=\\frac{1}{x-4}\\)?</p>','<p>Considering the vertical asymptote, the denominator cannot equal to \\(0\\). Hence: $$ \\begin{gathered} x-4 \\neq 0 \\\\ x \\neq 4 \\end{gathered} $$ <strong>Therefore, a vertical asymptote exists at \\(x=4\\)</strong>&nbsp;<br><br>Moreover, considering the horizontal asymptote, taking limits: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty} \\frac{1}{x-4} &amp; =\\lim _{x \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty} \\frac{\\frac{1}{x}}{1-\\frac{4}{x}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{0}{1-0} \\\\ &amp; =0 \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Therefore, a horizontal asymptote exists at \\(y=0\\)</strong></p>','2024-01-22 20:12:23',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(329,6,79,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the domain of \\(y=\\frac{1}{x+3}\\)?</p>','<p>The key point to remember here is that the domain includes all real \\(x\\), however the one exception is the vertical asymptote, where: $$ \\begin{gathered} x+3 \\neq 0 \\\\ x \\neq-3 \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, the domain would be for all real \\(x\\), but \\(x \\neq-3\\). Expressed in interval notation: $$ (-\\infty, 0) \\cup(0, \\infty) $$</p>','2024-01-22 20:18:45',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(330,6,79,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph below shows the function \\(y=f(x)\\):</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:24.61%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:549/435;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/99f249befe7a8b301eb9b41f57089d42.png\" width=\"549\" height=\"435\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of the following options is the most likely equation of the graph?</p>','<p>From the graph, it can be seen that there exists a vertical asymptote at \\(x=-1\\), as well as an \\(x, y\\) intercept at the origin.<br>&nbsp;</p><p><br><strong>Since a vertical asymptote exists, we can eliminate \\(y=\\sqrt{x}\\) and \\(y=-e^{-x}+1\\)&nbsp;</strong><br>&nbsp;</p><p><br><strong>Moreover, since there is no horizontal asymptote, we can eliminate \\(y=-\\frac{1}{x+1}+1\\)&nbsp;</strong><br>&nbsp;</p><p><br>Hence, the answer must be \\(y=\\ln (x+1)\\)</p>','2024-01-22 20:23:04',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(331,6,79,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Without using calculus, sketch the graph of \\(y=3-\\frac{1}{x+2}\\), showing any intercepts and asymptotes.</p>','<p>Since denominator cannot equal \\(0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; x+2 \\neq 0 \\\\ &amp; x \\neq-2 \\end{aligned} $$ There is thus a vertical asymptote \\(x=-2\\) Moreover, as \\(x \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty} 3-\\frac{1}{x+2} &amp; =3-0 \\\\ &amp; =3 \\end{aligned} $$ There is thus a horizontal asymptote \\(y=3\\) To find \\(x\\) - intercept, let \\(y=0\\) and solve for \\(x\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; 0=3-\\frac{1}{x+2} \\\\ &amp; 3=\\frac{1}{x+2} \\\\ &amp; 3 x+6=1 \\\\ &amp; 3 x=-5 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x=-\\frac{5}{3} \\text { is } x \\text {-intercept } \\end{gathered} $$To find \\(y\\) - intercept, let \\(x=0\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} y=3-\\frac{1}{0+2} \\\\ =3-\\frac{1}{2} \\\\ =\\frac{5}{2} \\\\ \\therefore y=\\frac{5}{2} \\text { is } y \\text {-intercept } \\end{gathered} $$ Now combining all this information and sketching:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:508/485;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9e959744ef46330dfb02f1c4bb64378f.png\" width=\"508\" height=\"485\"></figure>','2024-01-22 20:29:52',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(332,6,80,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The function \\(f(x)=\\ln x\\) is transformed into the function \\(g(x)=\\ln (x+2)-3\\) by a horizontal translation of \\(2\\) units, followed by a vertical translation of \\(3\\) units.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of the following correctly shows the directions of the translations?</p>','<p>When \\(x \\rightarrow x+\\alpha\\), this is a translation towards the left&nbsp;<br><br>When \\(\\ln (x+2) \\rightarrow \\ln (x+2)-3\\) this represents a vertical translation downwards</p>','2024-01-22 22:41:42',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(333,6,80,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) is shown below.</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:21.23%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:441/514;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9b80acc25063203e9e7681a9606321b8.png\" width=\"441\" height=\"514\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of the graphs below represents \\(y=f(x+2)+3\\)?</p>','<p><strong>Since \\(x \\rightarrow x+2\\), then this means that the graph is shifted left 2 units</strong></p><p><br><br><strong>Since \\(y=f(x+2) \\rightarrow y=f(x+2)+3\\), then this means that the graph is shifted up 3 units&nbsp;</strong></p><p><br><br>Hence, the original \\(x\\) - intercept at \\((2,0)\\) now has the coordinate: $$ (2-2,0+3)=(0,3) $$ Therefore, only one graph matches this description:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:18.01%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:370/579;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a5a98e68582cd374ffe13024ba020c68.png\" width=\"370\" height=\"579\"></figure>','2024-01-22 22:52:20',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(334,6,80,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) is shown below.</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:26.14%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:874/540;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e308256c590ea5bd5ac29b81e7a4a72a.png\" width=\"874\" height=\"540\"></figure><p>The graph is transformed into the following graph:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:33.56%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:529/307;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f7c77be893fe1fb286e915822cd932a6.png\" width=\"529\" height=\"307\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of these expressions is the equation of the new graph?</p>','<p><strong>The graph is seen to be shifted left by 4 units.</strong> Hence, it can be said that: $$ x \\rightarrow x+4 $$ Therefore, the new graph has equation \\(f(x+4)\\)</p>','2024-01-22 22:58:30',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(335,6,80,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) is shown below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:24.35%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:429/406;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e3f3e0d09a9789b0f7f88536b23d3803.png\" width=\"429\" height=\"406\"></figure><p>Hence, sketch the graph of \\(y=f(x+3)\\)</p>','<p>Since \\(x \\rightarrow x+3\\), this represents a graph shift \\(3\\) units to the left.&nbsp;<br><br>Thus, the new \\(x\\) - intercepts will now be: $$ \\begin{gathered} x=-1-3,0-3,3-3 \\\\ \\therefore x=-4,-3,0 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-22 23:03:31',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(336,6,80,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Given the graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) shown below, sketch \\(y=f(x+3)+5\\), showing any important features.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:511/389;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/470dfc9c9f2f754361b68dcd6727a8df.png\" width=\"511\" height=\"389\"></figure>','<p>Since \\(x \\rightarrow x+3\\), the graph will be shifted to the left \\(3\\) units&nbsp;<br><br>Moreover, since \\(y=f(x+3) \\rightarrow y=f(x+3)+5\\), the graph will be shifted upwards \\(5\\) units.&nbsp;<br><br>Therefore, the vertex of the graph (pointy bit) which originally had coordinate of \\((3,0)\\), now has coordinate \\((0,5)\\)</p><p>Sketching the graph:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:463/519;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/04ebbf4cfab44ce51e5763780ecf3e7c.png\" width=\"463\" height=\"519\"></figure>','2024-01-22 23:06:15',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(337,6,80,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) is shown below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:45.83%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1379/672;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/c1fb2b5c3993b2dfe89bb897cb56a4db.png\" width=\"1379\" height=\"672\"></figure><p>On the same axes, draw the curve \\(y=f(x+1)+1\\)</p>','<p>When \\(x \\rightarrow x+1\\), this means that the function is shifted left \\(1\\) unit&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When a \"\\(+1\\)\" is added, this means that the function is shifted upwards \\(1\\) unit&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, the final transformation is shifted left \\(1\\) unit and up \\(1\\) unit. The graph (in red) would therefore look like:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:41.71%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1379/672;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/8826624436e58e81eb3e59e03a60be68.png\" width=\"1379\" height=\"672\"></figure>','2024-01-22 23:09:21',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(338,6,81,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The circle \\((x-6)^2+(y+4)^2=9\\) is enlarged by a factor of \\(2\\) with centre the origin.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is its resulting equation?</p>','<p>If the circle is enlarged with centre at the origin, this means that it is both horizontally and vertically dilated by a factor of \\(2\\).&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p><br><strong>Horizontally dilated by a factor of \\(2\\) means that \\(x \\rightarrow \\frac{x}{2}\\)&nbsp;</strong><br>&nbsp;</p><p><br><strong>Vertically dilated by a factor of \\(2\\) means that \\(y \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{2}\\)</strong> $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; \\therefore\\left(\\frac{x}{2}-6\\right)^2+\\left(\\frac{y}{2}+4\\right)^2=9 \\\\ &amp; \\left(\\frac{x-12}{2}\\right)^2+\\left(\\frac{y+8}{2}\\right)^2=9 \\\\ &amp; \\frac{(x-12)^2}{4}+\\frac{(y+8)^2}{4}=9 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore(x-12)^2+(y+8)^2=36 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-22 23:17:08',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(339,6,81,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The function \\(f(x)=4(x+1)^3\\) is transformed by a vertical dilation with scale factor \\(2\\) as well as a horizontal dilation with scale factor \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the equation of the new function \\(g(x)\\)?</p>','<p>A vertical dilation with scale factor \\(2\\) means that: $$ \\begin{gathered} y \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{2} \\\\ \\therefore \\frac{y}{2}=4(x+1)^3 \\\\ y=8(x+1)^3 \\end{gathered} $$A horizontal dilation with scale factor \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\) means that: $$ \\begin{gathered} x \\rightarrow \\frac{x}{\\frac{1}{3}}=3 x \\\\ \\therefore g(x)=8(3 x+1)^3 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-22 23:17:29',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(340,6,81,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following gives the transformation(s) needed to change \\(y=\\frac{3}{x+1}\\) into \\(y=-\\frac{6}{x+1}\\)?</p>','<p>If we apply a vertical dilation of scale factor \\(2\\) to the equation \\(y=\\frac{3}{x+1}\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} y \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{2} \\\\ \\therefore \\frac{y}{2}=\\frac{3}{x+1} \\\\ y=\\frac{6}{x+1} \\end{gathered} $$ Then, if we flip the graph about the \\(x\\) - axis: $$ \\begin{gathered} y \\rightarrow-y \\\\ \\therefore-y=\\frac{6}{x+1} \\\\ y=-\\frac{6}{x+1} \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, the series of transformations needed would be applying a vertical dilation of scale factor \\(2\\), then flipping the graph about the \\(x\\) - axis.</p>','2024-01-22 23:17:48',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(341,6,81,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>The function \\(f(x)=\\frac{6 x}{\\sqrt{x^2+1}}\\) is dilated horizontally by scale factor \\(2\\) . Find the equation of the new function \\(g(x)\\)</p>','<p>Since there is a horizontal dilation of factor \\(2\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} x &amp; \\rightarrow \\frac{x}{2} \\\\ \\therefore g(x) &amp; =\\frac{6\\left(\\frac{x}{2}\\right)}{\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{x}{2}\\right)^2+1}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3 x}{\\sqrt{\\frac{x^2}{4}+1}} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-22 23:18:13',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(342,6,81,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>The function \\(f(x)=2^x+1\\) is dilated vertically by a factor of \\(2\\). Find the equation of the function formed and sketch the result, showing key features.</p>','<p><strong>First finding the new equation, after being dilated vertically by a factor of \\(2\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; y \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{2} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\frac{y}{2}=2^x+1 \\\\ &amp; y=2\\left(2^x+1\\right) \\\\ &amp; =2^{x+1}+2 \\\\ &amp; \\end{gathered} $$ Finding key features before sketching the graph, we start off with the \\(y\\) - intercept:<br>&nbsp;</p><p>When \\(x=0\\) : $$ \\begin{aligned} y &amp; =2^{0+1}+2 \\\\ &amp; =4 \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, \\(\\mathrm{y}\\) - intercept occurs at \\(y=4\\). Moreover, we should notice that when \\(x=-1\\) : $$ \\begin{aligned} y &amp; =2^{-1+1}+2 \\\\ &amp; =2^0+2 \\\\ &amp; =1+2 \\\\ &amp; =3 \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Therefore, when \\(x=-1, y=3\\)</strong><br><br><strong>Additionally, for the graph of \\(y=2^x\\), a horizontal asymptote of \\(x=0\\) would occur because as \\(x \\rightarrow-\\infty, 2^x \\rightarrow 0\\).</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Therefore, for the graph of \\(y=2^{x+1}+2\\), we find the horizontal asymptote: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{x \\rightarrow-\\infty} 2^{x+1}+2 &amp; =0+2 \\\\ &amp; =2 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the horizontal asymptote will be \\(x=2\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Finally, sketching the graph:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:23.17%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:435/500;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/979a2e7bf12ffa5cb2e8b2f79e512f86.png\" width=\"435\" height=\"500\"></figure>','2024-01-22 23:18:47',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(343,6,82,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The function \\(f(x)=2(x+2)^3\\) is transformed by a horizontal translation \\(2\\) units to the right, followed by a vertical dilation with scale factor \\(2\\).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">What is the equation of the new function, \\(g(x)\\)?</p>','<p><strong>A horizontal translation to the right \\(2\\) units means that:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} x &amp; \\rightarrow x-2 \\\\ \\therefore 2(x+2)^3 &amp; \\rightarrow 2(x-2+2)^3 \\\\ &amp; =2 x^3 \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>A vertical dilation with factor \\(2\\) means that:</strong> $$ y \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{2} $$$$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore y=2 x^3 \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{2}=2 x^3 \\\\ y=4 x^3 \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, (g(x)=4 x^3\\)</p>','2024-01-23 00:37:45',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(344,6,82,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The diagram below shows the graph of \\(y=f(x)\\):</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:35.06%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1427/940;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/99bfcf42209246a49cdcdc654e9a427f.png\" width=\"1427\" height=\"940\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of the following shows the graph of \\(y=f(x+2)-1\\)?</p>','<p><strong>If \\(x \\rightarrow x+2\\), this means that the graph shifts to the left \\(2\\) units</strong></p><p><strong>If \\(f(x+2) \\rightarrow f(x+2)-1\\), this means that the graph shifts downwards \\(1\\) unit</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, the points: $$ \\begin{aligned} (-3,2) &amp; \\rightarrow(-5,1) \\\\ (1,-2) &amp; \\rightarrow(-1,-3) \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, my answer is the graph:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:36.41%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1366/919;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/0498d25ff9666f9360b7145bed036673.png\" width=\"1366\" height=\"919\"></figure>','2024-01-23 00:37:45',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(345,6,82,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=\\frac{3}{x+2}\\) is translated \\(5\\) units right and dilated vertically by a factor of \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of the following gives the equation of the new function?</p>','<p>When the graph is translated \\(5\\) units right: $$ \\begin{gathered} x \\rightarrow x-5 \\\\ \\therefore \\frac{3}{x+2} \\rightarrow \\frac{3}{x-5+2}=\\frac{3}{x-3} \\\\ y=\\frac{3}{x-3} \\end{gathered} $$ A vertical dilation by a factor of \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\) means: $$ y \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{\\frac{1}{3}}=3 y $$$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore 3 y=\\frac{3}{x-3} \\\\ &amp; y=\\frac{1}{x-3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 00:38:18',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(346,6,82,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Give a possible sequence of transformations that transforms \\(y=f(x)\\) to \\(y=4 \\times f(3 x-6)+2\\). Ensure that you use appropriate terminology in your response&nbsp;</p>','<p>Starting off with \\(y=f(x)\\) <strong>First, a horizontal translation to the right 6 units means that \\(x \\rightarrow x-6\\) $$ \\therefore y=f(x-6) $$</strong></p><p><strong>Then, a horizontal dilation by a factor of \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\) means that \\(x \\rightarrow \\frac{x}{\\frac{1}{3}}=3 x\\)</strong> $$ \\therefore y=f(3 x-6) $$ <strong>Next, a vertical dilation by a factor of 4 means that \\(y \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{4}\\)</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore \\frac{y}{4}=f(3 x-6) \\\\ &amp; y=4 \\times f(3 x-6) \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Finally, a vertical translation up 2 units means that \\(y \\rightarrow y-2\\)</strong>$$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; \\therefore y-2=4 \\times f(3 x-6) \\\\ &amp; y=4 \\times f(3 x-6)+2 \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-23 00:39:16',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(347,6,82,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>i. Clearly state the transformations that need to be applied to \\(y=\\frac{1}{x}\\) to obtain the new function \\(y=\\frac{5}{2 x+6}+2$\\)</p><p>[2 marks]<br>&nbsp;</p><p><br>ii. Hence, draw a neat sketch of \\(y=\\frac{5}{2 x+6}+2\\)</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. We begin with \\(y=\\frac{1}{x}\\) First, shifting to the left \\(6\\) units, we get \\(x \\rightarrow x+6\\) $$ \\therefore \\frac{1}{x} \\rightarrow \\frac{1}{x+6} $$ Then, a horizontal dilation of factor \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\), we get \\(x \\rightarrow \\frac{x}{\\frac{1}{2}}=2 x\\) $$ \\therefore \\frac{1}{x+6} \\rightarrow \\frac{1}{2 x+6} $$ Then, a vertical dilation of factor \\(5\\), we get \\(y \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{5}\\) $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore y=\\frac{1}{2 x+6} \\rightarrow \\frac{y}{5}=\\frac{1}{2 x+6} \\\\ y=\\frac{5}{2 x+6} \\end{gathered} $$ Finally, we shift the graph up \\(2\\) units to get: $$ y=\\frac{5}{2 x+6}+2 $$ <strong>Note that other answers do exist, feel free to send any alternative answers to us as well!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Before sketching, first determine asymptotes and intercepts: Since the denominator cannot equal to \\(0\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; \\therefore 2 x+6 \\neq 0 \\\\ &amp; 2 x \\neq-6 \\\\ &amp; x \\neq-3 \\end{gathered} $$ <strong>Vertical asymptote exists at \\(x=-3\\)</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When \\(x \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty\\): $$ \\lim _{x \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty} \\frac{5}{2 x+6}+2=0+2=2 $$ <strong>Horizontal asymptote exists at \\(y=2\\)</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To find the \\(y\\) - intercept, let \\(x=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y &amp; =\\frac{5}{0+6}+2 \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{17}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Therefore, \\(y\\) - intercept at \\(\\left(0, \\frac{17}{6}\\right)\\)</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To find the \\(x\\) - intercept, let \\(y=0\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; 0=\\frac{5}{2 x+6}+2 \\\\ &amp; -2=\\frac{5}{2 x+6} \\\\ &amp; 2 x+6=-\\frac{5}{2} \\\\ &amp; 2 x=-\\frac{5}{2}-6 \\\\ &amp; 2 x=-\\frac{17}{2} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x=-\\frac{17}{4} \\end{gathered} $$<strong>Therefore, \\(x\\) - intercept at \\(\\left(-\\frac{17}{4}, 0\\right)\\)</strong>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p><br>Now sketching the graph:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:27.46%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:622/457;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/eaedc1d79cbd38bb18bbb528e929cab4.png\" width=\"622\" height=\"457\"></figure>','2024-01-23 00:39:51',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(348,6,82,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>The function \\(f(x)=e^x\\) is transformed to \\(g(x)=-e^{2(x+3)}\\).</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Describe, in words, the sequence of transformations.</p>','<p><strong>We start with \\(f(x)=e^x\\)&nbsp;</strong><br><br>To undergo the transformation \\(e^x \\rightarrow-e^x\\), we first reflect about the \\(x\\) - axis.&nbsp;<br><br>Then, to undergo the transformation \\(e^x \\rightarrow-e^{2 x}\\), we then must horizontally dilate by a factor of half, since if we dilate by a factor of half: $$ x \\rightarrow \\frac{x}{\\frac{1}{2}}=2 x $$ Finally, to undergo the transformation \\(-e^{2 x} \\rightarrow-e^{2(x+3)}\\), we finally must shift left \\(3\\) units, since if we shift left by \\(3\\) units: $$ x \\rightarrow(x+3) $$ <strong>Therefore, this is the sequence of transformations we must go through&nbsp;</strong><br><br><strong>Note</strong> here that another potential answer would\'ve been to shift left \\(\\frac{3}{2}\\) units first before horizontally dilating by a factor of \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\). Either answer will be accepted, but the order must be correct!</p>','2024-01-23 00:40:20',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(349,6,82,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>The circle \\(x^2+6 x+y^2-4 y-12=0\\) is reflected in the \\(x\\) - axis.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Sketch the reflected circle, showing the coordinates of the centre and the radius.</p>','<p>When a graph is reflected about the \\(x\\) - axis, the transformation which occurs is: $$ \\begin{aligned} y &amp; \\rightarrow-y \\\\ \\therefore x^2+6 x+y^2-4 y-3 &amp; \\rightarrow x^2+6 x+(-y)^2-4(-y)-3 \\\\ &amp; =x^2+6 x+y^2+4 y-3 \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{gathered} x^2+6 x+y^2+4 y-3=0 \\\\ x^2+6 x+9+y^2+4 y+4-12=4+9 \\\\ (x+3)^2+(y+2)^2=13+12 \\\\ \\therefore(x+3)^2+(y+2)^2=25 \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, the centre of the circle has coordinates \\((-3,-2)\\)&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p><br>Radius is \\(\\sqrt{25}=5\\)</p>','2024-01-23 00:40:37',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(350,6,83,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>By drawing two appropriate graphs, determine how many roots there are of the equation \\(e^x+2 x-5=0\\)</p>','<p>Since we know there are \\(2\\) graphs, rearrange our equation to make \\(e^x\\) the subject: $$ \\therefore e^x=5-2 x $$ Hence, now sketching these \\(2\\) graphs:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:23.97%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:536/518;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ef476ef9facb17cb3b4763729fa3fe0d.png\" width=\"536\" height=\"518\"></figure><p><strong>Notice that there is no need to find the coordinate of the intersection point, however the \\(x\\) and \\(y\\) intercepts should be shown.</strong>&nbsp;<br><br>Since there is only \\(1\\) intersection point, there will thus only be one \\(1\\) root for the equation</p>','2024-01-23 02:37:07',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(351,6,83,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>i. Sketch the graph of \\(y=|3 x+7|\\), clearly labelling the \\(x\\) and \\(y\\) intercepts&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. By using the graph sketched in part i) above, or otherwise, state the values(s) of \\(m\\) such that \\(|3 x+7|=m\\) has no solutions&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. <strong>For the graph of \\(y=|3 x+7|\\): To find the \\(y\\) - intercept, let \\(x=0\\):</strong> $$ y=|0+7|=7 $$ Therefore, \\(y\\) - intercept coordinate is \\((0,7)\\) To find the \\(x\\)-intercept, let \\(y=0\\):<br>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 0=|3 x+7| \\\\ &amp; 3 x+7=0 \\\\ &amp; 3 x=-7 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x=-\\frac{7}{3} \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, \\(x\\) - intercept coordinate is \\(\\left(-\\frac{7}{3}, 0\\right)\\)&nbsp;</p><p><br>Now sketching the graph:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:32.06%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:539/487;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/1686c1ddf4c825def1e21a80b04a4414.png\" width=\"539\" height=\"487\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Now considering a line with equation \\(y=m\\), and the previous graph \\(y=\\mid 3 x+\\) \\(7 \\mid\\), if we want \\(|3 x+7|=m\\) to have no solutions, then the two graphs cannot intersect.&nbsp;<br><br><strong>Hence, in order for \\(y=m\\) to not intersect with the previous graph, \\(m\\) must be lower than \\(0\\)</strong>, i.e.: $$ m&lt;0 $$ Since any horizontal line below the \\(x\\) - axis will not touch the absolute value graph.</p>','2024-01-23 02:37:23',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(352,6,83,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>The function \\(y=\\frac{2}{x-2}\\) has been graphed on the coordinate plane below:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:425/425;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/fed886370a6f51e88fe1d2ef692f5fda.png\" width=\"425\" height=\"425\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Sketch the graph of \\(y=|x|-3\\) on the same axes above, clearly showing any intercepts with the axes&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Hence, determine the number of solutions of the equation: $$ |x|-\\frac{2}{x-2}=3 $$&nbsp;</p><p>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. <strong>Considering the intercepts:</strong></p><p>To find \\(y\\) - intercept, let \\(x=0\\). $$ \\therefore y-\\text { intercept at } y=-3 $$To find \\(x\\) - intercept, let \\(y=0\\)$$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; \\therefore 0=|x|-3 \\\\ &amp; |x|=3 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x-\\text { intercept at } x= \\pm 3 \\end{gathered} $$Now sketching the graph:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:35.1%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:598/343;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/42b50d0aa3541fdf5e92e7f74c3bb8d7.png\" width=\"598\" height=\"343\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. <strong>Equating the equation of the two graphs:</strong> $$ \\begin{gathered} \\frac{2}{x-2}=|x|-3 \\\\ \\therefore|x|-\\frac{2}{x-2}=3 \\end{gathered} $$ Since there are \\(3\\) intersections between the two graphs, there will hence be \\(3\\) solutions to the equation.</p>','2024-01-23 02:37:36',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(353,6,83,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>By drawing graphs on the same coordinate axes, show how many solutions exist for the equation \\(\\sin x=\\left|\\frac{x-\\pi}{4}\\right|\\) in the domain \\((-\\infty, \\infty)\\)</p>','<p>Sketching the two graphs \\(y=\\sin x\\) and \\(y=\\left|\\frac{x-\\pi}{4}\\right|\\) on the same axes:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:28.14%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:610/411;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/d43e1f0273bde0fedb1b534d8b885306.png\" width=\"610\" height=\"411\"></figure><p>As can be seen, since the graphs intersect each other twice, it can be said that there are two solutions to the equation \\(\\sin x=\\left|\\frac{x-\\pi}{4}\\right|\\) !</p>','2024-01-23 02:37:56',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(354,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The derivative of \\(y=e^{6 x}\\) is:</p>','<p>Using the chain rule for exponentials \\(\\left(e^{f(x)}\\right)^{\\prime}=f^{\\prime}(x) e^{f(x)}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =(6 x)^{\\prime} e^{6 x} \\\\ &amp; =6 e^{6 x} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 21:24:10',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(355,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given that \\(f(x)=e^{x^3}\\), then \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\) will equal to which of the following?</p>','<p>Using the chain rule for exponentials \\(\\left(e^{f(x)}\\right)^{\\prime}=f^{\\prime}(x) e^{f(x)}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\left(x^3\\right)^{\\prime} e^{x^3} \\\\ &amp; =3 x^2 e^{x^3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 21:36:39',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(356,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The derivative of \\(e^{4 x^3+1}\\) is:</p>','<p>Using the chain rule for exponentials \\(\\left(e^{f(x)}\\right)^{\\prime}=f^{\\prime}(x) e^{f(x)}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(e^{4 x^3+1}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\left(4 x^3+1\\right)^{\\prime} e^{4 x^3+1} \\\\ &amp; =12 x^2 e^{4 x^3+1} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 21:46:24',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(357,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>If \\(y=x^2 e^{3 x-1}\\), then \\(y^{\\prime}\\) is equal to:</p>','<p>Considering the product rule \\((u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u\\)<br>And using the chain rule for exponentials \\(\\left(e^{f(x)}\\right)^{\\prime}=f^{\\prime}(x) e^{f(x)}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =\\left(x^2\\right)^{\\prime} e^{3 x-1}+\\left(e^{3 x-1}\\right)^{\\prime} x^2 \\\\ &amp; =2 x e^{3 x-1}+(3 x-1)^{\\prime} e^{3 x-1} x^2 \\\\ &amp; =2 x e^{3 x-1}+3 x^2 e^{3 x-1} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 21:52:42',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(358,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the derivative of \\(\\frac{e^{3-x}}{x^3}\\)?</p>','<p>Considering the quotient rule \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}\\)&nbsp;<br>And using the chain rule for exponentials \\(\\left(e^{f(x)}\\right)^{\\prime}=f^{\\prime}(x) e^{f(x)}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(\\frac{e^{3-x}}{x^3}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{\\left(e^{3-x}\\right)^{\\prime} x^3-\\left(x^3\\right)^{\\prime} e^{3-x}}{\\left(x^3\\right)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{-e^{3-x} x^3-3 x^2 e^{3-x}}{x^6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{-e^{3-x} x^2(x+3)}{x^6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{-e^{3-x}(x+3)}{x^4} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 21:59:58',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(359,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the derivative of \\(4^{3 x-5}\\)?</p>','<p>Using the formula for \\(y=a^{f(x)}\\) on the formula sheet: $$ \\frac{d y}{d x}=(\\ln a) f^{\\prime}(x) a^{f(x)} $$ Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(4^{3 x-5}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =(\\ln 4)(3 x-5)^{\\prime} 4^{3 x-5} \\\\ &amp; =3(\\ln 4) 4^{3 x-5} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 22:11:33',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(360,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the derivative of \\(2^{3 x+1}\\)?</p>','<p>Using the formula for \\(y=a^{f(x)}\\) on the formula sheet: $$ \\frac{d y}{d x}=(\\ln a) f^{\\prime}(x) a^{f(x)} $$ Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(2^{3 x+1}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =(\\ln 2)(3 x+1)^{\\prime} 2^{3 x+1} \\\\ &amp; =3(\\ln 2) 2^{3 x+1} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 22:17:29',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(361,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given that \\(f(x)=5^{x^3-2 x^2+2}\\), which of the following is the correct expression for \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\)?</p>','<p>Using the formula for \\(y=a^{f(x)}\\) on the formula sheet: $$ \\frac{d y}{d x}=(\\ln a) f^{\\prime}(x) a^{f(x)} $$ Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(5^{x^3-2 x^2+2}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =(\\ln 5)\\left(x^3-2 x^2+2\\right)^{\\prime}\\left(5^{x^3-2 x^2+2}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =\\ln 5\\left(3 x^2-4 x\\right)\\left(5^{x^3-2 x^2+2}\\right) \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 22:22:35',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(362,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Find the equation of the normal to \\(y=x e^x\\) at the point where \\(x=1\\)</p>','<p><strong>To find the normal, we differentiate first:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =(x)^{\\prime} e^x+\\left(e^x\\right)^{\\prime} x\\&nbsp;[\\text {product rule }] \\\\ &amp; =e^x+x e^x \\end{aligned} $$ When \\(x=1\\), the gradient of the tangent is: $$ \\begin{aligned} m &amp; =e^1+1\\left(e^1\\right) \\\\ &amp; =2 e \\end{aligned} $$ Since the gradient of the normal will be the negative reciprocal of the tangent, the gradient of the normal will be: $$ m_n=-\\frac{1}{2 e} $$ <strong>When \\(x=1, y=1 e^1=e\\)</strong><br>&nbsp;</p><p>Finally, using the point - gradient formula to find the equation of the normal: $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; y-y_1=m_n\\left(x-x_1\\right) \\\\ &amp; y-e=-\\frac{1}{2 e}(x-1) \\\\ &amp; y-e=-\\frac{x}{2 e}+\\frac{1}{2 e} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore y=-\\frac{x}{2 e}+\\frac{1}{2 e}+\\mathrm{e} \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-23 22:27:28',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(363,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The displacement of a particle measured in \\(x\\) centimetres after \\(\\mathrm{t}\\) seconds is given by the expression: $$ x=2 e^{t^2+1} $$</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which of the following is the expression for the velocity of this object?</p>','<p>The velocity of a particle is defined as the rate of change of its displacement. Hence \\(v=\\frac{d x}{d t}\\), so differentiating \\(x\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} v=\\frac{d x}{d t} &amp; \\left.=2\\left(t^2+1\\right)^{\\prime} e^{t^2+1} \\text { [Chain rule] }\\right] \\\\ &amp; =2 \\cdot 2 t e^{t^2+1} \\\\ &amp; =4 t e^{t^2+1} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 22:32:15',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(364,6,84,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The displacement of a particle measured in \\(x\\) metres after \\(t\\) seconds is given by the expression: $$ x=e^{2 t}+3 t^2+2 t $$</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">All the following expressions are true EXCEPT for:</p>','<p><strong>Testing out each option to check if they are true or not:</strong> When \\(t=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} x &amp; =e^0+3(0)^2+2(0) \\\\ &amp; =1 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, when \\(t=0, x=1\\) is true</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Differentiating \\(x\\) to find the expression for velocity \\(v\\):</strong> $$ v=\\frac{d x}{d t}=2 e^{2 t}+6 t+2\\ [\\text {Chain rule}] $$ Hence, \\(v=2 e^{e t}+6 t+2\\) is true when \\(t=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} v &amp; =2 e^0+6(0)+2 \\\\ &amp; =2+2 \\\\ &amp; =4 \\end{aligned} $$Hence, when \\(t=0, v=4\\) is true</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Differentiating \\(v\\) again to find the expression for \\(a\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} a=\\frac{d v}{d t} &amp; =2 \\cdot 2 e^{2 t}+6\\ [\\text {Chain rule}] \\\\ &amp; =4 e^{2 t}+6 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, \\(a\\) being equal to \\(2 e^{2 t}+6\\) is FALSE. The reason why it is wrong is because the chain rule has not been applied!</p>','2024-01-23 23:08:12',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(365,6,85,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the derivative of \\(2 \\ln (4 x)\\)?</p>','<p>Using the chain rule for logarithms \\((\\ln f(x))^{\\prime}=\\frac{f^{\\prime}(x)}{f(x)}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} (2 \\ln 4 x)^{\\prime} &amp; =2 \\cdot \\frac{(4 x)^{\\prime}}{4 x} \\\\ &amp; =2 \\cdot \\frac{4}{4 x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{x} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 23:26:13',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(366,6,85,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>If \\(y=3 \\ln \\left(x^2\\right)\\), then the expression for \\(y^{\\prime}\\) will be:</p>','<p>Using the chain rule for logarithms \\((\\ln f(x))^{\\prime}=\\frac{f^{\\prime}(x)}{f(x)}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(3 \\ln \\left(x^2\\right)\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =3 \\cdot \\frac{\\left(x^2\\right)^{\\prime}}{x^2} \\\\ &amp; =3 \\cdot \\frac{2 x}{x^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{6}{x} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 23:26:13',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(367,6,85,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given that \\(f(x)=x \\ln x\\), then \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\) will equal:</p>','<p>Considering the product rule \\((u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u\\)</p><p>And using the derivative for logarithms \\((\\ln x)^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{x}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} (x \\ln x)^{\\prime} &amp; =(x)^{\\prime} \\ln x+(\\ln x)^{\\prime} x \\\\ &amp; =1 \\cdot \\ln x+\\frac{1}{x} \\cdot x \\\\ &amp; =\\ln x+1 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 23:26:13',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(368,6,85,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the derivative of \\(y=\\frac{x^2}{\\ln \\left(x^2\\right)}\\)?</p>','<p>Considering the quotient rule \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}\\)</p><p>And using the chain rule for logarithms \\((\\ln f(x))^{\\prime}=\\frac{f^{\\prime}(x)}{f(x)}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{\\left(x^2\\right)^{\\prime} \\ln \\left(x^2\\right)-\\left(\\ln \\left(x^2\\right)\\right)^{\\prime} x^2}{\\ln \\left(x^2\\right)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2 x \\ln \\left(x^2\\right)-\\frac{2 x}{x^2} \\cdot x^2}{\\ln \\left(x^2\\right)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2 x \\ln \\left(x^2\\right)-2 x}{\\ln \\left(x^2\\right)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2 x\\left(\\ln \\left(x^2\\right)-1\\right)}{\\ln \\left(x^2\\right)^2} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 23:26:13',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(369,6,85,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Find \\(\\frac{d}{d x}\\left(\\ln \\left(\\frac{3 x}{x^2+2}\\right)\\right)\\), giving your answer in simplest form.</p>','<p>Let \\(y=\\ln \\left(\\frac{3 x}{x^2+2}\\right)\\):</p><p>Using logarithmic laws: $$ y=\\ln (3 x)-\\ln \\left(x^2+2\\right) $$ Since \\((\\ln x)^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{x}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore y^{\\prime} &amp; \\left.=3 \\times \\frac{1}{3 x}-\\frac{2 x}{x^2+2} \\text { [Chain Rule }\\right] \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{x}-\\frac{2 x}{x^2+2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\left(x^2+2\\right)-2 x^2}{x\\left(x^2+2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2-x^2}{x\\left(x^2+2\\right)} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 23:44:01',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(370,6,85,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the derivative of \\(\\log _2 x\\)?</p>','<p><strong>First changing bases to make it better to differentiate using log laws:</strong> $$ \\log _2 x=\\frac{\\ln x}{\\ln 2} $$ <strong>Then using the derivative for logarithms \\((\\ln x)^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{x}\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(\\log _2 x\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\left(\\frac{1}{\\ln 2} \\cdot \\ln x\\right)^{\\prime} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\ln 2} \\cdot \\frac{1}{x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{x \\ln 2} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 23:48:21',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(371,6,85,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>If \\(y=3 \\log _5 x\\), then \\(\\frac{d y}{d x}\\) will equal:</p>','<p><strong>First changing bases to make it better to differentiate using log laws:</strong> $$ 3 \\log _5 x=3 \\frac{\\ln x}{\\ln 5} $$ <strong>Then using the derivative for logarithms \\((\\ln x)^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{x}\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(3 \\log _5 x\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\left(\\frac{3}{\\ln 5} \\cdot \\ln x\\right)^{\\prime} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3}{\\ln 5} \\cdot \\frac{1}{x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3}{x \\ln 5} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 23:48:21',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(372,6,85,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the gradient of the normal to \\(y=\\log _3 x\\) at the point \\((9,2)\\)?</p>','<p>$$ y=\\log _3 x $$ <strong>Converting in terms of \\(\\ln x\\) using change of base law:</strong> $$ y=\\frac{\\ln x}{\\ln 3} $$ Since \\((\\ln x)^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{x}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\ln 3} \\times \\frac{1}{x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{x \\ln 3} \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>When \\(x=9\\) for \\(y^{\\prime}\\), the gradient of the tangent will be:</strong> $$ m_t=\\frac{1}{9 \\ln 3} $$ Since the gradient of a normal is the negative reciprocal of the tangent: $$ \\begin{aligned} m_n &amp; =-\\frac{1}{m_t} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{1}{\\frac{1}{9 \\ln 3}} \\\\ &amp; =-9 \\ln 3 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-23 23:48:21',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(373,6,87,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the derivative of \\(y=\\cos 2 x\\)?</p>','<p>Recall that \\((\\cos u)^{\\prime}=-\\sin u\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; y=\\cos 2 x \\\\ &amp; y^{\\prime}=(2 x)^{\\prime} \\times-\\sin 2 x \\text { [chain rule] } \\\\ &amp; \\quad=-2 \\sin 2 x \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 00:16:00',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(374,6,87,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>If \\(y=\\sin \\left(x^2+1\\right)\\), then \\(\\frac{d y}{d x}\\) will be equal to:</p>','<p>Recall that \\((\\sin u)^{\\prime}=\\cos u:\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; y=\\sin \\left(x^2+1\\right) \\\\ &amp; y^{\\prime}=\\left(x^2+1\\right) \\times \\cos \\left(x^2+1\\right)[\\text {chain rule}] \\\\ &amp; \\quad=2 x \\cos \\left(x^2+1\\right) \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 00:16:00',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(375,6,87,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>What is the derivative of \\(\\sin (\\ln x)\\), where \\(x&gt;0\\)?</p>','<p>Considering that \\((\\ln x)^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{x}\\) and \\((\\sin x)^{\\prime}=\\cos x\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} (\\sin (\\ln x))^{\\prime} &amp; =(\\ln x)^{\\prime} \\cos (\\ln x) \\ [\\text {Chain rule}] \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{x} \\cos (\\ln x) \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 00:16:00',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(376,6,87,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the derivative of \\(f(x)=2 \\tan 3 x\\)?</p>','<p>Recall that \\((\\tan u)^{\\prime}=\\sec ^2 u\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} f(x) &amp; =2 \\tan 3 x \\\\ f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =(3 x)^{\\prime} \\cdot 2 \\sec ^2 3 x \\text { [Chain rule] } \\\\ &amp; =3 \\cdot 2 \\sec ^2 3 x \\\\ &amp; =6 \\sec ^2 3 x \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 00:16:00',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(377,6,87,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Find the derivative expression for \\(y=x \\cos x\\)</p>','<p>Recall the product rule \\((u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; y=x \\cos x \\\\ \\therefore y^{\\prime}= &amp; (x)^{\\prime} \\cos x+(\\cos x)^{\\prime} x \\\\ = &amp; \\cos x-x \\sin x \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 00:16:00',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(378,6,87,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Find the equation of the tangent to the curve \\(y=\\sin x\\) at \\(x=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\).</p>','<p><strong>For tangent questions, we differentiate first:</strong> $$ y^{\\prime}=\\cos x $$ When \\(x=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\), the gradient of the tangent is: $$ m=\\cos \\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{1}{2} $$ <strong>When \\(x=\\frac{\\pi}{3}, y=\\sin \\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\)</strong></p><p>Finally using the point - gradient formula to find the equation of the tangent: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; y-y_1=m\\left(x-x_1\\right) \\\\ &amp; y-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}=\\frac{1}{2}\\left(x-\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\right) \\\\ &amp; y-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}=\\frac{x}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore y=\\frac{x}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{6}+\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 01:02:33',0,1,NULL,180,'hard','subtopic'),(379,6,87,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Show that \\((\\cot x)^{\\prime}=-\\operatorname{cosec}^2 x\\).</p>','<p>$$ (\\cot x)^{\\prime}=\\left(\\frac{\\cos x}{\\sin x}\\right)^{\\prime} $$ Considering quotient rule where \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(\\frac{\\cos x}{\\sin x}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{(\\cos x)^{\\prime} \\sin x-(\\sin x)^{\\prime} \\cos x}{\\sin ^2 x} \\\\ = &amp; \\frac{-\\sin x \\times \\sin x-\\cos x \\times \\cos x}{\\sin ^2 x} \\\\ = &amp; \\frac{-\\sin ^2 x-\\cos ^2 x}{\\sin ^2 x} \\\\ = &amp; \\frac{-1}{\\sin ^2 x}\\left[\\because \\sin ^2 x+\\cos ^2 x=1\\right] \\\\ = &amp; -\\operatorname{cosec}^2 x \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\text { LHS }=\\text { RHS } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 01:02:33',0,1,NULL,180,'hard','subtopic'),(380,6,87,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Differentiate \\(\\frac{\\cos 4 x}{x}\\)</p>','<p>Using quotient rule \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v \\prime u}{v^2}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\left(\\frac{\\cos 4 x}{x}\\right)^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{(\\cos 4 x)^{\\prime} x-x^{\\prime} \\cos 4 x}{x^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{-4 x \\sin 4 x-\\cos 4 x}{x^2} \\text { [Chain Rule] } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 01:02:33',0,1,NULL,180,'hard','subtopic'),(381,6,88,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>A farmer illegally sprayed a large amount of chemical pesticide on his land. The concentration of the chemical in the soil was initially measured to be \\(6 \\mathrm{~kg} / \\mathrm{ha}\\). One month later, it was measured to be \\(2.8 \\mathrm{~kg} / \\mathrm{ha}\\).<br><br>It is known that the concentration, \\(C\\), of the chemical in \\(\\mathrm{kg} /\\) ha is given by the formula \\(C=C_0 e^{-k t}\\), where \\(t\\) is the time in months after the chemical pesticide was initially sprayed, and \\(C_0\\) is a constant.</p><p>i. Find the values of \\(C_0\\) and \\(k\\)&nbsp;</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. The soil is said to be no longer toxic when the concentration of chemicals in the soil falls below \\(0.1 \\mathrm{~kg} / \\mathrm{ha}\\). How many months would it take for the soil on the farmer\'s land to be no longer toxic?</p><p>[2 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. We know that initially, \\(t=0\\) and \\(C=6\\)</strong> $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 6=C_0 e^{-k \\times 0} \\\\ =C_0 \\times 1 \\\\ \\therefore C_0=6 \\end{gathered} $$ Moreover, it is also known that when \\(t=1, C=2.8\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore 2.8 &amp; =6 \\times e^{-k \\times 1} \\\\ &amp; =6 e^{-k} \\\\ \\frac{2.8}{6} &amp; =\\frac{1}{e^k} \\\\ \\frac{30}{14} &amp; =e^k \\\\ \\therefore k &amp; =\\ln \\frac{30}{14} \\\\ &amp; =\\ln \\frac{15}{7} \\end{aligned} $$ <strong>Note that answers should be given in exact value (otherwise 1 mark will be deducted)</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. Letting \\(C \\leq 0.1\\):</strong> $$ \\therefore C=6 e^{-k t} \\leq 0.1 $$ Where \\(k=\\ln \\left(\\frac{30}{14}\\right)\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; e^{-k t} \\leq \\frac{1}{60} \\\\ &amp; -k t \\leq \\ln \\frac{1}{60} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t \\geq-\\frac{1}{k} \\ln \\left(\\frac{1}{60}\\right) \\\\ &amp; \\geq 5.37 \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the farmer will need to wait 6 months for the soil to no longer be toxic</p>','2024-01-24 03:11:45',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(382,6,88,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>The effectiveness of an antibiotic drug is determined by its ability to reduce the number of bacteria in a culture over time. The bacterial culture is reduced according to the model \\(N=N_0 e^{-k t}\\) where \\(N\\) is the number of bacteria left, and $t$ is the time since the antibiotic was administered in seconds.<br><br>An antibiotic is tested in a culture initially with \\(1500\\) bacteria, which reduces to \\(300\\) within \\(8\\) minutes. How many bacteria are left in the culture after \\(4\\) minutes? Give your answer to the nearest whole number.</p>','<p>Since the culture initially has \\(1500\\) bacteria, this means that when \\(t=0, N=1500\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 1500=N_0 e^0 \\\\ N_0=1500 \\end{gathered} $$ Moreover, when \\(t=4 \\times 60=240, N=300\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 300=1500 e^{-240 k} \\\\ \\frac{1}{5}=e^{-240 k} \\\\ -240 k=\\ln \\frac{1}{5} \\\\ \\therefore k=-\\frac{1}{240} \\ln \\frac{1}{5} \\\\ =\\frac{1}{240} \\ln 5 \\end{gathered} $$ <strong>Note: This is a common trick! Be careful what \\(t\\) is defined as. Therefore, to find how many bacteria are left after \\(4\\) minutes, let \\(t=4\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} N &amp; =1500 e^{-4 \\times \\frac{1}{240} \\ln 5} \\\\ &amp; =1500 e^{-\\frac{1}{60} \\ln 5} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 1460 \\text { (nearest whole number) } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 03:32:53',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(383,6,88,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u></p><p>The number of shrimps, \\(N\\), in my shrimp farm at time \\(t\\) weeks, is given by the formula \\(N=N_0 e^{k t}\\), where \\(N_0\\) is a constant. Initially, there were \\(1000\\) shrimp in the hatchery, and after \\(4\\) weeks there were \\(3500\\) shrimp in the farm.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Calculate the value of \\(k\\) and \\(N_0\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find at what rate (to the nearest whole number) the shrimp population is growing in my farm after the \\(6^{\\text {th }}\\) week<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. It is given that there were initially \\(1000\\) shrimp. Hence, when \\(t=0, N=1000\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore 1000 &amp; =N_0 e^{k \\times 0} \\\\ &amp; =N_0 \\times 1 \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, \\(N_0=1000\\) Moreover, when \\(t=4, N=3500\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 3500=1000 e^{4 k} \\\\ \\frac{3500}{1000}=e^{4 k} \\\\ 4 k=\\ln \\frac{7}{2} \\\\ \\therefore k=\\frac{1}{4} \\ln \\frac{7}{2} \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. Since this question is dealing with rates, we must differentiate \\(N=1000 e^{k t}\\), where \\(k=\\frac{1}{4} \\ln \\frac{7}{2}\\)</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\frac{d N}{d t} &amp; =1000 \\times k e^{k t} \\\\ &amp; =1000 k e^{k t} \\end{aligned} $$ When \\(t=6\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d N}{d t} &amp; =1000 k e^{6 k} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 2051 \\text { shrimp/month (nearest who number) } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 03:36:43',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(384,6,88,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>A drug is metabolised by the body, meaning its amount in milligrams is reduced over a period of time. The drug is reduced to the model \\(N=N_0 e^{-k t}\\) where \\(N\\) is the number of milligrams and \\(t\\) is the time since the drug was first administered in hours.<br><br>This drug is given with an initial dosage of \\(800 \\mathrm{mg}\\), which reduces to \\(200 \\mathrm{mg}\\) after \\(2\\) hours. How much bacteria will be left after \\(4\\) hours?</p>','<p><strong>Unpacking the information first, when \\(t=0, N=800\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; 800=N_0 e^0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore N_0=800 \\end{gathered} $$ <strong>When \\(t=2, N=200\\)</strong>: $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; 200=800 e^{-2 k}\\left[\\because N_0=800\\right] \\\\ &amp; \\frac{1}{4}=e^{-2 k} \\\\ &amp; -2 k=\\ln \\frac{1}{4} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore k=-\\frac{1}{2} \\ln \\frac{1}{4} \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, when \\(t=4\\), finding the value of \\(N\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} N &amp; =800 e^{-4 \\times-\\frac{1}{2} \\ln \\frac{1}{4}} \\\\ &amp; =800 e^{2 \\ln \\frac{1}{4}} \\\\ &amp; =800 e^{\\ln \\left(\\frac{1}{4}\\right)^2} \\\\ &amp; =800 e^{\\ln \\frac{1}{16}} \\\\ &amp; =800 \\times \\frac{1}{16} \\\\ &amp; =50 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the amount left is \\(50 \\mathrm{mg}\\)</p>','2024-01-24 03:43:32',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(385,6,88,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>The number \\(N\\) of bacteria in a mouldy piece of cheese at time \\(t\\) hours is given by the equation: $$ N=28 e^{k t} $$After \\(8\\) hours, the number of bacteria present is \\(42\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i.&nbsp; Find the exact value of \\(k\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Determine the exact number of bacteria after \\(48\\) hours<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. At what rate is the number of bacteria increasing after \\(48\\) hours? Give your answer to the nearest whole number&nbsp;<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p>i. When \\(t=8, N=42\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; 42=28 e^{8 k} \\\\ &amp; \\frac{42}{28}=e^{8 k} \\\\ &amp; \\frac{3}{2}=e^{8 k} \\\\ &amp; 8 k=\\ln \\frac{3}{2} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore k=\\frac{1}{8} \\ln \\frac{3}{2} \\end{gathered} $$ii. When \\(t=48\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} N &amp; =28 e^{48 k}, \\text { where } k=\\frac{1}{8} \\ln \\frac{3}{2} \\\\ &amp; =28 e^{48 \\times \\frac{1}{8} \\ln \\frac{3}{2}} \\\\ &amp; =28 e^{6 \\ln \\frac{3}{2}} \\\\ &amp; =28 e^{\\ln \\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\right)^6} \\\\ &amp; =28\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\right)^6 \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{5103}{16} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>iii. When looking at rates, first differentiate: $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; N=28 e^{k t}, \\text { where } k=\\frac{1}{8} \\ln \\frac{3}{2} \\\\ &amp; \\frac{d N}{d t}=28 \\times k e^{k t} \\text { [Chain Rule] } \\\\ &amp; =28 k e^{k t} \\end{gathered} $$ When \\(t=48\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d N}{d t} &amp; =28 k e^{48 k} \\\\ &amp; =28 \\times \\frac{1}{8} \\ln \\frac{3}{2} \\times e^{48 \\times \\frac{1}{8} \\ln \\frac{3}{2}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{7}{2} \\ln \\frac{3}{2} e^{6 \\ln \\frac{3}{2}} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 16 \\text { bacteria/hour } \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 03:48:37',0,1,5,540,'medium','subtopic'),(386,6,88,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [4 marks total]</u><br>A factory produces phones, with its annual production of \\(M\\) phones at time \\(t\\) years given by: $$ M=A e^{k t}, \\text { where } A \\text { is a constant } $$ Initially, the factory production was \\(4000\\) phones per annum. Five years later, this production had increased to \\(5500\\) phones per annum.<br>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Find the values of \\(A\\) and \\(k\\), giving your answers in exact values&nbsp;<br>[2 marks]<br>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. How many years will it take for the production to triple its original output? Give your answer to the nearest whole number.<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. When \\(t=0, M=4000\\)</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 4000=A e^0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore A=4000 \\end{aligned} $$ When \\(t=5, M=5500\\) $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; 5500=4000 e^{5 k} \\\\ &amp; \\frac{11}{8}=e^{5 k} \\\\ &amp; 5 k=\\ln \\frac{11}{8} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore k=\\frac{1}{5} \\ln \\frac{11}{8} \\end{gathered} $$</p><p><br><strong>ii. The original output was \\(4000\\), so triple of that would be \\(12000\\)</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, letting \\(M=12000\\) and solving for \\(t\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; 12000=4000 e^{k t}, \\text { where } k=\\frac{1}{5} \\ln \\frac{11}{8} \\\\ &amp; 3=e^{k t} \\\\ &amp; k t=\\ln 3 \\end{gathered} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} t &amp; =\\frac{1}{k} \\ln 3 \\\\ t &amp; =\\frac{1}{\\frac{1}{5} \\ln \\frac{11}{8}}(\\ln 3) \\\\ \\therefore t &amp; \\approx 17[\\text { nearest whole number }] \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, it takes 17 years to triple the annual output</p>','2024-01-24 03:55:07',0,1,4,420,'medium','subtopic'),(387,6,90,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f^{\\prime}(x)\\) is shown below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:34.53%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:850/689;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/76407664e6eed201dea4677c6ad02427.jpeg\" width=\"850\" height=\"689\"></figure><p>The values of \\(x\\) for which \\(f(x)\\) is decreasing are:</p>','<p>Since this is the graph of \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\), when \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&lt;0, f(x)\\) is decreasing.</p><p>&nbsp;<br>Hence, observing the graph for when the line is decreasing, \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&lt;0\\) when: $$ x&lt;-4 $$</p>','2024-01-24 21:01:07',0,1,1,60,'medium','subtopic'),(388,6,90,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of the function \\(y=f(x)\\)is known to have a maximum turning point at the point \\(P(3,5)\\). Therefore, which of the following will be true for the graph of \\(y=-f(3 x)\\)?</p>','<p>The graph of \\(y=-f(3 x)\\) is the graph of \\(f(x)\\) except vertically dilated by a factor of \\(-1\\) and then horizontally dilated by factor \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Note that although originally a maximum turning point, since a vertical dilation by a factor of \\(-1\\) is the same as reflecting the graph about the \\(x\\) - axis, this point now becomes a minimum turning point!</p>','2024-01-24 21:23:15',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(389,6,90,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given the following sign table for \\(y=x^3-4 x^2+4 x+5\\), which of the following is correct?</p><p>\\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline x &amp; 0 &amp; \\frac{2}{3} &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\\\ \\hline y^{\\prime} &amp; 4 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 &amp; 7 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array}</p>','<p>Recalling that when \\(y^{\\prime}&gt;0\\), the graph is increasing and when \\(y^{\\prime}&lt;0\\), the graph is decreasing, hence:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:42.51%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:847/176;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/6e94939bf0f033f028e754ab53a1e62b.png\" width=\"847\" height=\"176\"></figure><p>We can therefore see that when \\(x=2\\), a minimum turning point occurs!</p>','2024-01-24 21:23:15',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(390,6,90,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following are the \\(x\\) - coordinates of the stationary points for the function \\(f(x)=\\frac{x^3}{3}-x^2-8 x+5\\)?</p>','<p><strong>To find stationary points, first differentiate:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =3 \\cdot \\frac{x^2}{3}-2 x-8 \\\\ &amp; =x^2-2 x-8 \\end{aligned} $$ Stationary points occur when \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=0\\). Hence, factorising \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\) to solve for \\(x\\): $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=(x-4)(x+2) $$ \\(\\therefore x=4\\) OR \\(x=-2\\) are stationary points for \\(f(x)\\)</p>','2024-01-24 21:37:22',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(391,6,90,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [6 marks total]</u></p><p>A function is given by \\(f(x)=4 x^4-9 x^2\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i.&nbsp; &nbsp;Show that the \\(x\\)-intercepts are \\(0\\), \\(\\frac{3}{2}\\) and \\(-\\frac{3}{2}\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii.&nbsp; Prove that \\(f(x)\\) is an even function<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Prove that \\(x=\\frac{3}{2 \\sqrt{2}}\\) is a stationary point<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. Given that \\(\\left(\\frac{3}{2 \\sqrt{2}},-\\frac{81}{16}\\right)\\) is a minimum turning point, explain in words why \\(\\left(-\\frac{3}{2 \\sqrt{2}},-\\frac{81}{16}\\right)\\) is also a minimum turning point<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p><strong>i. Letting \\(f(x)=0\\):</strong> $$ 0=4 x^4-9 x^2 $$ Factorising: $$ x^2\\left(4 x^2-9\\right)=0 $$ Considering the difference of squares: $$ \\begin{gathered} x^2(2 x+3)(2 x-3)=0 \\\\ \\therefore x=0, \\frac{3}{2} \\text { OR }-\\frac{3}{2} \\end{gathered} $$ <strong>ii. For a function \\(f(x)\\) to be even, \\(f(-x)=f(x)\\) Hence:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} f(-x) &amp; =4(-x)^4-9(-x)^2 \\\\ &amp; =4 x^4-9 x^2 \\\\ &amp; =f(x) \\\\ \\therefore &amp; f(-x)=f(x) \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, \\(f(x)\\) is even</p><p><strong>iii. Differentiating \\(f(x)\\):</strong><br>$$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =4 \\times 4 x^3-9 \\times 2 x \\\\ &amp; =16 x^3-18 x \\\\ &amp; =2 x\\left(8 x^2-9\\right) \\end{aligned} $$ To find the \\(x\\) - coordinate of the stationary point, let \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=0\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} 2 x\\left(8 x^2-9\\right)=0 \\\\ \\therefore x=0 \\text { OR } 8 x^2=9 \\\\ x^2=\\frac{9}{8} \\\\ x=\\pm \\sqrt{\\frac{9}{8}} \\\\ =\\pm \\frac{3}{2 \\sqrt{2}} \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, \\(x=\\frac{3}{2 \\sqrt{2}}\\) is a stationary point<br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>iv. Since the function \\(f(x)\\) is even, then that means graphically, the function is reflected about the \\(y\\)-axis.</strong><br><br>Hence, any turning points on the right side of the \\(y\\)-axis will also be present on the left side of the \\(y\\) - axis.<br><br>Therefore, because \\(-\\frac{3}{2 \\sqrt{2}}\\) is equal in magnitude to \\(\\frac{3}{2 \\sqrt{2}}\\), then \\(\\left(-\\frac{3}{2 \\sqrt{2}},-\\frac{81}{16}\\right)\\) is also a minimum turning point</p>','2024-01-24 21:45:20',0,1,6,600,'medium','subtopic'),(392,6,90,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks]</u></p><p>Find the nature and coordinates of the stationary point for the curve \\(y=\\frac{\\ln x}{x^4}\\)</p>','<p>First differentiating \\(y\\) using the quotient rule \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime} &amp; =\\frac{(\\ln x)^{\\prime} x^4-\\left(x^4\\right)^{\\prime} \\ln x}{\\left(x^4\\right)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\frac{1}{x} \\times x^4-4 x^3 \\ln x}{x^8} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^3-4 x^3 \\ln x}{x^8} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^3(1-4 \\ln x)}{x^8} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1-4 \\ln x}{x^5} \\end{aligned} $$ To find the \\(x\\) - coordinate of the stationary point, let \\(y^{\\prime}=0\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} y^{\\prime}=\\frac{1-4 \\ln x}{x^5}=0 \\\\ \\therefore 1-4 \\ln x=0 \\\\ 1=4 \\ln x \\end{gathered} $$$$ \\begin{gathered} \\ln x=\\frac{1}{4} \\\\ \\therefore x=e^{\\frac{1}{4}} \\end{gathered} $$ When \\(x=e^{\\frac{1}{4}}, y=\\frac{\\ln e^{\\frac{1}{4}}}{\\left(e^{0.25}\\right)^4}=\\frac{\\frac{1}{4}}{e}=\\frac{1}{4 e}\\). Hence, its coordinate is \\(\\left(e^{\\frac{1}{4}}, \\frac{1}{4 e}\\right)\\) Finally, to determine its nature we draw the sign table:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:897/161;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/63ff4817cb7d319be23122ed44d0b6dc.png\" width=\"897\" height=\"161\"></figure><p>\\(\\therefore\\) Maximum Turning Point at&nbsp;\\(\\left(e^{\\frac{1}{4}}, \\frac{1}{4 e}\\right)\\)</p>','2024-01-24 21:54:03',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(393,6,91,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) is shown below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:41.11%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1179/632;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/79707837fb557732cbbb72b3e460290b.png\" width=\"1179\" height=\"632\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Which statement below is correct?</p>','<p><strong>The curve is seen to be concave up, so:</strong> $$ f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)&gt;0 $$ Moreover, the curve is also always increasing, so: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0 $$</p>','2024-01-24 21:59:39',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(394,6,91,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>It is known that for a particular function \\(y=f(x)\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; f(-1)=-4 \\\\ &amp; f^{\\prime}(-1)=0 \\\\ &amp; f^{\\prime \\prime}(-1)=-2 \\end{aligned} $$ Which statement below is true regarding the graph of \\(y=f(x)\\)?</p>','<p>Since \\(f^{\\prime}(-1)=0\\), this means that there is a stationary point when \\(x=-1\\).&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Moreover, since and \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(-1)&lt;0\\) then that means the stationary point is concave down.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, this would be a maximum turning point at the coordinates \\((-1,-4)\\)</p>','2024-01-24 21:59:39',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(395,6,91,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>For what values of \\(x\\) is the curve \\(g(x)=3 x^3+2 x^2\\) concave up?</p>','<p>To check for concavity, considering the double derivative \\(g^{\\prime \\prime}(x)\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; g^{\\prime}(x)=9 x^2+4 x \\\\ &amp; g^{\\prime \\prime}(x)=18 x+4 \\end{aligned} $$ Curve is concave up when \\(g^{\\prime \\prime}(x)&gt;0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 18 x+4&gt;0 \\\\ &amp; 18 x&gt;-4 \\\\ &amp; x&gt;-\\frac{4}{18} \\\\ &amp; x&gt;-\\frac{2}{9} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 21:59:40',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(396,6,91,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The diagram below shows a sketch of the gradient function of the curve \\(y=f(x)\\).</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:48.64%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1583/681;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ae05687b691b94be170564599b14cf51.png\" width=\"1583\" height=\"681\"></figure><p>Which of the following is a true statement? The curve \\(y=f(x)\\) has:</p>','<p><strong>Note that this is the graph for \\(y=f^{\\prime}(x)\\). When \\(x=1, f^{\\prime}(1)=0\\), meaning that it is a stationary point.</strong><br><br>Moreover, since \\(x=1\\) is one of the stationary points for \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\), then \\(\\left[f^{\\prime}(x)\\right]^{\\prime}=f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)=0\\) (the derivative of the derivative is the double derivative.)<br><br>Hence, \\(x=1\\) is also a point of inflection. Thus, this is a horizontal point of inflection.</p>','2024-01-24 21:59:40',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(397,6,91,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The amount, \\(A\\) of medicine in the body \\(t\\) hours after it is administered is given by: $$ A=6 t^2-t^3, \\text { for } 0 \\leq t \\leq 6 $$&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">When is the amount of medicine in the blood increasing most rapidly?</p>','<p><strong>Since we are looking for a rate of increase, differentiate first:</strong> $$ A^{\\prime}=12 t-3 t^2 $$ Then, sketching the first derivative graph \\(A^{\\prime}\\):</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:41.44%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1070/658;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/219b3aa6b72945738803f994614bb869.png\" width=\"1070\" height=\"658\"></figure><p><strong>\\(A^{\\prime}\\) is largest when \\(t=2\\), meaning that the rate of increase of the medicine is largest at this time.&nbsp;</strong><br><br>Alternatively, we can also figure out the answer through finding when \\(A^{\\prime \\prime}=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; A^{\\prime \\prime}=12-6 t=0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=2 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-24 21:59:40',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(398,6,92,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>The graph of \\(y=f(x)\\) is shown below. For which interval is \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&lt;0\\)?</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:43.74%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1360/715;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/c198da88153a603bc5dfec7ca034110e.png\" width=\"1360\" height=\"715\"></figure>','<p>Since we are looking for when \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&lt;0\\), this is when the graph is decreasing.&nbsp;</p><p>Notice that the graph is decreasing when \\(-2&lt;x&lt;4\\).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, in interval notation this may be expressed as: $$ (-2, -4)$$</p>','2024-01-24 22:35:49',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(399,6,92,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>The following graph shows the function \\(y=f(x)\\) with a horizontal asymptote at \\(y=1:\\)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:552/271;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/262c77849942bc7db96956273766f9e7.png\" width=\"552\" height=\"271\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Hence, sketch the graph of \\(y=f^{\\prime}(x)\\)</p>','<p>There is a visible stationary point at \\(x=0\\), and the graph for \\(f(x)\\) is becoming increasing flat as \\(x \\rightarrow \\infty\\) and \\(x \\rightarrow-\\infty\\), which means that \\(f^{\\prime}(x) \\rightarrow 0\\) as \\(x \\rightarrow \\infty\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Moreover, on the left half of the graph \\(f(x)\\) is increasing so \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0\\) and on the right half \\(f(x)\\) is decreasing so \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&lt;0\\) Hence, graphically \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\) looks like:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:25.5%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:475/429;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/3b4809a3fb294920de15436be43b1006.png\" width=\"475\" height=\"429\"></figure>','2024-01-24 22:39:55',0,1,2,180,'medium','subtopic'),(400,6,92,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [6 marks total]</u></p><p>Let \\(f(x)=-5 x e^{-x}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i.&nbsp; Find and determine the nature of any stationary points of \\(f(x)\\)&nbsp;</p><p>[3 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Given that there is a point of inflection at \\(x=2\\), sketch the graph of \\(y=f(x)\\), showing any stationary points, the point of inflection, and any intercepts on the coordinate axes</p><p>[3 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. To find stationary points, first differentiate \\(f(x)=-5 x e^{-x}\\)</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =(-5 x)^{\\prime} e^{-x}+-5 x\\left(e^{-x}\\right)^{\\prime}\\ &nbsp;[\\text {Product Rule}] \\\\ &amp; =-5 e^{-x}-5 x\\left(-e^{-x}\\right)\\ [\\text {Chain Rule}] \\\\ &amp; =-5 e^{-x}+5 x e^{-x} \\\\ &amp; =5 e^{-x}(x-1) \\end{aligned} $$ Letting \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=0\\) and solving for \\(x\\) for stationary points: $$ \\begin{gathered} f^{\\prime}(x)=5 e^{-x}(x-1)=0 \\\\ \\therefore x=1 \\text { ONLY }\\left[\\because e^{-x} \\neq 0\\right] \\end{gathered} $$ Finding the coordinates of stationary points: When \\(x=1, y=-5(1) e^{-1}=-\\frac{5}{e}\\). Coordinate is hence \\(\\left(1,-\\frac{5}{e}\\right)\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Testing its nature by using a sign table:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:34.1%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:857/142;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/1e4463c4378b2e323d4fc60dd70de9fb.png\" width=\"857\" height=\"142\"></figure><p><strong>Hence, it is a minimum turning point at \\(\\left(1,-\\frac{5}{e}\\right)\\)</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. For the point of inflection:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>When \\(x=2, y=-5(2) e^{-2}=-\\frac{10}{e^2}\\)&nbsp;</p><p>The coordinate is hence \\(\\left(2,-\\frac{10}{e^2}\\right)\\)&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Therefore, sketching the graph:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:51.72%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1266/585;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9a4c0e36dc18f118fc3c3bdd47949b40.png\" width=\"1266\" height=\"585\"></figure>','2024-01-25 01:24:33',0,1,6,600,'medium','subtopic'),(401,6,92,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [8 marks total]</u></p><p>Consider the function \\(y=3 x e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i.&nbsp; &nbsp;Find the coordinates of any stationary points and determine their nature<br>[3 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii.&nbsp; Find coordinates of any points of inflection<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. For what values of \\(x\\) is the curve concave down?&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. Draw a sketch of the curve, showing all important points<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. To find stationary points first differentiate:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} y &amp; =3 x e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\\\ y^{\\prime} &amp; \\left.=3(x)^{\\prime} e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+3 x\\left(e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\right)^{\\prime} \\text { [Product Rule }\\right] \\\\ &amp; =3 e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+3 x \\times \\frac{1}{3} e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\ [\\text { Chain Rule }] \\\\ &amp; =3 e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+x e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\end{aligned} $$ Letting \\(y^{\\prime}=0\\) and solving for \\(x\\) for stationary points: &nbsp;\\begin{gathered} y^{\\prime}=3 e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+x e^{\\frac{x}{3}}=0 \\\\ e^{\\frac{x}{3}}(3+x)=0 \\\\ \\therefore x=-3 \\end{gathered}</p><p>Finding the coordinates of stationary points:</p><p>When \\(x=-3, y=3(-3) e^{-\\frac{3}{3}}=-\\frac{9}{e}\\). The coordinate is hence \\(\\left(-3,-\\frac{9}{e}\\right)\\)</p><p>Testing its nature by using a sign table:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:874/179;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/7db564d15edefa8ab1405d4d9e8f2461.png\" width=\"874\" height=\"179\"></figure><p>Hence, minimum turning point at \\(\\left(-3,-\\frac{9}{e}\\right)\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. \\(\\quad y^{\\prime}=3 e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+x e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\)</strong></p><p>Considering the second derivative: $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime \\prime} &amp; =3 \\times \\frac{1}{3} e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+(x)^{\\prime} e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+x\\left(e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\right)^{\\prime} \\text { [Product Rule ] } \\\\ &amp; =e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+x \\times \\frac{1}{3} e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\\\ &amp; =2 e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+\\frac{x}{3} e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\end{aligned} $$ Letting \\(y^{\\prime \\prime}=0\\) and solving for \\(x\\): $$ \\begin{gathered} 2 e^{\\frac{x}{3}}+\\frac{x}{3} e^{\\frac{x}{3}}=0 \\\\ e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\left(2+\\frac{x}{3}\\right)=0 \\\\ \\frac{x}{3}=-2 \\\\ \\therefore x=-6 \\end{gathered} $$ When \\(x=-6, y=3(-6) e^{\\frac{-6}{3}}=-18 e^{-2}=-\\frac{18}{e^2}\\)</p><p>Drawing a sign table:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:41.77%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:848/215;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/b2747be3e342c33f4a40674c9869e018.png\" width=\"848\" height=\"215\"></figure><p>Hence, the point of inflection is at \\(\\left(-6,-\\frac{18}{e^2}\\right)\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>iii. In order to be concave down, \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)&lt;0\\). Hence, \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)&lt;0\\) when \\(x&lt;-6\\)</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>iv. Sketching the graph now:</strong></p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:58.13%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1379/890;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/6543fd506bb5b7ad4e17b8120fb63f77.png\" width=\"1379\" height=\"890\"></figure>','2024-01-25 01:35:05',0,1,8,840,'medium','subtopic'),(402,6,92,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [14 marks total]</u></p><p>Consider the function \\(f(x)=(x-3)(x+1)^3\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Find the intercepts of \\(y=f(x)\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Show that \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=4(x+1)^2(x-2)\\) and that \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)=12(x+1)(x-1)\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Find the coordinates of the stationary points of \\(y=f(x)\\) and hence determine their nature<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iv. Find the coordinates of any points of inflection of \\(y=f(x)\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>v. Sketch the graph of \\(y=f(x)\\), showing all features above<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>vi. State, in the correct order, the transformation needed to obtain the graph of: $$ y=f\\left(2\\left(x+\\frac{1}{4}\\right)\\right) $$<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>vii. Hence, on the same graph as part \\(\\mathrm{v}\\), sketch the graph of \\(y=f\\left(2\\left(x+\\frac{1}{4}\\right)\\right)\\), showing coordinates of \\(x\\) - intercepts, stationary points and inflection points<br>[2 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. First finding the \\(y\\) - intercept by letting \\(x=0\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} y &amp; =(0-3)(0+1)^3 \\\\ &amp; =-3 \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, \\(y\\) - intercept at \\((0,-3)\\) Then, finding the \\(x\\) - intercept by letting \\(y=0\\) : $$ \\begin{gathered} 0=(x-3)(x+1)^3 \\\\ \\quad \\therefore x=3 \\text { OR }-1 \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, \\(x\\) - intercept at \\((3,0)\\) and \\((-1,0)\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. Differentiating \\(f(x)\\) by using the product rule \\((u v)^{\\prime}=u^{\\prime} v+v^{\\prime} u\\)</strong>: $$ \\begin{aligned} f(x) &amp; =(x-3)(x+1)^3 \\\\ f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =(x-3)^{\\prime}(x+1)^3+\\left((x+1)^3\\right)^{\\prime}(x-3)[\\text {Product rule}] \\\\ &amp; =(x+1)^3+3(x+1)^2(x-3) \\\\ &amp; =(x+1)^2[(x+1)+3(x-3)] \\\\ &amp; =(x+1)^2[x+1+3 x-9] \\\\ &amp; =(x+1)^2(4 x-8) \\\\ &amp; =4(x+1)^2(x-2) \\end{aligned} $$ Differentiating \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\) now using the product rule again: $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =4(x+1)^2(x-2) \\\\ f^{\\prime \\prime}(x) &amp; =4(2)(x+1)(x-2)+4(1)(x+1)^2[\\text {Product Rule}] \\\\ &amp; =(x+1)(8(x-2)+4(x+1)) \\\\ &amp; =(x+1)(8 x-16+4 x+4) \\\\ &amp; =(x+1)(12 x-12) \\\\ &amp; =12(x+1)(x-1) \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>iii. To find stationary points, let \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=0\\) and solve for \\(x\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{gathered} 4(x+1)^2(x-2)=0 \\\\ \\therefore x=-1 \\text { OR } 2 \\end{gathered} $$ When \\(x=-1, y=(-1-3)(-1+1)^3=0\\). Hence, coordinate is \\((-1,0)\\)&nbsp;<br>When \\(x=2, y=(2-3)(2+1)^3=-27\\). Hence, coordinate is \\((2,-27)\\)<br><br>Check for the nature of stationary point by using \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)\\) from part ii):&nbsp;<br>When \\(x=-1, f^{\\prime \\prime}(-1)=12(-1+1)(-1-1)=0\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Therefore, since \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)=0\\), the stationary point \\((-1,0)\\) is a horizontal point of inflection When \\(x=2, f^{\\prime \\prime}(2)=12(2+1)(2-1)=36\\).&nbsp;<br><br>Therefore, since \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)&gt;0\\), the stationary point \\((2,-27)\\) is a minimum turning point</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>iv. Points of inflection occur when \\(f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)=0\\), so solving for \\(x\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime \\prime}(x)= &amp; 12(x+1)(x-1)=0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x=-1 \\text { OR } 1 \\end{aligned} $$We already know that \\((-1,0)\\) is a horizontal point of inflection, so now testing if \\(x=1\\) is a point of inflection by testing change in concavity:</p><p>Checking for change of concavity using a sign table:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:870/213;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/76053267f4a09fc798c15c9bcbe3c160.png\" width=\"870\" height=\"213\"></figure><p>Hence, \\(x=1\\) is a point of inflection since change of concavity occurs.&nbsp;<br><br>When \\(x=1, y=(1-3)(1+1)^3=-16\\). Coordinate of POI is therefore \\((1,-16)\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>v. Sketching the graph of \\(f(x)\\):</strong></p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:52.77%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1379/890;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/37ec185e85435dce795a90a46490b161.png\" width=\"1379\" height=\"890\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>vi. Starting from \\(y=f(x)\\):</strong></p><p>First horizontally dilating by a factor of \\(\\frac{1}{2}, x \\rightarrow \\frac{x}{\\frac{1}{2}}=2 x\\) $$ \\therefore y=f(x) \\rightarrow f(2 x) $$ Next, shifting to the left by \\(\\frac{1}{4}\\) unit, \\(x \\rightarrow x+\\frac{1}{4}\\)$$ \\therefore y=f(2 x)=f\\left(2\\left(x+\\frac{1}{4}\\right)\\right) $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>vii. As per the previous description, for the new graph \\(y=f\\left(2\\left(x+\\frac{1}{4}\\right)\\right)\\):</strong>&nbsp;<br><br>Because of the horizontal dilation by factor \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\), all \\(x\\) - coordinates are multiplied by half.&nbsp;</p><p>Then, because of the shift left \\(\\frac{1}{4}\\) unit, all \\(x\\) - coordinates are subtracted by \\(\\frac{1}{4}\\)</p><p>For example, the original point \\((-1,0)\\) now becomes \\(\\left(-\\frac{3}{4} \\cdot 0\\right)\\)&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, sketching the graph:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:69.23%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:1379/890;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/40f4a0f045a66c284ccfb2fdb3575fc5.png\" width=\"1379\" height=\"890\"></figure>','2024-01-25 04:07:36',0,1,14,1440,'medium','subtopic'),(403,6,93,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [6 marks total]</u></p><p>A closed water tank is cylindrical in shape, with a circular base that has a radius of \\(r\\) metres and a height of \\(h\\) metres. It is known to hold \\(250 \\pi \\mathrm{mm}^3\\) of water. The material for both the flat circular top and base costs \\(\\$ 9\\) per square metre and the material for the curved surface costs \\(\\$ 12\\) per square metre.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i.&nbsp; &nbsp;Show that the height of the tank is \\(h=\\frac{250}{r^2}\\)</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii.&nbsp; Derive an expression for the cost of construction in terms of \\(r\\)</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>iii. Find the dimensions of the tank to the nearest \\(1\\) decimal point that minimises the cost of construction</p><p>[3 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. The volume of a cylinder is given as:</strong> $$ V=\\pi r^2 h $$ Since it is known \\(V=250 \\pi\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\therefore 250 \\pi=\\pi r^2 h \\\\ &amp; \\therefore h=\\frac{250}{r^2} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. Consider the surface area of a cylinder:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} S A &amp; =\\text { bottom }+\\text { top }+\\text { curved } \\\\ &amp; =\\pi r^2+\\pi r^2+2 \\pi r h \\\\ &amp; =2 \\pi r^2+2 \\pi r h \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the cost of construction will be: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Cost } &amp; =9 \\times 2 \\pi r^2+12 \\times 2 \\pi r h \\\\ &amp; =18 \\pi r^2+24 \\pi r h \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(h=\\frac{250}{r^2}\\) from part i): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Cost } &amp; =18 \\pi r^2+24 \\pi r\\left(\\frac{250}{r^2}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =18 \\pi r^2+\\frac{6000 \\pi}{r} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>iii. To find the minimum cost, differentiate the cost equation with respect to \\(r\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d C}{d r} &amp; =18 \\pi \\times 2 r+6000 \\pi(-1) r^{-2} \\\\ &amp; =36 \\pi r-\\frac{6000 \\pi}{r^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{36 \\pi r^3-6000 \\pi}{r^2} \\end{aligned} $$ Letting \\(\\frac{d C}{d r}=0\\) and solving for \\(r\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{36 \\pi r^3-6000 \\pi}{r^2}=0 \\\\ &amp; 36 \\pi r^3-6000 \\pi=0 \\\\ &amp; 36 \\pi r^3=6000 \\pi \\\\ &amp; r^3=\\frac{6000}{36} \\end{aligned} $$ Testing if this is a minimum point by double differentiating: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d^2 C}{d r^2} &amp; =36 \\pi-(6000 \\pi) \\times-2 r^{-3} \\\\ &amp; =36 \\pi+\\frac{12000 \\pi}{r^3} \\end{aligned} $$ Let \\(r^3=\\frac{6000}{36}\\):$$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d^2 C}{d r^2} &amp; =36 \\pi+\\frac{12000 \\pi}{\\left(\\frac{6000}{36}\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =36 \\pi+72 \\pi \\\\ &amp; =108 \\pi \\end{aligned} $$ \\(\\therefore\\) Since \\(\\frac{d^2 C}{d r^2}&gt;0, r^3=\\frac{6000}{36}\\) is a minimum point $$ \\therefore r=\\sqrt[3]{\\frac{6000}{36}} \\approx 5.5 m\\ [\\text {nearest } 1 \\text { d.p.}] $$ Since \\(h=\\frac{250}{r^2}\\): $$ \\therefore h=\\frac{250}{\\left(\\sqrt[3]{\\frac{6000}{36}}\\right)^2} \\approx 8.3 m\\ [\\text {nearest 1 d.p.] } $$</p>','2024-01-25 04:23:36',0,1,6,600,'medium','subtopic'),(404,6,93,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [6 marks total]</u></p><p>An enclosure in the shape of a right - angled triangle is to be made using \\(27 \\mathrm{~m}\\) of fencing, with the boundary of an existing paddock serving as one side of the triangle \\((h)\\), meaning no fencing is required. The area of the enclosure is given as \\(\\mathrm{Am}^2\\), with the side perpendicular to \\(h\\) being \\(x\\) metres long.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:328/169;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/380cf9daae29a844841749caeb556b3e.png\" width=\"328\" height=\"169\"></figure><p>i. Show that the area of the enclosure is given by \\(\\frac{3 x \\sqrt{81-6 x}}{2}\\)</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the value of \\(x\\) which will maximise the area</p><p>[4 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. Since the amount of fencing to be used is \\(27 \\mathrm{~m}\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; x+\\text { hypotenuse }=27 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\text { hypotenuse }=27-x \\end{aligned} $$ By Pythagoras theorem: $$ \\begin{aligned} h &amp; =\\sqrt{\\text { hypotenuse }{ }^2-x^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{(27-x)^2-x^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\sqrt{729-54 x+x^2-x^2} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; =\\sqrt{9(81-6 x)} \\\\ &amp; =3 \\sqrt{81-6 x} \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the area of the triangle will be: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area } &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times x \\times h \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x}{2} \\times 3 \\sqrt{81-6 x} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3 x \\sqrt{81-6 x}}{2} \\end{aligned} $$ As required.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. To find the maximum area, differentiate the area equation with respect to \\(x\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d A}{d x} &amp; =\\left(\\frac{3}{2} x \\sqrt{81-6 x}\\right)^{\\prime} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3}{2} \\sqrt{81-6 x}+(\\sqrt{81-6 x})^{\\prime} \\times \\frac{3}{2} x \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3}{2} \\sqrt{81-6 x}+\\frac{1}{2} \\times-6 \\times(81-6 x)^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\times \\frac{3}{2} x \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3}{2} \\sqrt{81-6 x}-\\frac{9 x}{\\sqrt{81-6 x}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3(81-6 x)-18 x}{2 \\sqrt{81-6 x}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{243-18 x-18 x}{2 \\sqrt{81-6 x}} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{243-36 x}{2 \\sqrt{81-6 x}} \\end{aligned} $$Letting \\(\\frac{d A}{d x}=0\\) and solving for \\(x\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{243-36 x}{2 \\sqrt{81-6 x}}=0 \\\\ &amp; 234-36 x=0 \\\\ &amp; 36 x=234 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x=6.5 \\end{aligned} $$ Testing if this is a maximum point by sign table:</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:706/146;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a6dd217cc0fbfa44d27ef42b8708030d.jpeg\" width=\"706\" height=\"146\"></figure><p>\\(\\therefore\\) Maximum Point at \\(x=6.5\\)&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, area is maximum when \\(x=6.5 \\mathrm{~m}\\)</p>','2024-01-25 04:23:49',0,1,6,600,'medium','subtopic'),(405,6,93,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>A light is to be placed over the centre of a circle, radius \\(a\\) units. The intensity, \\(I\\), of the light is proportional to the sine of the angle, \\(\\alpha\\), at which the rays strike the circumference of the circle, divided by the square of the distance, \\(d\\), from the light to the circumference of the circle; i.e. \\(I=\\frac{k \\sin \\alpha}{d^2}\\), where \\(k\\) is a constant.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:104/200;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ba71910e1770b62792ce9d04c04bf627.png\" width=\"104\" height=\"200\"></figure><p>i.&nbsp; Show that \\(I=\\frac{k y}{\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^{\\frac{3}{2}}}\\)</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the best height for the light to be placed over the centre of the circle so as to provide the maximum illumination to the circumference</p><p>[3 marks]</p>','<p>i.<br>$$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; I=\\frac{k \\sin \\alpha}{d^2} \\\\ &amp; \\sin \\alpha=\\frac{y}{d} \\\\ &amp; d^2=y^2+a^2 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore I=\\frac{k\\left(\\frac{y}{d}\\right)}{y^2+a^2} \\\\ &amp;= \\frac{k y}{d\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp;= \\frac{k y}{\\sqrt{y^2+a^2}\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp;= \\frac{k y}{\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^{\\frac{3}{2}}} \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii.<br>$$ I=\\frac{k^2 y^2}{\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^3} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d I}{d y} &amp; =\\frac{\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^3 \\cdot 2 k^2 y-k^2 y^2 \\cdot 3\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^2 \\cdot 2 y}{\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2 k^2 y\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^3-6 k^2 y^3\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^2}{\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2 k^2 y\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^2\\left[\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)-3 y^2\\right]}{\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^6} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2 k^2 y\\left(a^2-2 y^2\\right)}{\\left(y^2+a^2\\right)^4} \\end{aligned} $$ Let \\(\\frac{d I}{d y}=0\\) $$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore 2 k^2 y\\left(a^2-2 y^2\\right)=0 \\\\ \\therefore y=0, \\pm \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{2}} \\\\ \\left.\\therefore y=0, \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{2}} \\text { (as } y \\geq 0\\right) \\end{gathered} $$ But \\(y=0\\) provides no illumination to the circumference. $$ \\therefore y=\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{2}} $$</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:271/128;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/7562903f457583dac953654acaca9702.png\" width=\"271\" height=\"128\"></figure><p>\\(\\therefore y=\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{2}}\\) provides the maximum illumination to the circumference.</p>','2024-01-25 04:24:14',0,1,5,540,'medium','subtopic'),(406,6,93,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>A piece of string of length \\(10 \\mathrm{~m}\\) is cut into \\(2\\) pieces, one piece forming a square with sides \\(x m\\) in length and the other piece forms a circle.</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:24.81%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:616/581;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/0e233ef8e64e11b32bbc129128926ca9.png\" width=\"616\" height=\"581\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Show that the radius of the circle in terms of \\(x\\) is given by \\(r=\\frac{5-2 x}{\\pi}\\)</p><p>[1 mark]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Hence, find the lengths of the two pieces of string which obtain the minimum total area, giving your answer in exact values</p><p>[4 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. The perimeter of the square is given as \\(4 x\\).</strong> Hence, the amount of string used for the circle will be: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\text { Circumference }=10-4 x \\\\ \\therefore 2 \\pi r=10-4 x \\\\ r=\\frac{10-4 x}{2 \\pi} \\\\ r=\\frac{5-2 x}{\\pi} \\end{gathered} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. To find the minimum area, we need to first find the area expression:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Total Area } &amp; =\\text { Circle }+\\text { Square } \\\\ &amp; =\\pi r^2+x^2 \\\\ &amp; =\\pi\\left(\\frac{5-2 x}{\\pi}\\right)^2+x^2 \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{(5-2 x)^2}{\\pi}+x^2 \\end{aligned} $$ To find stationary point first differentiate: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\frac{d A}{d x} &amp; =\\frac{-2 \\times 2(5-2 x)}{\\pi}+2 x\\ [\\text {Chain Rule}] \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{-4(5-2 x)}{\\pi}+\\frac{2 x \\pi}{\\pi} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{-20+8 x+2 x \\pi}{\\pi} \\end{aligned} $$ Letting \\(y^{\\prime}=0\\) and solve for \\(x\\) for stationary points: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{d A}{d x}=\\frac{-20+8 x+2 x \\pi}{\\pi}=0 \\\\ &amp; -20+8 x+2 x \\pi=0 \\\\ &amp; x(8+2 \\pi)=20 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore x=\\frac{20}{8+2 \\pi}=\\frac{10}{4+\\pi} \\end{aligned} $$ Double differentiating to determine its nature: $$ \\frac{d^2 A}{d x^2}=\\frac{8+2 \\pi}{\\pi}&gt;0 $$Since \\(\\frac{d^2 A}{d x^2}\\) is always \\(&gt;0\\), this means that \\(\\frac{d A}{d x}\\) is always increasing. Hence, the minimum area will occur when \\(x=\\frac{10}{4+\\pi}\\)&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Length required for square is: $$ 4 x=\\frac{40}{4+\\pi} m $$ Length required for circle therefore is:</strong></p><p>$$ 10-\\frac{40}{4+\\pi} m $$ <strong>Finding the coordinates of stationary points:&nbsp;</strong><br><br>When \\(x=0, y=3(0)^4-2(0)^3+4=4[0,4]\\)&nbsp;<br><br>When \\(x=\\frac{1}{2}, y=3\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^4-2\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^3+4=\\frac{63}{16}\\left[\\frac{1}{2}, \\frac{63}{16}\\right]\\)&nbsp;<br><br>Next, considering the second derivative to find their nature: $$ \\begin{aligned} y^{\\prime \\prime} &amp; =12 \\times 3 x^2-6 \\times 2 x \\\\ &amp; =36 x^2-12 x \\end{aligned} $$ When \\(x=0, y^{\\prime \\prime}=36(0)^2-12(0)=0\\)<br><br>Since \\(y^{\\prime \\prime}=0\\), this means that stationary point \\((0,4)\\) is a horizontal point of inflection&nbsp;</p><p>When \\(x=\\frac{1}{2}, y^{\\prime \\prime}=36\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^2-12\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)=3\\)&nbsp;</p><p>Since \\(y^{\\prime \\prime}&gt;0\\), this means that stationary point \\(\\left(\\frac{1}{2}, \\frac{63}{16}\\right)\\) is a minimum turning point</p>','2024-01-25 04:24:14',0,1,5,540,'medium','subtopic'),(407,6,93,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [5 marks total]</u></p><p>A cylindrical waste tank can hold a volume of \\(6 \\mathrm{~m}^3\\), as shown in the diagram below:</p><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:28.64%;\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:605/614;\" src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/6264a9865071159f49d25e22b43a2273.png\" width=\"605\" height=\"614\"></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>i. Show that the surface area is given by \\(S=2 \\pi r^2+\\frac{12}{r}\\) metres squares</p><p>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Find the radius that would give the smallest possible surface area of the waste tank</p><p>[3 marks]</p>','<p><strong>i. The surface area of a cylinder is given as:</strong> $$ A=\\text { circular top }+\\text { circular base }+\\text { curved rectangle } $$ For the rectangle, its area is equivalent to circumference \\(\\times\\) height, hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} A &amp; =\\pi r^2+\\pi r^2+2 \\pi r h \\\\ &amp; =2 \\pi r^2+2 \\pi r h \\end{aligned} $$ To find an expression for \\(h\\) in terms of \\(r\\), consider the volume of the cylinder: $$ \\begin{gathered} V=\\pi r^2 h=6 \\\\ \\therefore h=\\frac{6}{\\pi r^2} \\end{gathered} $$ Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} A &amp; =2 \\pi r^2+2 \\pi r \\times \\frac{6}{\\pi r^2} \\\\ &amp; =2 \\pi r^2+\\frac{12}{r} \\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>ii. To find the minimum area, first differentiate \\(A\\) from part i)</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} A= &amp; 2 \\pi r^2+12 r^{-1} \\\\ \\frac{d A}{d r} &amp; =4 \\pi r-\\frac{12}{r^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{4 \\pi r^3-12}{r^2} \\end{aligned} $$ Letting \\(\\frac{d A}{d r}=0\\) and solve for \\(r\\) for stationary points: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{d A}{d r}=\\frac{4 \\pi r^3-12}{r^2}=0 \\\\ &amp; 4 \\pi r^3-12=0 \\\\ &amp; r^3=\\frac{12}{4 \\pi}=\\frac{3}{\\pi} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore r=\\sqrt[3]{\\frac{3}{\\pi}} \\end{aligned} $$ Double differentiating A to determine the nature of this turning point: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{d A}{d r}=4 \\pi r-\\frac{12}{r^2} \\\\ &amp; \\frac{d^2 A}{d r^2}=4 \\pi+\\frac{24}{r^3} \\end{aligned} $$Therefore, since \\(\\frac{d^2 A}{d r^2}&gt;0\\) always when \\(r&gt;0\\), then therefore \\(r=\\sqrt[3]{\\frac{3}{\\pi}}\\) is a minimum point and is when the minimum area occurs</p>','2024-01-25 04:24:14',0,1,5,540,'medium','subtopic'),(408,6,94,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the primitive of \\(f(x)=x^2\\)?</p>','<p><strong>Recall that the primitive of \\(x^n\\) is \\(\\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}\\)&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Hence, letting \\(F(x)\\) be the primitive of \\(f(x)\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} F(x) &amp; =\\frac{x^{2+1}}{2+1}+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^3}{3}+C \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-25 23:11:27',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(409,6,94,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following is the primitive of \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=-x^3\\)?</p>','<p>Recall that the primitive of \\(x^n\\) is \\(\\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}\\)&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, letting \\(f(x)\\) be the primitive of \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} f(x) &amp; =-\\frac{x^{3+1}}{3+1}+C \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{x^4}{4}+C \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-25 23:11:27',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(410,6,94,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given that the primitive of \\(f(x)=2 x^5\\) is \\(a x^6+C\\), where \\(a\\) is a constant, then the value of \\(a\\) is:</p>','<p>First, finding the primitive of \\(2 x^5\\) by recalling: $$ x^n=\\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} $$ The primitive of \\(f(x)=2 x^5\\) will be: $$ \\begin{aligned} F(x) &amp; =2 \\times \\frac{x^{5+1}}{5+1}+C \\\\ &amp; =2 \\times \\frac{x^6}{6}+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3} x^6+C \\\\ &amp; \\therefore a=\\frac{1}{3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-25 23:11:27',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(411,6,94,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given that \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=(x-2)\\left(\\frac{x}{2}+3\\right)\\), then which of the following will be its primitive, \\(f(x)\\)?</p>','<p>First we must expand our brackets before finding the primitive: $$ \\begin{aligned} f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\frac{x^2}{2}+3 x-x-6 \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^2}{2}+2 x-6 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, recalling that the primitive of \\(x^n=\\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}\\) and that we can split up a function: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore f(x) &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^{2+1}}{2+1}+2 \\times \\frac{x^{1+1}}{1+1}-6 x+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^3}{3}+2 \\times \\frac{x^2}{2}-6 x+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^3}{6}+x^2-6 x+C \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-25 23:11:27',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(412,6,94,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [3 marks total]</u></p><p>i. Differentiate \\(\\ln (\\sin x)\\)<br>[2 marks]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Hence, find the primitive of \\(\\cot x\\)&nbsp;<br>[1 mark]</p>','<p>i. Since \\((\\ln u)^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{u}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned}(\\ln (\\sin x))^{\\prime} &amp; =(\\sin x)^{\\prime} \\times \\frac{1}{\\sin x}[\\text { Chain rule] } \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{\\cos x}{\\sin x} \\\\ &amp; =\\cot x\\end{aligned} $$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>ii. Since the derivative of \\(\\ln (\\sin x)\\) is \\(\\cot x\\), by the anti-derivative, the primitive of \\(\\cot x\\) will therefore be: $$ \\ln (\\sin x)+C $$ [Note: we must include the&nbsp;\\(+C\\) in our answer]</p>','2024-01-25 23:11:53',0,1,3,300,'medium','subtopic'),(413,6,95,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Which of the following correctly represents the result of \\(\\int x^2+x-2 d x\\)?</p>','<p>Evaluating the indefinite integral by using the formula \\(\\int x^n d x=\\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+C\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\int x^2+x-2 d x &amp; =\\frac{x^{2+1}}{2+1}+\\frac{x^{1+1}}{1+1}-2 x+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^3}{3}+\\frac{x^2}{2}-2 x+C \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-25 23:32:00',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(414,6,95,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given that \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=8 x-5\\) and \\(f(1)=4\\), what is the equation of \\(f(x)\\)?</p>','<p><strong>Since \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=8 x-5\\), evaluating the indefinite integral by using the formula \\(\\int x^n d x=\\) \\(\\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+C\\) </strong>$$ \\begin{aligned} f(x) &amp; =\\int 8 x-5 d x \\\\ &amp; =8 \\cdot \\frac{x^2}{2}-5 x+C \\\\ &amp; =4 x^2-5 x+C \\end{aligned} $$ When \\(x=1, f(1)=4\\). Therefore:$$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; f(1)=4=4(1)^2-5(1)+C \\\\ &amp; 4=4-5+C \\\\ &amp; 4=-1+C \\\\ &amp; \\therefore C=5 \\end{gathered} $$ Hence, the equation is \\(f(x)=4 x^2-5 x+5\\)</p>','2024-01-25 23:32:00',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(415,6,95,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Find \\(\\int \\frac{2 x^4+4 x^2+1}{x^2} d x\\)</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>First splitting the numerator: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\int \\frac{2 x^4+4 x^2+1}{x^2} d x &amp; =\\int 2 x^2+4+\\frac{1}{x^2} d x \\\\ &amp; =\\int 2 x^2+4+x^{-2} d x \\end{aligned} $$ Then integrating: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\int 2 x^2+4+x^{-2} d x &amp; =\\frac{2 x^3}{3}+4 x+\\frac{x^{-2+1}}{-2+1}+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2 x^3}{3}+4 x-x^{-1}+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2 x^3}{3}+4 x-\\frac{1}{x}+C \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-25 23:32:42',0,1,2,240,'medium','subtopic'),(416,6,95,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>The gradient function of a curve is \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=6 x+4\\). The curve is known to pass through the point \\((-1,5)\\). Find \\(f(x)\\)</p>','<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br>Integrating \\(f^{\\prime}(x)\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} y=\\int 6 x+4 d x &amp; =6 \\cdot \\frac{x^2}{2}+4 x+C \\\\ &amp; =3 x^2+4 x+C \\end{aligned} $$ When \\(x=-1, y=5\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 5=3(-1)^2+4(-1)+C \\\\ &amp; 5=3-4+C \\\\ &amp; 5=-1+C \\\\ &amp; \\therefore C=6 \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-25 23:32:42',0,1,2,240,'medium','subtopic'),(417,6,95,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Short Answer [2 marks]</u></p><p>Given that \\(f(x)=\\left(1-x^{\\frac{2}{3}}+x\\right) \\sqrt{x}\\), find its primitive function \\(F(x)\\)</p>','<p><strong>Since \\(F(x)\\) is the primitive function of \\(f(x)\\):</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} F(x) &amp; =\\int\\left(1-x^{\\frac{2}{3}}+x\\right) \\sqrt{x} d x \\\\ &amp; =\\int\\left(1-x^{\\frac{2}{3}}+x\\right) x^{\\frac{1}{2}} d x \\end{aligned} $$ Then, expanding brackets: $$ F(x)=\\int x^{\\frac{1}{2}}-x^{\\frac{2}{3}} \\cdot x^{\\frac{1}{2}}+x \\cdot x^{\\frac{1}{2}} $$ Simplifying the indices: $$ \\begin{aligned} F(x) &amp; =\\int\\left(x^{\\frac{1}{2}}-x^{\\frac{2}{3}+\\frac{1}{2}}+x^{1+\\frac{1}{2}}\\right) d x \\\\ &amp; =\\int\\left(x^{\\frac{1}{2}}-x^{\\frac{7}{6}}+x^{\\frac{3}{2}}\\right) d x \\end{aligned} $$<strong>Then finally&nbsp;integrating:</strong> $$ \\begin{aligned} F(x) &amp; =\\int x^{\\frac{1}{2}} d x-\\int x^{\\frac{7}{6}} d x+\\int x^{\\frac{3}{2}} d x \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^{\\frac{1}{2}+1}}{\\frac{1}{2}+1}-\\frac{x^{\\frac{7}{6}+1}}{\\frac{7}{6}+1}+\\frac{x^{\\frac{3}{2}+1}}{\\frac{3}{2}+1}+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^{\\frac{3}{2}}}{\\frac{3}{2}}-\\frac{x^{\\frac{13}{6}}}{\\frac{13}{6}}+\\frac{x^{\\frac{5}{2}}}{\\frac{5}{2}}+C \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{2}{3} x^{\\frac{3}{2}}-\\frac{6}{13} x^{\\frac{13}{6}}+\\frac{2}{5} x^{\\frac{5}{2}}+C \\end{aligned} $$</p>','2024-01-25 23:32:42',0,1,2,240,'medium','subtopic'),(418,6,96,'mcq',NULL,'<p><u>Multiple Choice</u></p><p>Given that \\(f^{\\prime}(x)=(x+3)^9\\), then which of the following expressions will represent \\(f(x)\\)?</p>','<p>Recalling the reverse chain rule: $$ \\begin{gathered} &amp; \\int(a x+b)^n d x=\\frac{1}{a} \\cdot \\frac{(a x+b)^{n+1}}{n+1}+C \\\\ &amp; \\therefore f(x)=\\int(x+3)^9 d x=\\frac{1}{1} \\cdot \\frac{(x+3)^{10}}{9+1}+C \\\\ &amp;&nbsp; &nbsp;=\\frac{(x+3)^{10}}{10}+C \\\\ &amp; \\end{gathered} $$</p>','2024-01-26 00:03:51',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(419,6,96,'mcq',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2024-01-26 00:03:51',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(420,6,96,'mcq',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2024-01-26 00:03:51',0,1,1,120,'medium','subtopic'),(421,6,96,'mcq',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2024-01-26 00:04:09',0,1,2,240,'medium','subtopic'),(422,6,96,'mcq',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2024-01-26 00:04:09',0,1,2,240,'medium','subtopic');
